<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Which of our current drama series does it seem likely broadcasters will want
to repeat in the year 2024? The question is prompted by today's repeat of
The Twilight Zone, a series of splendid fantasy and science fiction stories
which began transmission in the US in 1959. Today's episode, 'The Chaser',
was first broadcast in today's form in May 1960, though it was previously
performed live in 'The Billy Rose Television Theatre' in 1951. Roger is
madly in love with Leila, but she scarcely notices he exists. So he buys a
love potion which is only too astonishingly effective.
This is not one of the best episodes, but the whole series stands up
remarkably well. Unhappily Channel 4 will not be screening it until 1.35 in
the morning; a job for the VCR perhaps. Earlier the same channel begins a
new quiz which sounds as though it might make up for the loss of 'My Music':
The Music Game (8.30). Tony Slattery is in the chair but the panel does not
look as though it was chosen solely for musical expertise. Happily the best
impressionist of his generation makes a welcome return to BBC2 in a new
series: Rory Bremner (9.00).
</TEXT>
