<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Arts: Joan of Arc at the Stake - Brighton Festival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD CRICHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Honegger's dramatic oratorio Joan of Arc at the Stake was the idea of Ida
Rubinstein, the mime, dancer and actress. She wanted Claudel to write the
poem. His reaction was 'Another Joan of Arc? No, I won't'. But she received
the text shortly afterwards. Honegger set to work, apparently greatly
stimulated. Rubinstein intended Joan as part of a double bill with the
scenic cantata La Sagesse, commissioned by her from Milhaud, and to perform
them at the Paris Opera. That institution, as so often, had cold feet. So
Joan was first done in concert form, with Rubinstein, in German, at Basle in
1938. La Sagesse was not given until after the war. Since the centenaries of
both Honegger and Milhaud fall this year a performance, at last, of the
double bill would have been a bright feather in Brighton's cap.
Or perhaps not. Generous rehearsal time would be needed and there did not
appear to have been enough of that for Sunday's concert performance of Joan
in the Dome. The BBC Symphony Orchestra came to join the Festival Chorus.
Since large forces are needed and the Dome platform is circumscribed, the
chorus was split in two and placed at the opposite ends of the balcony. I
was near the half with the men and the Christ's Hospital Junior Girls' Choir
(very good).
It cannot have been easy for the conductor David Robertson to keep the two
halves together. Maybe for those sitting dead centre (and for listeners to
Radio 3) things may have sounded better. It was not only the choral ensemble
that was rough. The picturesque touches with which Claudel larded his text
made slight impact. For much of the time the orchestra leathered away
between mezzoforte and fortissimo without light or shade.
There was a half-hearted attempt at semi-staging. A Cross was placed behind
the trombones and fitfully illuminated. The women soloists were dressed in
bright colours. Joan, barefoot, wore a simple dark dress. Fiona Shaw,
Brighton's successor to Ida Rubinstein, Vera Zorina, Ingrid Bergman and
other stars, has striking features almost as Gothic as Edith Sitwell and a
voice admirable for conveying suffering and hope, capable of holding its own
with the BBC SO. Miss Shaw remained obediently at the conductor's side but
looked as if she wanted to roam. Hence perhaps signs of physical tension.
Among the small parts tenor Neil Jenkins as Porcus and actor John Woodvine
as Brother Dominic stood out. In general Mr Robertson showed too little
regard for his soloists.
Joan of Arc at the Stake continues to win a popular success only rivalled
among works of this hybrid form by Orff's Carmina burana. It was given in
Dennis Arundell's English translation in which one is not too conscious of
that kind of French rhetoric which implies that if you intone names like
France, Burgundy, Rheims or Domremy often enough you have made a statement.
Many find the emotional impact strong: for others what remains is little
more than hot air and stale incense. Honegger was an able, attractive
composer. The tapestry is skilfully woven: the build-up of the last scene
and ending is impressive. Yet the final impression is of musical footnotes.
Sponsored by British Gas
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
