<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Essex man reflects anti-Labour mood - Council Elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR lost ground across southern England last night, surrendering seats to
the Conservatives and the Liberal Democrats.
Essex man delivered the most spectacular rebuff to Labour: the Tories won
all 15 seats up for grabs in Basildon (one third of the council), and took
control. Large swings also occurred in Milton Keynes, Welwyn Hatfield and
Brighton, where Labour lost eight seats to the Tories but narrowly held
control. Labour also lost control of Cambridge, where it won the Commons
seat in the general election.
Mr Bryan Gould, MP for Dagenham and a Labour leadership candidate, put a
brave face on the party's poor showing, blaming 'voter fatigue',
particularly among Labour supporters. No elections were held in London
yesterday, but a BBC projection of the results across the whole region put
Labour third behind the Liberal Democrats in share of the vote  - with only
21 per cent.
However, Labour retained control of far more councils than the Liberal
Democrats, and held areas such as Crawley, Harlow, Reading, Slough and
Watford, all of which returned Tories in the general election last month.
Liberal Democrats took comfort from gains in Bath, Portsmouth and Eastbourne
 - which they lost in the general election. The Tories went some way to
healing one self-inflicted wound by defeating rebel Tories in West
Oxfordshire whose defection two years ago presaged the downfall of the poll
tax  - and, indeed, its authoress.
Earlier in the day, the Tories hailed the defection of a Labour councillor
in Berkshire, saying it had been the second such defection since last
month's general election.
Mr Cliff Rayner, formerly a Labour member of Berkshire county council,
joined the Conservative group, giving it exactly half the 76 county council
seats, and increasing the prospect that the party can win back the council.
Labour's attempts in Liverpool to shake off its problems with Militant
backfired as its vote was split and the Liberal Democrats made 10 gains out
of 34 seats contested, Ian Hamilton Fazey writes.
The Broad Left, fielding 22 candidates against official Labour ones, won
only one seat. The Liberal Democrats, who were defending eight seats, ended
the night with 18.
Labour remains the largest party on the council but the numbers of seats are
finely balanced. Labour has 40 seats, Liberal Democrats 37 and the Broad
Left 18.
</TEXT>
