<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Dewhurst butchers chain faces shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEWHURST, which runs the UK's biggest chain of butchers shops, will today
disclose details of a substantial rationalisation of its 1,006 shops.
Nevertheless the company, part of the privately owned Vestey business
empire, yesterday refused to comment on the widespread reports that it
planned to close up to 600 shops with the loss of 1,000 jobs.
The company said it first had to inform its 4,234 staff of its decisions at
regional meetings. There was disquiet, though, about possible closures at
Dewhurst outlets yesterday.
Dewhurst's plight may partly reflect the financial strains of the Vestey
parent company, which was recently forced to make substantial provisions on
its property portfolio.
It also highlights the intense pressure that traditional butchers have
experienced as a result of changing shopping habits and the growth of
supermarket chains.
According to estimates from Verdict, the retail research company, the big
grocery chains now account for more than half of all carcase meat sold in
the UK and about 92 per cent of bacon, ham, poultry and other meat products.
Mr Richard Hyman, Verdict's director, said: 'I do not think it is too
fanciful to suggest that this is at least partly due to the changing nature
of society.
'Mothers do not pass on knowledge about cuts of meat to their children. It
is pretty innocuous to go into a supermarket and choose a recognisable chunk
of meat, whereas in a serviced butcher's shop you have to know what you are
asking for.'
Mr John Fuller of the National Federation of Meat Traders, which represents
independent butchers, said butchers were trying to raise knowledge through
educational programmes at schools.
He added that, although butchers had undoubtedly suffered from supermarket
competition, there were grounds for believing that smaller, family-owned
butchers were experiencing a comeback, partly at the expense of the bigger
chains  - such as Dewhurst.
'Elements like the weather do have an impact on whether people buy stewing
steak or barbecue meats,' he said. 'The private butcher is an entrepreneur
and can respond a lot more quickly than the larger managed groups.'
Nevertheless, the latest government figures showed that the number of
registered butchers firms fell by 540 to 13,641 in the year ending April
1991. Thirty years ago there were more than 33,000 butchers shops on
Britain's high streets.
</TEXT>
