<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Heseltine order on drugs deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AAH HOLDINGS, the UK pharmaceuticals wholesaler, is to be asked to divest
part of its acquisition of the UK business of Medicopharma NV, the Dutch
pharmaceuticals wholesaler, on the ground that competition has been stifled.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, yesterday instructed Sir
Gordon Borrie, director-general of fair trading, to seek appropriate
divestment undertakings from AAH after a Monopolies and Mergers Commission
report that concluded that the merger was likely to operate against the
public interest.
The commission found that the acquisition made by AAH in November last year
led to a reduction in competition in the Grampian and Highland regions of
Scotland that was significantly greater than would have occurred if
Medicopharma's UK subsidiaries had been placed in receivership.
The commission did not consider that competition would be significantly
affected at national level or in areas served by the other two depots of
Medicopharma UK acquired by AAH  - at Weedon, Northamptonshire, and Romford,
Essex  - or in the supply to hospitals, where AAH is by far the largest
wholesaler.
The commission recommended that AAH should be required to divest a business
approximating as closely as possible to the business carried on by
Medicopharma UK from its Aberdeen depot immediately before the acquisition.
AAH and UniChem are the two largest UK wholesalers of pharmaceutical
products, accounting for slightly more than 60 per cent of sales in 1990.
AAH had 30 per cent of the market, valued at Pounds 2.84bn. Medicopharma UK
was the third-largest wholesaler in 1990, accounting for 8 per cent of the
market.
AAH accounted for more than 70 per cent of sales of ethical drugs to
hospitals by wholesalers in 1990 and about 33 per cent of total sales to
hospitals, including direct sales. Medicopharma UK accounted for about 3 per
cent of sales of ethicals to hospitals in 1990.
Medicopharma entered the UK wholesale market in 1990 through the acquisition
of two existing wholesalers, Butler, and the wholesale business of Macarthy.
AAH said yesterday it was disappointed that the acquisition had been
referred to the MMC but welcomed the commission's finding that there was no
material effect on competition at a national level or in most of the UK.
Mr Andrew Wallis, finance director, said the inquiry had delayed the
integration of the Romford and Weedon warehouses into AAH's distribution
network, but that could now proceed.
AAH foresaw no difficulty in complying with the commission's recommendation
in respect of the Aberdeen warehouse, Mr Wallis added.
Mr Heseltine is making an order under the 1973 Fair Trading Act as a
protective measure to guard against AAH's taking any action intended to
frustrate the divestment.
</TEXT>
