<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Campaign for safer roof work launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HEALTH and Safety Executive warned the construction industry yesterday
that it was mounting a safety drive on construction involving roof work,
Diane Summers writes.
Inspectors will order building sites to halt work and will take legal action
in serious cases where safety rules are being breached, the HSE said.
Dr Paul Davis, head of the HSE's construction group, said at the launch of
its campaign: 'Cowboy roofers, like their namesakes . . . often die young.'
Almost every roof work death could be prevented by simple precautions and
the use of proper equipment.
Roofers' deaths in building accidents make them the largest single
occupational group for fatalities. Construction itself is the most dangerous
of all industry sectors. Most roof work is done by about 7,000 contractors
who provide work for 30,000 roofers. The sector is difficult to regulate
because three quarters of the workers are self-employed and working for
companies of three people or fewer.
