<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Funds told to be tougher against fraud: Call from Bank to
pensions industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PENSION FUNDS must take a more active stand to prevent further Maxwell-style
frauds, a Bank of England official told the annual conference of the
National Association of Pension Funds in Glasgow.
Mr Pen Kent, Bank of England director for finance and industry, said the
association's members 'are not standing up to be counted'. Shareholders too
often failed to exercise their right to vote and bore some responsibility
for failing to insist on proper curbs on Robert Maxwell.
Shareholders had not contributed enough to the debate over what companies
should disclose in their corporate accounts, he added. 'We need to hear more
from users of accounts about what is currently provided.'
Mr Kent said that although there is 'no such thing as a risk-free society',
there is a need to tighten regulation of the investment industry.
Mr Brian McMahon, association chairman, outlined its support for pension
reform. 'The days are gone, indeed if they ever existed, when this
association could say that everything is fine, nothing wrong with the way we
run our schemes, and especially nothing wrong with the way I run mine,' Mr
McMahon said. 'Maxwell has cast a giant shadow over us.'
The association is studying a compensation arrangement for pension scheme
members similar to that available to private investors. Other reforms backed
by the association include requiring boards of trustees to offer equal
representation to employers and members. The association also says pension
schemes should be required to pay for trustees to obtain training.
</TEXT>
