FT  08 MAY 92 / New ferry is largest in Channel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITTANY Ferries, the French cross-Channel ferry operator, has taken
possession of the largest vessel yet to ply between the UK and France - the
Normandie, weighing in at 27,000 gross tonnes (above), Richard Tomkins
writes.
The Pounds 80m vessel, which will make its maiden voyage on the
Portsmouth-Caen route on May 18, can carry a total of 2,200 passengers and
630 cars.
Built by the Kvaerner Masa shipbuilding company at its Turku yard in
Finland, the ferry incorporates restaurants, bars, a children's playroom,
two cinemas and a fully equipped hospital.
The vessel forms part of a Pounds 350m investment programme being undertaken
by Brittany Ferries on its fast-growing western Channel routes, which are
less vulnerable to the threat of the Channel tunnel than the shorter routes
to the east.
Last month the company took possession of the 20,500 grt Barfleur, which has
just gone into service between Poole and Cherbourg.
This will shortly be followed by the introduction of the 31,400 grt Nils
Holgersson  - one of the world's 20 largest ferries  - to the routes between
Plymouth and Roscoff in Brittany and Plymouth to Santander in Spain.
</TEXT>
