FT  08 MAY 92 / Move to cut audits attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS to abolish the statutory audit requirement for small companies should
be strongly resisted, the outgoing president of the Chartered Association of
Certified Accountants said yesterday.
Mr Ken Anderson attacked both the idea and its supporters at the
association's annual meeting in London.
The Department of Trade and Industry is considering abolishing the mandatory
audit requirement for very small companies. Under the proposals,
requirements could be eased for all companies below the Pounds 36,600 value
added tax threshold.
Mr Anderson accused the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and
Wales  - which has supported the idea  - of 'orchestrating' a campaign for
abolition. 'In the current climate, with the audit side of the profession
under such focus . . . it is surely not the time to seek to reduce the role
of the audit,' he said.
He argued that limited liability status imposed responsibilities on
companies.
