<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / MPs to meet SIB chief over Lloyd's inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S OF London will come under political pressure again next week when a
party of MPs visits Sir David Walker, chairman of the Securities and
Investments Board, to discuss his inquiry into alleged malpractices.
The authorities at the insurance market faced intense scrutiny earlier this
year when MPs said Names working in the market were benefiting at the
expense of Names outside. Names are the individuals whose assets support
underwriting.
The MPs will seek assurances that Sir David is gaining access to all the
information he needs for his inquiries. The party is expected to include Mr
Paul Marland, the Conservative MP for Gloucestershire West, who is also a
Lloyd's Name.
The credibility of the inquiry is critical to Lloyd's as it seeks to rebuild
confidence in the face of its difficulties. Losses in 1989 are expected to
amount to more than Pounds 1.35bn, with some recent estimates putting the
figure as high as Pounds 2bn.
At the time of Sir David's appointment in February, Mr David Coleridge,
chairman of Lloyd's, commented: 'I needed a man who was so white that
snow-white looked dirty.'
Mr Marland is also expected to be at the forefront of calls for a fully
fledged Commons debate on Lloyd's. He is understood to have written to Mr
Neil Hamilton, a junior trade and industry minister, to request a meeting
with him and other interested parties.
In a separate development, Lloyd's has received a legal opinion from Mr
Jonathan Sumption QC that it can admit corporate members without any
alteration of the Lloyd's Act, which provides for the market's
self-regulation.
The opinion potentially clears the way for more rapid implementation of the
proposals made by the Rowland report in January to bring corporate capital
to the market.
It had been assumed that changes in the act would be needed. However,
Lloyd's will still need to talk to various regulatory bodies, including the
US Securities and Exchange Commission, about the reforms.
Potential investors may be encouraged by the findings of Mr Chris Hitchings,
an insurance analyst with Hoare Govett, the securities house.
Lloyd's has consistently outperformed both UK composite insurers and US
insurers in terms of both its profit margins and the strength of its
solvency margins, says Mr Hitchings in a report that analyses financial data
from Lloyd's and the UK and US insurance industries on a like-for-like
basis.
Between 1950 and 1989, Lloyd's reported average annual profits (as a
percentage of net written premiums) of 6 per cent, compared with 3.9 per
cent for UK companies and 2.9 per cent for US insurers.
Lloyd's losses for 1989  - which the market reports next month  - are likely
to be much worse than those experienced by the UK companies, partly because
of its heavy exposure to natural catastrophes.
However, had UK companies accounted on the same basis as Lloyd's, their
results for 1989 would have been worse, says Mr Hitchings in his report.
Many of the companies' 1990 and 1991 losses occurred because of the need to
make provisions for claims made on policies underwritten in earlier years.
</TEXT>
