<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Acas reports slow growth in derecognition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DERECOGNITION of unions, especially for supervisory, technical and
professional jobs, is being considered by a 'slowly growing number of
employers', according to the annual report of Acas, the conciliation
service.
Nevertheless, the report also points to a greater readiness on the part of
individuals and unions to use the law against employers by taking unfair
dismissal and discrimination cases to industrial tribunals.
Acas, which has a statutory duty to conciliate between employee and employer
before a case goes to a tribunal, saw a large increase in its workload in
individual and collective cases last year. In the first quarter of this
year, individual conciliation cases have increased by 40 per cent over the
same period last year.
Of the 60,605 individual conciliation cases last year, a 16 per cent rise
over 1990, only 32 per cent went to tribunals.
Sex discrimination cases rose by 119 per cent to 3,500. That was because of
a wave of cases influenced by the European Court's Barber judgment, which
extended the definition of equal pay to include pensions.
Sir Douglas Smith, Acas chairman, also pointed to cultural changes that had
led to a greater readiness by women to go to court. Unions, too, had changed
their attitudes and 'are much more ready to ensure that members are aware of
their statutory rights'.
Although that is a sign of unions having less leverage through collective
bargaining on matters such as election for redundancy, Sir Douglas said he
did not believe unions were terminally weakened. He said national union
leaders were more pragmatic than they used to be, but union strength often
remained considerable at local level.
Sir Douglas said he did not believe that employers wanted to scrap the
Bridlington rules, through which the Trades Union Congress regulates
disputes between unions.
He also expects much more work involving the public sector  - hitherto four
fifths of Acas's work has been in the private sector  - as new, more
devolved industrial relations are introduced into many public services.
The Acas report said it had already intervened in National Health Service
trusts where 'there often remains a lack of expertise and experience (in
industrial relations) among local managers and trade union reps alike'.
The report also warns public-sector managers not to embrace uncritically
performance-related pay at a time when the private sector's experience is
becoming 'more mixed' and some employers are re-examining the advantages and
disadvantages.
Report 1991. Acas Reader, PO Box 797, London SE8 4JX. Pounds 1
</TEXT>
