FT  08 MAY 92 / Mercury increases pay bill by 5.7%
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MERCURY Communications has increased its salary bill by 5.7 per cent,
putting pay rises at the telecommunications group at the top end of current
awards, Hugo Dixon and David Goodhart write.
Mercury, BT's main rival in the telecommunications market, has also improved
benefits, including paternity leave and a helpline for staff.
Individual rises will vary because Mercury operates a performance-related
pay scheme. The scheme takes account of market rates and the company's
financial position as well as the performance of individual employees.
Mercury, which does not recognise unions, prides itself on being at the
forefront of industry in setting pay and conditions.
The National Communications Union, the main BT union, claims that the
generosity of the deal is in part a response to its present recruiting
efforts.
Mr Alan Harley, NCU national organiser, said Mercury responded 'in a
friendly manner' before the general election. But since then 'it has stopped
replying to our letters'.
