<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Pigging out at the Cafe Royal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Cafe Royal in London became a pig pen yesterday. It was the venue for
the National Pig Development Company to show off its new Anglo-Chinese
hybrid, the Manor Meishan.
Lord Plumb, Conservative MEP for The Cotswolds and former president of the
National Farmers' Union, described the hybrid as a 'quantum leap in pig
breeding'. It combines the astonishing reproductive performance of the
Meishan  - each sow has 16 piglets a litter and produces two or three
litters a year  - with the lean meat characteristic of the British Large
White and Landrace breeds.
China sold 32 of its fat, wrinkly Meishan pigs in 1987 to a consortium of
British pig breeding companies for use in a research programme co-ordinated
by the Institute of Animal Physiology and Genetics Research in Edinburgh.
The Manor Meishan is the first commercial result. It looks smooth and sleek,
without the heavy folds of skin characteristic of its Chinese ancestors.
Like them, it has 16 teats  - and sometimes even 18  - to accommodate its
large litters (a typical European pig has 12).
National Pig Development, a private company based at Driffield, Humberside,
will supply Manor Meishans 'exclusively to the UK market for the foreseeable
future'. The company expects to deliver 2,000 pigs in the next year.
Lord Plumb welcomed the 'cost-cutting' hybrid as a development that would
help British farmers compete.
</TEXT>
