<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Climate treaty sets no emission limits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE UN, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A DRAFT treaty on climatic change, to be signed by world leaders next month,
would commit rich countries to fight global warming by restricting
greenhouse-gas pollution, but would stop well short of setting limits,
Reuter reports from the United Nations in New York.
According to a new text of the treaty, circulated yesterday, developed
countries would agree to limit emissions of gases such as carbon dioxide and
to protect 'sinks', such as forests, that absorb such emissions.
The text, or a slightly amended version of it, was expected to be handed to
UN negotiators today for approval by tomorrow. The treaty is to be a
centrepiece of the UN's Earth Summit at Rio de Janeiro next month.
By way of victory for the US, which has opposed the requirement of specific
emission targets, the draft treaty contains only loose goals. One section
recognises that reduction of emissions 'to earlier levels' by the end of the
decade would contribute to fighting climatic change; another says countries
should aim to return emissions to 1990 levels.
Critics charged the draft could allow signatories to comply whatever they
did. Mr Alden Meyer of the Union of Concerned Scientists said the UN
negotiations had produced 'a toothless global warming treaty, totally
inadequate to the threat posed by the continued build-up of greenhouse gases
in the atmosphere.'
The language of the text was vaguer than an earlier European Community
proposal to require stabilisation of carbon-dioxide emissions at 1990 levels
by 2000, and was a far cry from the sharp cuts environmental activists say
are necessary.
</TEXT>
