<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / German industry's resolve undiminished
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMAN industry's resolve to keep wage settlements low this year is unlikely
to be weakened by the terms of last night's public sector pay deal, judging
by comments from employers.
IG Metall, the engineering union, yesterday continued demonstrations aimed
at countering the employers' offer of 3.3 per cent and upholding its 9.5 per
cent demand.
Mr Klaus Murmann, head of the German employers' association, said the public
sector pay award should not be taken as a guideline for industry. High
private-sector settlements could increase unemployment and inflation.
He said that private industry would do its utmost to see that pay deals were
lower than in the public sector. He was speaking as last night's settlement
with the public sector union was becoming clear.
In recent weeks, employers have warned of the consequences of high wage
settlements at a time when the domestic boom, sparked by unification, is
slowing down, foreign markets have yet to recover fully from recession, and
competition is increasing from lower-cost countries.
In the car and components sector especially, companies have stressed the
need to cut costs and improve efficiency. Volkswagen, Mercedes-Benz, BMW,
and Opel (part of General Motors of the US) have all said they intend to
reduce their workforces in coming years, though avoiding redundancies where
possible.
Some companies have also been locating more investment overseas. 'Unions
don't consider the psychological impact on companies' investment thinking of
wage claims of around 10 per cent,' said Mr Heinz Schimmelbusch, head of
Metallgesellschaft, the mining, metal and engineering group.
Its car-parts subsidiary intends to raise output in Brazil and France to
help offset high domestic costs. Kugelfischer, a bearings company, has been
reducing staff to combat the effect of high costs at a time of slack
worldwide demand.
'What we need is a couple of years with no wage increases,' said Mr Wolfgang
Masuch, Kugelfischer's commercial director.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9247</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEHA7ADSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920508
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Competitiveness of exports bears up under pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMPETITIVENESS of Germany's exporters has been dented by rising wage
inflation since unification, but it will take a few more high pay
settlements before the gains of recent years are whittled away.
German unit labour costs  - the wage cost per unit of output produced - are
now rising faster than those of its main European competitors and, with
exchange rates fixed in the European exchange rate mechanism, this growth
feeds directly to lost export competitiveness. However, the rise in the unit
labour costs of German manufacturing industry since 1987 is still lower than
for manufacturers in France, Italy and the UK, as the right-hand chart
shows.
German wage earnings have grown faster than those in France since 1987, the
year of the last important realignments within the ERM. But Germans'
superior productivity growth record has meant that its unit labour costs
have risen by less than those of French industry. The UK and Italy have seen
larger increases in both earnings and unit labour costs than in Germany.
In part, the rise in German wage inflation results from the economic
consequences of unification and the demand boom sparked off by a rise in
consumer spending by east Germans  - funded largely by hand-outs from the
western government.
However, it is also a product of pre-unification tensions. The latter half
of the 1980s was a period of unusual wage restraint. In return for a drop in
working hours, the unions agreed to moderate their wage demands.
With hindsight, the unions overestimated the cost to employers of the fall
in working hours. As a result the share of national income distributed to
labour fell to levels not seen since the early 1970s. The strikes are partly
the result of union attempts to claw back labour's share.
The Bundesbank has responded to rising inflationary pressures by pushing up
interest rates across Europe; while the government, faced with a ballooning
fiscal deficit, has pushing up income taxes. The recent crop of wage demands
is the direct manifestation of the refusal of west German workers to accept
a fall in their after-tax incomes.
Despite Germany's boom, and slow or zero growth elsewhere in Europe, UK and
Italian wage inflation remains higher than in Germany.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
