<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Labour loses heavily in polls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LABOUR party suffered heavy losses in yesterday's local elections in
England, deepening the party's post-general election gloom.
The Conservative share of the vote, projected across Great Britain, was
estimated by the BBC at about 45 per cent  - the Tories' strongest local
election showing since Mrs Thatcher first took power in 1979.
Basildon again exemplified Labour's trauma in southern England. The Essex
town unexpectedly returned a Tory MP last month: yesterday all the 15 seats
up for grabs on its council fell to the Tories, who took control.
The ghost of Militant also refused to die: the Liberal Democrats gained 10
seats in Liverpool, seven from Militant and three from Labour, while in
Glasgow Labour's five losses were all to hard-left rebels.
Labour's performance was little better in the Midlands: it lost control of
Walsall and Wolverhampton and fell back sharply in Birmingham and Coventry.
Its only comfort was the Tories' failure to regain Derby.
The number of councils lost by Labour was limited, however, because only
one-third of seats, in a minority of councils, were being contested. There
were no elections in London, Leicester, Nottingham and Plymouth.
Scotland continued to buck the English trend, showing only a modest Tory
advance. Labour added Aberdeen to its council strongholds north of the
border while the Tories failed to win Edinburgh  - though Labour lost its
overall majority in the city.
Labour lost control of 16 councils in total, including Bury (Greater
Manchester), Cambridge, Dudley, Milton Keynes, Rochdale, Walsall, Welwyn
Hatfield, and Wyre Forest. The party also suffered notable losses in
Brighton, Bristol, Manchester, Newcastle upon Tyne and Peterborough.
Mr Chris Patten, Tory party chairman, hailed the results as 'terrific - a
strong confirmation
of last month's general election result'.
For Labour, Mr John Cunningham conceded 'disappointment'. 'The general
election defeat means that we are losing hundreds of seats in safe Labour
areas.'
For the Liberal Democrats, Mr Simon Hughes predicted the party would end the
night with its largest number of councillors ever  - although its share of
the vote was barely up on 1988, the last time the seats fought for yesterday
were contested.
With 3,652 of the 3,910 results declared, Labour had suffered a net loss of
362 seats, with the Conservatives gaining 303 seats and the Liberal
Democrats 65. Most Tory gains were at the expense of Labour, with the
Liberal Democrats gaining from both sides.
The turnout was low across Britain  - as little as 20 per cent in some
inner-city wards.
Despite making a net gain of 31 seats, the Scottish National Party failed to
add much momentum to its campaign for Scottish independence.
Only four councils in Wales voted yesterday, with none changing control.
Results, reaction and analysis, Page 11
</TEXT>
