<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Lloyds bid for Midland hit by Brittan decision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN, ROBERT PESTON and DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYDS BANK said yesterday it was determined to proceed with its proposal to
buy Midland Bank despite a severe blow to its hopes from Sir Leon Brittan,
the EC competition commissioner.
Sir Leon said he believed a bid for Midland from Hongkong and Shanghai
Banking Corporation fell within Brussels' jurisdiction while Lloyds' rival
proposal would not.
Lloyds was confident Sir Leon's announcement was an interim statement and
did not mean the Hongkong bid would definitely fall outside UK jurisdiction.
Lloyds wants both bids to be investigated by Britain's Monopolies and
Mergers Commission.
The Financial Times reported yesterday that the Office of Fair Trading was
planning to recommend that Lloyds' proposed bid  - but not the HSBC offer  -
be referred to the MMC.
Separately, Lloyds challenged Midland's refusal of commercial information
needed for a formal bid. Midland has already supplied the information to
Hongkong Bank.
Midland said its directors believed it would be wrong to release
confidential information when it was still unclear whether Lloyds would be
able to bid for it. Lloyds said it expected a ruling from the Takeover Panel
in due course.
This is the first time that Sir Leon, the EC competition commissioner, has
intervened during the Commission's routine one-month inspection of important
takeovers and mergers to make such an announcement purely about
jurisdiction.
An EC official said Sir Leon had done this to clear up mounting speculation
about how scrutiny might be divided between Brussels and London. However,
the official said that in the unlikely event the Commission was given
further relevant information, Sir Leon could change his mind about who has
jurisdiction.
The Commission said it was simply a matter of geography and arithmetic that
brought the HSBC bid within  - and the Lloyds proposal outside  - the remit
of the EC's 1990 merger regulation. In the case of Midland and HSBC, 'enough
of their business together is done outside the UK to bring the vetting of
such a merger to us', the EC official said. 'The competition implications of
the HSBC bid are therefore being considered in the normal way during the
remainder of the one-month inquiry period', Sir Leon said in his statement.
The Commission has until late May to decide whether to clear the bid or to
launch a full-scale four-month inquiry.
The UK has only two grounds on which to ask to deal with the bid itself. It
could invoke the merger regulation's Article 21, which deals with
non-competition aspects, to argue that prudential concerns require the bid
to be vetted in the UK. The Bank of England has already let it be known it
sees no threat posed by the HSBC bid to Midland's depositors. The UK's
second option is to claim, under Article 9, that the HSBC bid poses special
competition problems within the UK.
But this argument may be hard to sustain, given HSBC's geographical base.
The Commission has already sbown itself extremely unwilling to entertain
member states' pleas on these grounds. In any case, the UK has little time
to decide whether to use this latter option.
According to the regulation, a member state must request a referral within
three weeks of getting a copy from Brussels of the merger notification.
Editorial Comment, Page 16
Lex, Page 18
Takeover policy, Page 20
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
