<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Arts: The Coronation of Poppaea - Opera
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Monteverdi's last opera, when performed as superbly as it is in the new
Opera Factory production, becomes one of the most complex and disturbing of
all artistic experiences. Its main themes are sexual infatuation and the
abuse of state power, and the terrible links that can be forged between
them. Poppaea is like Mozart's Figaro in the way it presents a complete
spectrum of characters shaded by love and lust; but it is unlike that folle
journee in that the good end unhappily and the bad happily - and that, in
the view of the composer and his librettist Busenello, seems to be what Life
means.
This pitiless tale of moral and emotional ambiguities told in a score of
utmost grave beauty would seem to be native territory for David Freeman and
his Factory hands. So it proves. The Queen Elizabeth Hall stage, designed by
David Roger as an airy, marbled-tinted stepped arena with two small
instrumental bands disposed on either side, offers an acting space of ideal
intimacy - with different areas colonised at different times, the total made
grander than the sum of its parts.
The format of scenes, at once freely developing and strict in structural
control, is permitted to build up its awesome intensity without any of the
barriers normally placed between characters and audience in larger Poppaea
theatres. The text is uncut, and faster-moving than most nipped and tucked
ones; Anne Ridler's fine translation, uttered with unaffected clarity by the
entire cast, provides the motor power of the staging - as in this opera the
words always should but so often do not.
And Freeman's encouragement of all the ensemble virtues (which include
performers in more than one role) promotes a cross-cutting between the
opera's shared destinies that grapples the audience to their unfolding with
iron hooks. The treatment of one scene seems questionable: the Nero-Lucan
duet, here a dressing-up scene with the emperor in semi-drag and minions
throwing up into fruit-bowls. Historically suggestive, no doubt, but the
piercing irony of text would perhaps be better served by plainer means.
For the rest, though, the combination of fluidity, athletic movement and
unfettered characterisation makes this a sharper-pointed, more multi-faceted
Poppaea than any I have previously encountered. The tension pulled between
the three female leads is alarmingly taut: Marie Angel in the title role,
horribly well-judged in her calculated sensuality, the fast-vibrato-laden
tone-colour applied with pinpoint skill; Janis Kelly as Octavia,
magnificently aristocratic in bearing and declamation; and the attractively
bright-toned Sally Ann Shepherdson as Drusilla, who rises to her test of
loyalty (violently staged by Freeman) with fierce youthful passion.
The male-soprano leads are taken by male performers, and sung an octave
below pitch: common 20th-century practice, which normally fogs up the vocal
lines a great deal more than it does here - a tribute to the controlled
spontaneity and fleetness of the singing and its accompaniment under Peter
Robinson's direction. Nigel Robson's tenor Nero, pig-tailed, sexually
ambiguous and quick to violence, is another horribly well-judged portrayal;
Geoffrey Dolton's baritone Otho, the great romantic of the opera, pours out
his agonies in ever more eloquent style.
The Seneca of Michael Neill, in spite of odd vowel-sounds, touches all the
right depths. Howard Milner's high-tenor Nurse is both raucously funny and
genuinely tender, though in the lullaby - how revealing that the opera's
lyrical peak-point should be a hymn to sweet oblivion] - he inevitably
misses an alto's full rich tonal flow. No Poppaea has everything; this one
lacks the 'animal' lustre that great voices finely used can shed on the
drama. The qualities it does possess - dramatic conviction, musical
directness, wholeness of viewpoint - are more than sufficient compensation.
Queen Elizabeth Hall: performances until May 12, then five more in June
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
