<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Cultural change on training urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs URGED a significant cultural change to improve the status of training
yesterday.
The Commons employment committee made the recommendation in a report
containing a broad sweep of conclusions on the employment consequences of
sudden industrial change. Evidence was taken from a variety of industrial
areas.
The committee said British assumptions about manufacturing jobs needed to be
overhauled radically. It urged a change in attitude to engineers,
entrepreneurs, relocation and career change. 'Some evidence indicates
attitudes are already changing to relocation and career change, but more
needs to be done to encourage this trend.'
The report said companies should regard training as a profitable investment
rather than as a cost and criticised government training programmes for not
meeting the needs of industry.
A serious concern, the report said, was the maintenance of a modern national
skills base if the UK was to remain a serious competitor in world markets
and improve its international economic standing.
The committee commended British Coal Enterprise, a subsidiary of British
Coal, and British Steel, for their efforts to create new alternative
employment in areas where they made redundancies.
It recommended that, where possible, companies that made significant numbers
of employees redundant should extend practical help.
A report of the committee of public accounts published yesterday said it
regarded as 'unacceptable' the accounting procedures that led to more than
Pounds 85m being paid for training between 1989 and 1991 without adequate
documentation to substantiate claims.
The report, which follows a similar one from the National Audit Office, said
it was essential that Training and Enterprise Councils, which administer the
two main government training schemes, fulfilled their obligations to
undertake effective financial monitoring and control. It expected the
Department of Employment to apply contractual sanctions and penalties firmly
if Tecs failed to meet their obligations.
</TEXT>
