<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Egyptian government presented its 1992-93 budget to parliament
yesterday, cutting subsidies but increasing both military spending and civil
service salaries in line with inflation, Reuter reports from Cairo.
Egypt is part-way through a radical programme of economic reform, agreed
with the IMF last May.
The budget put spending for the year from July 1 at Dollars 18.9bn, up only
14 per cent against inflation of nearly 20 per cent.
The draft proposed a modest reduction in the budget deficit to Dollars
2.8bn. Targets agreed with the IMF include cutting the overall state budget
deficit to 6.5 per cent of GDP in 1992-93 from 9.5 per cent in 1991-92. The
draft budget covers only the central government and the IMF's targets are
based on all state spending.
