<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Followers of Nasser form new party: Surprise as Egyptian
'opposition' party is sanctioned by court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WITHOUT any fanfare, a political party bearing the name of Egypt's late
President Gamal Abdel Nasser has been quietly reconstituted in Egypt, but
commentators doubt it will become a force in the land.
Mohammed Sayed Ahmed, a columnist for the daily Al Ahram, said the decision
of an Egyptian court to sanction a Nasserite party after years of rebuffs,
reflected a desire by the government to extend Egypt's democratic base in
the almost certain knowledge that the new party would not pose a serious
challenge to the established order.
'The authorities no longer see it as a liability to have Nasserism as a
symbol of opposition,' said Mr Sayed Ahmed. 'Rather, they view the secular
Nasserites as a potential asset at a time when the religious trend is
gaining momentum.'
While the memory of Egypt's late president, who became a towering figure in
the Arab and developing world until he was diminished by the Arabs'
calamitous defeat in the 1967 war with Israel, remains strong at home, his
socialist-era rule from 1952-1970 is generally regarded to have been deeply
flawed, and to have contributed to many of Egypt's present ills.
Mona Makram Ebeid, an independent member of Egypt's parliament and a
sociology professor at the American University in Cairo, said the
Nasserites, to be known as the Arab Democratic Nasserist party (ADN), may
attract a 'nostalgia' vote, but doubted the party would become a rallying
point for disaffection.
'They have yet to put their house in order,' she said. 'They don't have a
charismatic leader, and their programme is still nebulous. One gets the
impression that they were surprised that they were accepted by the court.'
The Nasserites may, however, emerge as the main opposition bloc in Egypt's
parliament, the 454-seat People's Assembly, dominated by the National
Democratic Party with 348 seats.
At present the leftist Tugammu, or National Unionist Progressive Party, with
just six seats constitutes the only organised opposition. The remainder are
independents, some of whom might join the Nasserites.
Egypt's November, 1990, elections were boycotted by established
organisations such as the nationalist Wafd party, the Moslem Brotherhood,
the Socialist Labour Party and the Liberals.
The main opposition groupings said they boycotted the poll because they
could not be sure it would be free and fair.
Mohammed Faik, a former information minister under Nasser and one of the
leaders of the ADN, insisted this week that the party did not represent an
'idolisation' of Nasser. Rather, it wanted to use his legacy to promote Arab
unity and the 'excellent ideal of independent development.
'Nasserism is not a reactionary movement, it's not a theory, nor does it
mean a hero-worshipping,' he declared. 'It's just an experience affiliated
to Nasser ..'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
International Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9386</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEHBEAABFT</PROFILE>
