<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / EC applicants seek to speed entry: Czechs, Poles and
Hungarians to step up co-operation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRAGUE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE three central European countries of Czechoslovakia, Hungary and Poland
yesterday agreed to consider how their entry into the European Community
could be co-ordinated.
At the same time, Presidents Vaclav Havel of Czechoslovakia, Lech Walesa of
Poland, and Jozsef Antall of Hungary said they would step up economic,
political and security cooperation as as to speed up entry into the EC.
'We agreed that we will apply to the European Community together  .. if we
join our voices, our demands will be heard more strongly, than if we act
individually,' said Mr Havel.
The three presidents, who concluded a two-day meeting in Prague, the capital
of the Czech and Slovak republic, also jointly expressed their readiness to
recognise Macedonia, the former republic of Yugoslavia.
On the subject of greater European integration, the three presidents also
agreed to promote the possibility of Japan becoming an associated member of
the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe (CSCE).
Formal relations between Japan and the CSCE, the pan-European body which
includes former Soviet republics, were recently discussed between Mr Kiichi
Miyazawa, the Japanese prime minister and heads of state in Paris and Bonn.
</TEXT>
