<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity market surges to all-time high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HEAVY overseas buying of June Footsie futures, principally by US investment
banks, and a rethink by domestic institutions of the equity market's
prospects after Tuesday's interest rate cut, saw the FT-SE 100-share Index
burst through its all-time peak and launch a determined but ultimately
unsuccessful attack on the 2,700 level.
At the close of another session of heavy trading the index stood at a record
2,698.7, up 36.5 on the day.
The market's previous all-time peak, an intraday level of 2,683.7, was
attained last September, coinciding with a reduction in bank base rates to
10.5 per cent. Since the Tories' general election victory the Footsie has
risen 262.3 points, or almost 11 per cent. Many dealers were caught on the
hop by a sudden transformation in the market's fortunes which took place
mid-morning.
Share prices had opened with widespread but moderate losses as marketmakers,
mindful of Wall Street's overnight decline and a general view of a period of
consolidation, were happy to cut dealing levels in the hope that the lower
prices would attract much needed stock into the market.
Opening some five points down, the Footsie proceeded to drift back and
registered a decline just exceeding nine points within an hour of the
opening, reflecting bouts of profit-taking, before embarking on a remarkable
rally which eventually propelled the index into virgin territory.
A couple of indifferent trading results, from Tate &amp; Lyle and Trafalgar
House, added to the early uncertainty.
The emergence of the big US-sourced buying orders in the Footsie future  -
one leading US house was said to have purchased 2,000 contracts and another
was heavily involved on the buy side - triggered a scramble to cover short
positions by other brokers, and the future promptly surged ahead.
The cash market, where buying interest revealed widespread short positions
in many stocks, went with futures and, by midday, was threatening to
puncture the all-time high. Shortly afterwards the index sailed through the
previous high and kept on going, helped by a firm opening on Wall Street,
until it met a flurry of resistance just short of 2,700.
The US buying was not confined to futures, but encompassed traditional North
American investment favourites such as Hanson, Glaxo and SmithKline Beecham.
BAT, after good first-quarter results, was also well supported.
On the downside, Trafalgar House's halved interim dividend, in spite of the
increased profits, induced exceptionally heavy selling, while Tate &amp; Lyle's
half-year results and the post-figures meeting with sector analysts saw the
shares under pressure throughout the day.
British Gas was another notable underperformer, with the shares persistently
sold after Ofgas's demand for a cut in prices to customers. Mr Steve Turner,
energy specialist at Smith New Court, said Gas's warning on prices was: 'An
indication of a summer of discontent as far as relations between British Gas
and the industry regulator are concerned.' Seaq turnover in equities
totalled 637.1m shares.
</TEXT>
