<DOCNO>FT922-9393</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAHCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Money Markets: Sterling trade quiet
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER A busy period in the sterling money market dominated by the Bank of
England's  1/2 percentage point base rate cut on Tuesday, dealing resumed a
much calmer tone yesterday.
The volume of futures trading was exceptionally small. The combined trade in
both the June and September short sterling contracts hovered around 16,000
lots yesterday.
'On a normally quiet day, trading in a front month contract would never be
less than 18,000 to 20,000 lots,' commented Mr Nick Parsons, head of the
Treasury Advisory Group at CIBC in London. 'But the general mood is that
this level of base rates will be here for some time to come.'
June short sterling ended the day at 89.93, implying that interest rates in
June will be at 10.07 per cent. Traders believe that the floor for short
sterling is now 89.88, indicating an interest rate of 10.12 per cent in
June. 'The knowledge that interest rates will not go up means that nobody
will sell it any way below that,' said one trader yesterday.
In the interbank market there was only a little movement in period rates.
Most of them, in the immediate aftermath of Tuesday's cut, were at 10 1/8
per cent. Yesterday, rates for everything from two months money to six
months firmed up to 10 3/16 per cent. One week money was at the easier rate
of 10 per cent, after forecasts of a much smaller shortage in the discount
market for the first half of next week.
Yesterday morning, the Bank of England forecast a shortage of around Pounds
1.05bn in the discount market. In early operations, the Bank purchased bills
totalling Pounds 275m for resale to the market on May 27 at an interest rate
of 9 15/16 per cent.
In further operations, the Bank purchased bills totalling Pounds 262m, of
which Pounds 200m were Band-1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent and Pounds 62m
were for resale to the market on May 27 at an interest rate of 9 15/16 per
cent. The bank operated in the market in the afternoon, purchasing Pounds
147m of Band-1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent and Pounds 10m of Band-2 bills
at 9 7/8 per cent.
In the German money markets, attention focused on the Bundesbank's decision
to sell DM19.3bn of 28-day funds and DM7.8bn of 56-day money at 9.65 per
cent, a rise of 5 basis points on previous rates.
</TEXT>
