<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / International Company News: General Dynamics plans sale of
missiles operation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Dynamics, the second largest Pentagon contractor, aims to sell off
businesses which contribute about one-quarter of its revenues - including
its large missiles operation - in a radical plan to cope with the shrinking
defence market.
It is in the final phase of negotiating the sale of the missiles business,
and could announce a deal soon, Mr William Anders, the chairman, said
yesterday.
Mr Anders, who has been sharply reducing the size of the company since he
took over as chairman in 1991, told the annual meeting General Dynamics
would adapt to the 'new realities' of the defence market by concentrating on
four core areas: tactical aircraft, nuclear submarines, armoured vehicles
and space launch systems.
It recently sold its Cessna business aircraft subsidiary to Textron, and has
adopted a 'plan of contraction' which involves selling other non-core
businesses accounting for some Dollars 2.3bn of the group's Dollars 8.7bn of
annual revenues.
The list is headed by the missiles operation, which had sales last year of
Dollars 1.3bn and consists of two parts: an air defence systems division,
which makes tactical products such as the Stinger and Standard missiles; and
a section of the group's Convair subsidiary, which makes the Tomahawk
sea-launched cruise missiles used during the Gulf war.
Mr Anders said the missiles business had been seriously considered as a
potential core business. However, it could not become the leader in a field
which included nearly a dozen firms in the US alone. During talks with
numerous other companies, 'we found more interest in the purchase of our
operations than the sale of their own'.
Other parts of the group up for sale include the remainder of Convair, which
makes fuselages for the McDonnell Douglas MD-11 commercial aircraft; the
electronics division, which is a leading producer of avionics test
equipment; and a materials division which produces aggregates, concrete,
lime and coal.
Mr Anders' strategy is radically different from that of most defence
contractors, which have reacted to the shrinking Pentagon budget by trying
to diversify into non-defence areas. He said yesterday the benefits of
diversification were 'largely illusory'.
The restructuring of the group has helped increase the company's cash and
marketable securities to Dollars 1.2bn at the end of March. Mr Anders said
the company was generating cash 'well in excess' of that needed to meet
investment and debt reduction needs. He continued to favour some
distribution to shareholders. The company's shares closed down Dollars 1 at
Dollars 64 7/8 .
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
