<DOCNO>FT922-9405</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAG0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / International Company News: Curtain falls on a Hollywood
drama - Credit Lyonnais's ill-starred association with Giancarlo Parretti
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shortly after 10 o'clock this morning, in the nondescript town of
Wilmington, Delaware, the banging of an auctioneer's gavel should signal a
most ignominious fate for MGM, the once legendary Hollywood studio.
The auction is mainly a formality - the mechanism by which Credit Lyonnais
of France forecloses on a huge loan default and takes possession of MGM
stock by swapping around Dollars 400m of loans for 98.5 per cent of the
studio's shares.
In theory, anyone hoping to outbid the French state bank creditor and buy
MGM could come along this morning with at least Dollars 570m of cash in hand
 -Dollars 400m for the shares and another Dollars 170m for related loan
commitments. But MGM suffered a Dollars 347m loss last year, and will need a
further Dollars 200m of cash to make it through the current year. It's no
bargain.
Rather, the foreclosure by Credit Lyonnais is intended as the definitive
severing of ties between the Paris-based bank and Mr Giancarlo Parretti, the
controversial Italian financier from whom the shares are being taken away.
The mercurial Mr Parretti, who is still appealing a four-year jail sentence
in Naples on fraud charges, refuses to accept defeat. As recently as this
week he claimed he would win out over Credit Lyonnais, but as far as the
bank is concerned, a recent US injunction has rendered Mr Parretti more of a
nuisance than a threat.
Worse, from Credit Lyonnais's point of view, the ill-starred association
with the stocky former waiter has shocked many of its blue-chip clients and
investors and is costing the bank dearly.
The doubling of its 1991 bad debt provisions, to FFr9.5bn (Dollars 1.71bn),
is believed to have included part of the MGM exposure. According to
information obtained by the Financial Times, Credit Lyonnais's present loan
exposure to MGM and to Mr Parretti's various companies amounts to Dollars
1.25bn.
MGM was suffering long before November 1990, when Mr Parretti paid Dollars
1.3bn - most of it borrowed from Credit Lyonnais  - to acquire the studio.
The studio's difficulties were the result of the juggling of assets and
repeated sacking of executives by Mr Kirk Kerkorian, the Las Vegas nightclub
owner who had owned MGM since 1969.
When Mr Parretti bought MGM, he had as a partial backer, Mr Steve Ross, the
fast-talking chairman of Time Warner who promised Dollars 650m of loan
guarantees in exchange for right to the MGM film library. Within months Time
Warner claimed it had been betrayed and sued Mr Parretti for breach of
contract. In yet another reversal, Time Warner then decided to make peace
and do business again with Mr Parretti.
Mr Ross and Time Warner have come under harsh criticism for the association
with Mr Parretti, but they got a home video distribution deal on the cheap.
From the very start most of Wall Street and Hollywood were betting Mr
Parretti would not last very long at MGM, and rightly so.
By March 1991 - just four months after Mr Parretti took over the desk once
owned by Louis B. Mayer - a group of MGM unpaid creditors sued to force the
studio into bankruptcy.
Credit Lyonnais, alarmed at the deteriorating state of affairs, sent two top
executives to Hollywood, provided MGM with an emergency Dollars 145m fresh
line of credit and insisted as a condition that Mr Parretti give up his
position at Pathe, his master company, and at MGM.
In his place as chairman Mr Parretti put Mr Cesare De Michelis, the brother
of his old friend and fellow nightclub habitue Mr Gianni De Michelis,
Italy's Socialist foreign minister. Mr De Michelis lasted less than a month
before Mr Parretti and the French bank began to sue one another.
By the summer of 1991 the legal battle between Credit Lyonnais and Mr
Parretti had degenerated into a slanging match. Lawsuits flew back and forth
in America.
By late December 1991 the chancery court in Delaware, where MGM is
incorporated, had thrown out all of Mr Parretti's claims and upheld the
right of Credit Lyonnais to remove him and his associates. Mr William Allen,
the presiding judge, even declared that Mr Parretti 'did not give truthful
testimony when he testified under oath in this court'.
Mr Parretti could not be in Delaware to hear the verdict; he spent late
December in a Sicilian jail, accused of tax evasion.
Down, but not forgotten, the controversial Italian returned to the fray two
months ago, claiming that a Rome judge had ordered the sequester of MGM
stock and once again named the brother of Italy's foreign minister as MGM
chairman. It was at this stage that Credit Lyonnais secured the binding
Delaware injunction that ruled any Rome judge's views to be irrelevant under
US law.
With today's foreclosure auction, Credit Lyonnais is seeking to sever all
ties to Mr Parretti. True to form, Mr Parretti yesterday told the Financial
Times he considered the auction to be 'phony' and swore once again that Mr
De Michelis would be named to MGM.
The voluble Italian even argued he was not really in default on his loans
from Credit Lyonnais. 'How can I be in default? They never really asked me
to pay interest,' he maintained. Asked how much he had borrowed from the
French bank, Mr Parretti then claimed: 'I can't remember.'
Mr Parretti may not recall, but the amounts are considerable. It has been
learned that the Dollars 1.25bn total of Credit Lyonnais loan exposure
includes nearly Dollars 650m of loans to MGM itself, plus another Dollars
595m to three of Mr Parretti's holding companies - Comfinance, Melia and
Pathe Communications.
Credit Lyonnais is owed some Dollars 75m by Comfinance, a company that
jointly controls MGM by way of two other vehicles - Melia and Pathe. Melia
owes some Dollars 400m, including interest, while Pathe, owes Dollars 120m,
including interest.
Although Credit Lyonnais will convert about Dollars 400m of these loans into
equity as payment in today's auction, the bank will still be left with
Dollars 850m of combined MGM and Parretti-company debt on its books. The
bank does not expect to be able to sell MGM until the shattered studio can
begin producing profitable films, and that is likely to take at least
another two years.
Internal bank plans call for financial support of at least Dollars 200m this
year, and probably as much again in 1993.
That means that by early 1994, assuming MGM is profitable and saleable again
 -a big if in itself  - Credit Lyonnais will be sitting on a total outlay of
more than Dollars 1.2bn again.
Put simply, Credit Lyonnais is likely to be stuck in Hollywood, with heavy
loan exposure and a battered and loss-making studio on its hands, for quite
some time. Today's auction thus may represent a new beginning for MGM, but
at blockbuster cost.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 30
</PAGE>
