<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Beattie tackles tough times
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
JAMES BEATTIE, the Wolverhampton-based department store operator, saw
pre-tax profit decline by 14 per cent, from Pounds 9m to Pounds 7.73m, in
the year to January 31 1992.
Against the depressed background it was a commendable performance, said Sir
Eric Pountain, chairman.
Operating profit in the second half was only 6 per cent lower than last
year, and compared with a drop of 34 per cent in the first half. The
important Christmas trade was very late to develop.
Sales edged ahead to Pounds 67.6m (Pounds 67m) excluding VAT, and operating
profit was nearly 13 per cent lower at Pounds 5.25m. There had been tight
control on costs and the group also resisted the temptation to secure sales
volume by surrendering margins, Sir Eric said.
Investment income and interest declined to Pounds 2.49m (Pounds 3m)
reflecting the downward movement of interest rates. Earnings per share were
11.3p (13.03p) and the final dividend is 4.35p for a total of 5.75p (5.5p).
</TEXT>
