<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Lloyds takeover not in public interest,
says Bifu - The Battle for Midland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LLOYDS takeover of Midland Bank would lead to monopoly banking in some
towns and would not be in the public interest, Bifu, the banking union, will
tell MPs today, writes Catherine Milton.
The union is trying to increase support for a referral of the bid to the
monopoly authorities because it believes 30,000 jobs and 1,100 branches are
at risk if it succeeds.
In a dossier sent to Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary,
all MPs and British Euro MPs, the union explains why it believes the merger
would not be in the public interest.
'Such a merger would be harmful to customers and staff and to the UK economy
since it would lead to unemployment and reduce competition.
A number of towns currently have only a Lloyds and a Midland branch and
there would, in effect, be monopoly banking in those towns. The customer
would lose a choice.'
The union rejects the argument that the UK has too many bank branches,
saying it ranks equal fourth with France among nine leading nations for the
number of branches per head of population.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
