<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Suitors to lobby MPs next week - The Battle
for Midland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LOBBYING of members of parliament by Midland's two suitors will begin in
earnest next week when senior executives from both Hongkong Bank and Lloyds
are expected to meet Conservative backbenchers.
A meeting with Mr William Purves has been provisionally arranged for next
Wednesday or Thursday when the Hongkong Bank chairman is due in London.
MPs are understood to have offered Lloyds a similar opportunity although
details have yet to be finalised. It is expected that all Tory backbenchers
will have the option of attending the meetings.
The standard format is for those addressing such gatherings - usually
scheduled to last about an hour - to be given up to 15 minutes to present
their case before fielding questions.
Mr Tim Smith, the Conservative MP for Beaconsfield and an officer of the
Tory backbench finance committee in the last parliament, is understood to
have played a leading role in arranging the meetings. Such is the geographic
spread of the groups involved that interest among MPs is likely to be
exceptionally widespread.
Midland is next week expected to follow the example of its suitors in
writing to all MPs.
MPs recently received a letter from Sir Jeremy Morse, Lloyds chairman,
arguing that the Hongkong offer failed to address 'the fundamental problems
in the UK banking sector.' Hongkong Bank is expected to send out its own
letter to MPs shortly.
Meanwhile, Mr Michael Heseltine, President of the Board of Trade, will this
week field his first written questions on the tussle for Midland.
Ms Marjorie Mowlam, Labour front bench spokeswoman on City and corporate
affairs, is to ask Mr Heseltine when he expects to be informed both of the
EC competition directorate's views on the Hongkong proposals and of the
Office of Fair Trading's opinion of the possible takeover of Midland by
Lloyds.
Mr Heseltine will also be asked whether he proposes any amendment to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission's present approach to potential takeovers
in which the implication for competition is the sole criterion taken into
consideration.
</TEXT>
