<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Trafalgar House halves dividend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAFALGAR House, the property, construction and engineering group, halved
its dividend as pre-tax profits for the six months to March 31 increased 18
per cent on the back of a strong performance from construction and
engineering.
Sir Eric Parker, chief executive, said the group would focus on construction
and engineering which had an order book of almost Pounds 4bn as he unveiled
pre-tax profits of Pounds 54m compared with Pounds 45.5m. Turnover increased
from Pounds 1.5bn to Pounds 2.1bn.
Sir Eric said the cut in the interim dividend, from 8.8p to 4.4p, which was
signalled last year, would help mitigate its problems over unrelieved
advance corporation tax. He added the group still needed another UK business
to get rid of the problem once and for all.
Trafalgar had further bad news for former shareholders in Davy Corporation,
which the group took over last June. Although the group hopes to lease the
Ocean Emerald oil rig to Midland and Scottish Resources for about Pounds 20m
it held out little hope of Davy's former shareholders receiving the second
payment, totalling Pounds 54m or 45p a share.
This is because in Trafalgar's view MSR is still unlikely to be able to draw
upon the Pounds 118m letter of credit with the project's bankers. Without
the letter of credit Trafalgar House says it cannot make the second payment
to the Davy shareholders.
Operating profits from property and investment and shipping and hotels
continued to fall. The former reported profits of Pounds 6.6m, compared with
Pounds 19m, while the latter suffered a smaller profit fall to Pounds 5.9m
from Pounds 7.6m.
Sir Eric said property continued to experience depressed conditions,
although the removal of political uncertainty and lower interest rates gave
some prospect of a gradual UK recovery. Occupancy levels still remained
disappointing at between 50 per cent and 60 per cent.
Construction and engineering increased profits by 39 per cent to Pounds
53.3m. Sir Eric said the group would focus on these core businesses.
Net borrowings fell from Pounds 450m to Pounds 328m, although debt increased
since the year-end total of Pounds 182m. Fully diluted earnings per share
before extraordinary items fell to 4.8p from 5.9p.
Lex, Page 24
Observer, Page 23
</TEXT>
