<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / German strike talks to resume today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TALKS aimed at ending the 10-day-old public sector strike in Germany were
adjourned last night until today, with no sign of a promised new offer from
the employers.
Union officials and representatives of federal, state and local authorities
had just a brief meeting in Stuttgart after four hours of separate
consultations by the two sides. 'We stood next to each other and did not
have anything to say,' Ms Monika Wulf-Mathies, leader of the largest public
service union, oTV, told reporters.
Negotiators said they would meet this morning for 'further exploratory
talks'. The Bonn government's chief negotiator, Mr Rudolf Seiters, the
interior minister, added: 'We will have lots of time then.'
Hopes had been raised by the public sector employers' indications that they
would make a new offer to try to end what is already western Germany's most
disruptive wave of industrial action since the Second World War.
They previously offered a 4.8 per cent pay rise, while the unions originally
demanded a 9.5 per cent increase. Ms Wulf-Mathies, said before the talks
less than the 5.4 per cent proposed recently by arbitrators would be
rejected.
Both sides hinted earlier this week that a deal limiting wage rises for top
earners and giving more to the lower-paid might be the best way forward.
According to trade union estimates, more than 500,000 workers in both public
and private sectors were on strike yesterday.
While leading economists suggested that the stoppages would have to last at
least a month before having any noticeable effects on economic output,
tangible evidence of the strike's effects continued to mount.
The national railway network was within days of collapse, a Bundesbahn
official said. Only a quarter of its locomotives were still in service and
losses had already reached DM100m (Pounds 34m).
In Cologne 120 wagons of mail were standing in sidings. In Frankfurt an
estimated 13,000 tonnes of uncollected refuse was piled in streets.
At the same time unrest grew in the private sector. About 75,000 members of
the IG Metall engineering workers' union defied threats of a lock-out and
continued warning strikes as it became clear that employers were not yet
prepared to increase their 3.3 per cent pay offer.
IG Metall leaders will meet next Tuesday to decide on their next step.
Building workers, members of the IG Bau union, threatened a work-to-rule
until employers improved their 3.4 per cent offer. Printers demanding an 11
per cent increase continued token protests.
Prof Hans Schneider, chairman of the 'five wise men', the group of leading
independent economic advisers to the government, warned of dangerous
consequences for the economy if the talks led to excessive pay rises.
However, he added, a 5.5 per cent overall deal 'would not be the end of the
world'. He agreed with the respected Ifo economics institute in Munich that
a full month's stoppage in the public sector, with an average of 300,000
workers striking daily would cut the year's GDP growth by only between 0.1
per cent and 0.2 per cent.
</TEXT>
