<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Letter: Right ways for accountants to be regulated and
improve image (1)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From W B KIRKPATRICK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Touche Ross is to be congratulated on calling for the regulation of
auditors to be shifted from the Institute of Chartered Accountants to an
independent body ('Touche attacks ICAEW audit role', May 1). The institute
simply cannot be expected to be an effective regulator. Its primary role is
that of a trade association; inevitably, its role as advocate of the
immediate interest of members will take precedence over its role in
upholding professional standards and increasing public confidence. I am glad
I am not alone in knowing of cases where the two roles have been in
conflict.
The article by Geoffrey Holmes and Alan Sugden (Accountancy column, April
30) on 'six ways to improve the profession's image' would have carried more
weight if it had endorsed the Touche Ross proposal. The article did,
however, underline the importance of asserting the independence of auditors
as a step towards better corporate governance.
An audit is an integral part of good corporate governance and an independent
regulator for auditors is but one of the steps we have to take in the UK to
reach the goal of a truly independent audit.
W B Kirkpatrick,
20 Abbotsbury House,
Abbotsbury Road, London W14
</TEXT>
