<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Observer: Helm over
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
How times change. Had it not been for Trafalgar House's opportunist bid for
its smaller rival P &amp; O 10 years ago, Lord Sterling of Plaistow would not
have been press-ganged into taking the P &amp; O helm.
Today, a revitalised P &amp; O is worth more than three times as much as
Trafalgar House. Nor is it faced with the humiliation of having to halve its
dividend to survive the recession. So does Trafalgar House now need the same
sort of external shock to wake up its rather inbred management team?
Certainly, it has hired a slick PR professional to patch up its
accident-prone image, and there's no doubt that founder Sir Nigel Broackes
looks reinvigorated on his new diet. But something more will be needed to
convince the City that anything much has changed.
A few fresh non-executive faces on the board would be a start, especially if
the Trafalgar House really is intent on transforming itself into a world
class engineering giant. It is the sort of company that the new president of
the board of trade will need to keep an eye on.
</TEXT>
