<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Clash of wills over power for the people: The UK gas
regulator has raised the stakes in his campaign for lower domestic prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir James McKinnon, the gas industry regulator, has come out of the trenches
with his bayonet fixed, fighting for lower gas prices on behalf of UK
households. He jolted the stock market, which immediately knocked 8p off the
price of British Gas shares yesterday before they rallied to close 2 1/2 p
down at 262 1/2 p.
Stockbrokers reacted swiftly to Sir James's demands for British Gas to cut
domestic gas prices by up to 2p a therm, calculating that this would slice
at least Pounds 250m from the company's annual profits of more than Pounds
1bn. But the situation is more complex than the simple arithmetic implies.
The public row is just the latest clash of wills between an aggressive
regulator and a company that has yet to adjust to life under public
surveillance. Relations between Sir James and British Gas have struck a
discordant note since privatisation in 1986.
Sir James sets the price British Gas can charge households for gas supply in
a complicated formula which came into force last month. This limits gas
price increases to 5 percentage points below the rate of inflation, which
means that if the annual inflation rate is below 5 per cent, prices must
fall.
Sir James forecasts inflation will hover around the 4 per cent mark this
year; so prices must be reduced now. He is threatening legal action against
British Gas if it fails to comply with his request. 'Customers need a cut in
price as soon as possible. British Gas should not be using customers' money
to smooth out price rises and falls,' he said yesterday.
But a smooth price decline is what British Gas wants: the company says it
must avoid the 'yo-yo' effect of cutting prices now and possibly having to
raise them again if inflation increases later in the year.
When British Gas made its decision to freeze domestic prices at the
beginning of last month, the company said its projections of inflation were
rather shaky because it did not know the outcome of the general election.
'The prices are reviewed monthly and so at any time an adjustment can be
made,' an official said yesterday.
Part of the argument centres on Sir James's refusal to meet British Gas
officials to discuss a price cut. He said a meeting was unnecessary as the
evidence pointing to the need for a reduction was 'blindingly obvious'. The
lack of communication between Sir James and British Gas points to a somewhat
tense and combative relationship. Sir James is careful to maintain a
distance between himself and the company he regulates, but British Gas
accuses him of being aloof.
The contentious nature of the relationship meant that British Gas only
accepted the April price formula after a long-running dispute on pricing and
faced with the threat of a referral to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
But the company has now indicated that it wants the formula to be reviewed
in the wake of a separate agreement reached with the Office of Fair Trading
in January. The agreement requires it to relinquish half of its share of the
industrial gas market to rival suppliers in a bid to encourage more
competition. British Gas says its deal with the OFT changes its operating
conditions to such an extent that the tough price formula for the domestic
part of its business needs to be eased.
A gas industry observer suggests that British Gas could be sticking to a
clever strategy of freezing prices now in the hope of seeing the formula
revised later in the year, thereby allowing it to keep prices steady or even
to raise them.
Sir James, however, does not sympathise with the request by British Gas for
a revision to the formula. He believes the company should keep its domestic
and industrial businesses separate and that a drop in profit in one should
not affect prices in the other. His comments yesterday on prices could be
the opening salvo in a much more serious disagreement later in the year over
the actual level of the pricing formula.
British Gas must tread carefully if it wants to avoid becoming embroiled in
another distracting dispute over pricing. Sir James has found sympathy for
his views among some politicians, and his arguments have struck a chord
among consumers who resent the idea that they are being overcharged.
The British Gas case against an immediate price cut is technical and not so
readily absorbed by consumers, because it relies on complicated calculations
in the price formula. However, some industry observers believe the company
is right to be cautious and that Sir James has got his arithmetic wrong.
They point out that the current rate of inflation indicates the need for a
price cut of just 0.3p a therm rather than Sir James's 2p.
Sir James himself is rather vague as to how he arrived at the 2p a therm
figure and admits that a 1p reduction in price would probably be sufficient.
But if the battle goes to court Sir James will have to prove the accuracy of
his figures or risk a dent in his credibility.
A cut of only 0.3p a therm would translate into a very small reduction in
most domestic bills, and British Gas says it could make a more significant
cut if it waited until later in the year.
Overall the price paid for gas by UK consumers compares favourably with that
in other western European countries. According to many international
studies, British households pay lower gas bills than their German or Italian
counterparts.
Lower UK gas prices are, however, more a historical accident than a
regulatory triumph. In the past, the price paid by British Gas to North Sea
gas producers fluctuated with the rate of inflation, while prices on the
continent were more closely linked to oil prices.
When oil prices soared in the early 1970s, British consumers were paying
lower gas prices than continental users. In the 1980s, there was a move to
link UK prices more closely to the price of oil, but since then oil prices
have been low and again gas prices have remained relatively low in real
terms.
Nevertheless, consumers need to be convinced they are getting a fair deal or
they may switch to another energy supply. Mr Ian Powe of the Gas Consumers'
Council, a consumers' lobby, said yesterday that Sir James's initiative is
good news for customers.
If Sir James loses any future dispute over pricing, consumers could lose an
aggressive champion. By threatening British Gas with legal action, Sir James
is taking a gamble on the basis of his own calculations which some observers
believe are flawed. It is not clear whether Sir James would win a court
case.
'This is a battle of wills and it is hard to see how both parties can emerge
unscathed,' said Mr Peter Spring, industry analyst at Henderson Crosthwaite,
the broker. Both the regulator and the company have much at stake. For Sir
James, his reputation as an effective industry regulator and his credibility
are on the line. For British Gas, the loss of Pounds 250m in profit would be
extremely hard to justify to shareholders.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 23
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9436</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAF5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / A revolution on the runway: Boeing, the world's largest
commercial aircraft manufacturer, is adjusting to tougher competition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A cultural revolution is taking place at Boeing. For the first time in its
75-year history, the world's leading manufacturer of commercial jets has
appointed a woman - Mrs Rozanne Ridgway, a career diplomat  - to its
all-male board of directors.
More significantly, it is being forced to implement fundamental change in
the way it does business. It has adopted a more open stance towards the
outside world and is encouraging airlines, suppliers and subcontractors to
participate actively in the design of its latest airliner, the 777 widebody
twin engine jet.
In the past, Boeing felt it knew what was best for its airline customers.
'But with the 777, Boeing has for the first time given us direct access to
the process of designing a new aircraft,' says Mr James O'Sullivan, British
Airway's chief project engineer on the 777 programme.
Boeing is also openly talking for the first time of forging close ties,
including equity partnerships, with other companies. 'We have always been a
go-it-alone company with a fearsome amount of pride,' conceded Mr Frank
Shrontz, Boeing's chairman. 'It has been difficult for us to share with
others but we are changing that.'
The reasons, according to Mr Shrontz, are the huge investments necessary to
launch new programmes and the market risks which are forcing companies to
pool their resources. 'I see more and more openness in that sense. I don't
know where our next partners will come from but I am not ruling out
partnerships with any other company in the world.'
This new attitude reflects both the current conditions of the civil aviation
market, which is still struggling to recover from its worst slump since the
Second World War, and the changing nature of the competition facing Boeing.
The biggest challenge has undoubtedly come from Airbus Industrie, the
European aircraft consortium which has steadily built up market share during
the past 20 years with advanced new aircraft and government subsidies.
Airbus has now captured nearly 30 per cent of the world commercial jet
market and has started making serious inroads into some of Boeing's
traditional US airline customers.
Airbus has not only developed a comprehensive family of aircraft to compete
against Boeing, but has also sought to leapfrog its US rival by introducing
new technological concepts to commercial jets. These include fly-by-wire
controls, which enable the pilot's commands from the cockpit to be
transmitted electronically rather than mechanically to the flaps and the
rudder, and computer-aided design systems.
The European consortium is now also threatening to challenge Boeing's
dominance of the jumbo aircraft market by studying the development of a 600
to 800-seater aircraft for the end of the decade.
But Boeing is facing a more immediate threat at the top end of the market
from McDonnell Douglas. Boeing's American rival unveiled plans last week to
build the MD12, a 430 to 510-seat double decker jumbo aircraft to compete
against the Boeing 747-400 and the Seattle company's own longer-term plans
to develop a 600 to 800-seater aircraft either by stretching the 747 or
building an entirely new aircraft.
Both McDonnell Douglas and Airbus are seeking partnerships in the Far East,
one of the most promising markets for large jets, to help them develop their
new jumbos. Airbus has already had preliminary talks with three Japanese
manufacturers - Kawasaki Heavy Industries, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries and
Fuji Heavy Industries - to interest them in a possible equity partnership on
its new jumbo project.
McDonnell Douglas has been in negotiations for the past year to sell up to
49 per cent of its Douglas commercial aircraft business to Asian partners
with Taiwan Aerospace leading the field. Last week, the Taiwanese company
received qualified approval from its government to negotiate the purchase of
up to 40 per cent of the Douglas business for Dollars 2bn.
The proposed Taiwan Aerospace-Douglas deal has increasingly worried Boeing.
It fears this could eventually lead to the emergence of what it calls an
'Asian Airbus'. Mr Shrontz said he hoped the deal would not force Boeing to
fight another subsidised competitor.
The tentative agreement reached last month between the European Commission
and the US government on Airbus subsidies is expected to bring some
discipline to the commercial aircraft market. The agreement will limit
direct government support for future Airbus programmes to 33 per cent of
their total development costs. 'We would have preferred zero subsidies and
zero government involvement,' Mr Shrontz emphasised.
While Boeing believes it has secured an acceptable compromise with Airbus,
it fears Taiwan could distort the market because it is not a member of the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) nor of the Organisation for
Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), and therefore not bound by
Gatt and OECD agreements on commercial aircraft trade. While Taiwan has made
it clear that it seeks to join these organisations, it has also said it
would finance up to 49 per cent of the Douglas deal with low interest loans
and tax incentives.
All these pressures have coincided with the worst slump in civil aviation in
40 years. And Boeing has not escaped the downturn.
Although it has continued to report higher profits and sales (first quarter
net profits of Dollars 441m this year represented a 43 per cent increase
over the same period in 1991), Boeing is being forced to cut about 8,000
jobs this year and scale down production of its 737 narrowbody airliners
from 21 a month to 14 a month next October. Rising profits have resulted
from the high level of aircraft deliveries to customers and recovery in the
company's military activities, while the job cuts reflect a slump in orders.
Boeing does not expect any recovery in new orders until later next year.
Some of its main US customers, including United Airlines, American and
Delta, have announced deferrals of committed orders and significant cuts in
spending. At the latest count, about 725 aircraft are lying idle in the
Arizona desert.
Mr Shrontz said he was optimistic about the longer-term prospects for the
industry. In the short term, however, he acknowledged there was still
considerable uncertainty. 'We need a couple more quarters to tell us that we
are coming out of the recession and things are getting better,' he said.
But Boeing says it cannot afford to wait for the recovery to be sure of
retaining its 60 per cent share of the commercial jet market. Instead, the
company has decided to act now.
The strategy, reflecting the marketing and financial demands of airline
customers, is most evident with the Dollars 5bn Boeing 777 programme.
'The real difference is the direct involvement of airline customers right at
the start of the design of the aircraft,' said Mr Philip Condit, head of the
777 project and widely tipped to take over Boeing's commercial aircraft
division if the new aircraft is a success.
Boeing has formed 235 'design/build' teams grouping together airline
designers and maintenance engineers, suppliers of components and
subcontractors together with Boeing designers and engineers. These teams,
devised by Mr Condit, use powerful computers which enable them to share
their designs through a common database. International partners can
therefore communicate directly from their headquarters.
'One of the things we are trying to do is to meet customer requirements as
opposed to introducing technology for technology's sake,' Mr Condit said.
This collaborative approach is also aimed at building what Boeing calls a
'consumer-driven service-ready aircraft'. Airlines have welcomed the change
because it has helped them introduce specific improvements - such as the
fitting of new overhead luggage bins and better-designed cabin lighting
systems - more quickly.
Boeing wants to reduce to a minimum the changes which normally have to be
made to fix design problems during production of the aircraft and after it
has been delivered to its first airline customers in 1995.
In so doing, it is hoping to avoid repeating the mistakes made three years
ago on the development of the 747-400, the newest member of its jumbo
family. 'The scars of the 747-400 are still there,' Mr Condit conceded.
Boeing was forced to delay delivery for several months of the 747-400 to
initial customers because of teething problems and was also forced by
airlines to make changes to its original design. 'With the 777, we want a
fault-free introduction,' Mr Condit said.
Boeing is introducing more electronics in the 777 than it has ever done on a
new aircraft. The fly-by-wire system on the 777 will be as comprehensive as
on any Airbus aircraft; Boeing is introducing liquid crystal displays in the
cockpit; the 777 is the first aircraft Boeing has designed entirely by
computers using a three-dimensional digital system called Catia developed by
the French Dassault group; the US company is using computer-based training
methods to prepare pilots and maintenance engineers; it is using new
composite materials on the 777 tail and floor beams; it is also offering as
an option a folding wing tip mechanism to enable the aircraft to park more
easily at airport terminal gates.
'Boeing has been pushed by Airbus to develop a technically advanced
aircraft. They want to overtake Airbus after the European group leapfrogged
them,' explained Mr O'Sullivan of British Airways 'We are getting
consistently better and cheaper Boeings because of Airbus and the
competition,' he added. Mr Shrontz agreed. 'We would probably be a lot
flabbier today without competition.'
But with the launch of the 777 programme, 'it's bet your company time' all
over again, added Mr Dick Albrecht, a Boeing executive vice-president. 'The
development costs and lead times are so significant you really risk the
health of the company every time you launch a new programme,' he said.
And just as Boeing will start delivering the first 328-seater 777 widebody
jets to customers in 1995, it will have to consider launching an even more
expensive programme to develop its new jumbo aircraft. That aircraft is
likely to cost more than the 777 and will inevitably force Boeing to
accelerate its open-door strategy. For Boeing, survival as the industry
leader will hinge on its ability to absorb such change.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
