</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Leading Article: A UK lead in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LESS THAN 18 months ago Britain was the perennial spoiler of plans hatched
in Brussels and processed through the institutions of the European
Community. Now it is well placed to be among the first to ratify the
Maastricht treaty. Its economic policy is being shaped to ensure that in the
medium term it meets the convergence criteria set forth in that document.
The government remains determined to bring about the completion of the
single market. It looks forward with enthusiasm to the enlargement of the
EC. It wants to introduce budgetary discipline into community affairs and
will try again to make sense of the agricultural policy. In sum, the United
Kingdom seeks to be more than a good European; its aim is to be a leader of
Europe.
This is a reversal of postwar history, during which Britain has held back
from, or opposed, every development proposed by France and Germany, starting
with the coal and steel community. Now it is well placed to be the proposer
itself, either with the two leading mainland powers, or in concert with
other members. A British government has at last accepted that it is part of
the European entity.
This is the most striking inference to be drawn from the Queen's address to
parliament yesterday. Mr John Major became prime minister in November 1990
as a result of the downfall of Mrs Margaret Thatcher; her political demise
was brought about in large part by divisions among Conservatives over
European policy. Those divisions persist, but Mr Major has done much to
blunt the force of both the irreconcilable anti-Europeans (now reduced to a
rump) and the romantic Eurofederalists. He has united most of his party
around a centrist position defended with skill at Maastricht.
Fundamental decisions
The result was an agreement that recognises that the EC is a congeries of
states, whose fundamental decisions are made in a continuing series of
negotiations between its member governments. This concept has been eroded
with the extension of majority voting, but the essence remains. Defence and
security are not even within the EC structure. Britain stands alone in its
refusal to sign the social chapter and its insistence on an opt-out clause
on the single currency, but the community is learning to live with some of
the idiosyncrasies of its most powerful offshore member.
This general position will inform Mr Major's conduct of his government's
presidency of the EC, which begins in July. To judge by his style in
exploiting similar opportunities in the G7 and the security council last
year, the prime minister will make the most of it. He will be helped by both
pomp and circumstance. The Queen will visit the Council of Europe and
address the parliament in Strasbourg next week - the first such royal visit.
She will also make a state visit to France in June, and Germany in October;
the European Council will meet at her palace in Edinburgh in December.
Domestic discomfiture
As to circumstance, the domestic discomfiture of the French president and
the German chancellor, not to mention the disarray of the Italian
government, weakens if only temporarily the influence of those countries.
Britain is for the moment the only large European power with a stable
government and sufficient energy to shape the next phase of the EC's
development.
The moment may, however, be short-lived. There is an apparent contradiction
between the government's enthusiasm for enlargement of the community and its
distaste, expressed by the foreign secretary in a speech last week, for any
further structural negotiations before the agreed date of 1996. There may be
only three new members by then, but that would make an already complicated
structure even more unwieldy.
The president of the commission, Mr Jacques Delors, will shortly circulate
proposals designed to streamline the decision-making machinery before new
members join the existing 12. These are likely to strengthen the commission
and the parliament, probably at the expense of the intergovernmental
committees that at present hold most of the reins of power. If Mr Major
wants to lead opinion, and to retain the spirit of a Europe des patries, he
had better come up with some proposals of his own.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
