<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Arts: Le Bourgeois Gentilhomme - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In 1670 Moliere wrote the ultimate situation comedy about a man who wants to
change situation, Le Bourgeois Gentilhomme. Moliere was, as Voltaire said,
holding up views in general for the reprobation of mankind. The original is
rapier sharp, but the National Theatre Company's latest version could not
cut through a warm flan. This is theatre moyen sensuel, proud to be vulgar
and undemanding, the essence of bourgeois.
Moliere strove to entertain and to instruct. Gentilhomme finds him
castigating the arriviste, warning against the advancement of yearning and
suggesting proper self-culture instead. One sympathises with a man who
wishes to better himself but does not know how. This message arrives as a
series of moral choices neatly balanced, so one is instructed and flattered
into recognising the dangers of pretence.
One learns nothing, however, from this production. It lacks basic
intelligence. The director Richard Jones succeeds in making Moliere au
courant (with plenty of swearing), but has failed to use the resources of
17th-century France.
This play was written in the midst of two decades which yielded Pascal's
Pensees, La Rochefoucauld's Maximes and La Fontaine's Fables. Nothing of its
intellectual milieu survives. The Gentilhomme has been reduced to pantomime.
The production's strengths lie in its boldness: it is neither flawed nor
ill-executed, just disappointing. It starts happily, with Monsieur Jourdain
(very well played by Timothy Spall) amidst the competing pleasures offered
by his hireling masters of Music, Dance, Fencing and Philosophy. Jourdain is
quickly established as a boorish patron: 'It's always bleedin' shepherds' he
says to the Maestro presenting a pastoral.
His Tailor arrives to clothe him, a levee ensues; then Jourdain's
unimpressed Maid (Janine Duvitski) and unimpressable wife (Anita Dobson)
laugh at his pretention.
The production's only joke turns on Jourdain constantly slipping into his
bourgeois origins with 'You silly cow' or 'I beg you, please accept my
humble apologies for the bloody behaviour of my repellent wife.' The
earnestness for etiquette pervades every scene. His anxiety dominates the
action and marginalises the sub-plot, in which he is duped into funding a
spongeing aristocrat's amours and conned into marrying his daughter to her
lover disguised as Turkish royalty.
Moliere knew that manners govern general politeness, and change slowly;
etiquette polices the class boundaries, and changes quickly to keep out the
arriviste. But this production never probes at why Jourdain should want to
recreate himself. Only once does he cry poignantly, 'There's so much I don't
know.'
Taste has more to do with manners than appearances, and so the best scenes
of pretension, including a hugely excessive banquet, are conjured by word
and deed. The brash design, however, is inventive: value-added Louis
Quatorze, in pop-up storybook style, adds legs to the harpsichord and makes
puffy clouds float by outside.
The costumes (Nicky Gillibrand), particularly the beautifully accoutred
swarm of cooks, dancers and singers, make a plain delight in a world of
excess.
The fine music (Jonathan Dove), altered from Moliere's collaborator,
Jean-Baptiste Lully, shows that subtlety can make an impact, for the same
reason that Vaux le Vicomte is a finer Chateau than Versailles: it never
tries too hard.
Lyttelton Theatre, in repertory (071 928 2252)
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9441</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAF0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Arts: Marlene Dietrich - Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The voice was a mellifluous foghorn. The languorous eyelids hung at half
mast while the eyebrows were an elevated fantasy in mascara. And the
well-lit cheekbones were rocks towards which infatuated men sailed knowingly
to their destruction.
Marlene Dietrich, who died yesterday in Paris, was the cinema's most exotic
creation. Whether dressed for kitsch in her films with director Josef Von
Sternberg or slumming it in low-budget Westerns and thrillers, she seemed a
creature entirely composed of artifice.
She was happy that we should see her that way. Dietrich claimed there was no
connection between her public image and her well-guarded private life.
Different versions of that life battled it out in the biographies. Was she
born in Berlin on December 27 1901, as most books say? Yes - though she
herself preferred later dates. Was The Blue Angel (1930) her first film, as
she often insisted? No - it was merely her first film with Josef Von
Sternberg.
Before the icy master with the megaphone came on the scene, Dietrich had
appeared in some 18 films in her native Germany. And as a little-known
European actress she had even co-starred with another little-known European
actress, Greta Garbo, in GW Pabst's 1925 Joyless Street.
The Blue Angel made her world-famous: though the Dietrich she was to become
later under Sternberg - haughty, mysterious, swathed in soft-focus - was a
far cry from the piping cabaret vamp who sings 'Falling in love again' while
doing strange things with her legs on a chair.
Dietrich went to Hollywood in 1930, leaving her husband and daughter behind
in Germany. An off-screen romance began between her and Sternberg, while
on-screen they continued their partnership with six majestic films. The
sublime and the ridiculous lie down happily together in movie romances like
Morocco (1930), Dishonored (1931) and Shanghai Express (1932). And in the
Sternberg-Dietrich masterpiece The Scarlet Empress (1934) Dietrich's beauty
becomes merely one part, albeit the most plastic and haunting, of an
astonishing fresco of scenic effects and design inspirations.
The Sternberg-Dietrich films may be kitsch (her own favourite word of
dismissal), but they have their own passion and conviction. Away from
Sternberg, Dietrich never found the same creative spark, in either herself
or her directors. She seems miscast or undercast in films like Destry Rides
Again (1939), Manpower (1941), A Foreign Affair (1948) and Stage Fright
(1950). And she seems worse than miscast - wheeled on as if to parody
herself - in Hollywod's vain attempts to recreate the Sternbergian magic
with other directors: Richard Boleslawsky's The Garden Of Allah (1936) or
Mitchell Leisen's Golden Earrings (1947).
In later years Dietrich's legend transferred itself effectively to the stage
in her one-woman concerts. But in Hollywood after her heyday she came to be
used as little more than a flavour-enhancer. Glorified cameo roles in films
like Welles's Touch Of Evil (1958), Wilder's Witness For The Prosecution
(1957) and Kramer's Judgment At Nuremberg (1961) showed that Dietrich, even
if she could not exactly act, could smoulder interestingly. More: she could
suggest better than anyone a whole non-Californian world of casbahs,
cabarets and smoky enigma.
Unlike Garbo, Dietrich retired reluctantly from the screen and even returned
for an ill-judged guest role in Just A Gigolo (1978). Equally ill-judged,
perhaps, was her cantankerous voice-only participation in Maximilan Schell's
feature documentary Marlene (1985). Her bullying of interviewer-director
Schell leaves a harsh aftertaste. But there is no denying the spell of that
husky voice; nor, as we watch the vintage film clips, the power that those
chiselled, shining, iconic features still have today.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9442</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAFZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Arts: Injuries inflicted on basic intelligence - Cinema
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A bisexual murderess stabs men to death with an ice pick just after they
have sexually climaxed with her. Who is she? For adding this problem to the
workload of the California police, the screenwriter of Basic Instinct Joe
Eszterhas, formerly of Jagged Edge and Betrayed, was paid Dollars 3m: an
all-time record for a Hollywood script. For playing the San Francisco
detective who goes after her Michael Douglas was paid Dollars 14m. For
directing the film, Paul Verhoeven was paid - enough: let us just say that
the movie's budget was on the runaway side of Dollars 40m.
As a film critic I feel an equivalent amount would compensate me for
injuries to my intelligence. Basic Instinct is no Jagged Edge, even less a
Fatal Attraction. It is a contrived, flashy, predictable crowd-puller, all
the more disappointing for its early promise.
As sexual aggression thrillers go, this one leaves the starting-block at 99
mph. We begin with a young man dying in flagrante with an unidentified
blonde. We move on to Detective Douglas falling for lead suspect Sharon
Stone, a bombshell who writes best-selling novels from her lavish Monterey
retreat. And we are shocked as more ice-picked bodies hit the ground and Mr
Douglas keeps hitting the sheets. He does so in startlingly explicit detail
(for Hollywood) either with Miss Stone or with curvaceous police
psychiatrist Jeanne Tripplehorn.
When not being stoned or tripplehorned, Douglas occasionally does some
police work. Here Basic Instinct shows its edgy best. Douglas displays a
line in teeth-gritting angst worthy of father Kirk, and tension is spiced by
the frequency with which the sleuths are outsmarted by the suspect. For Miss
Stone discovers that by throwing nonchalant sexual candour at the Fuzz or by
wearing no knickers during interrogation - five stunned police heads keep
dipping whenever she uncrosses her legs - she can reduce the San Francisco
PD to drooling incompetence.
Yet for two hours the film asks 'Did she do the murders?' Since no
definitive video evidence of them exists, whereby a Californian court could
identify and acquit the culprit, Douglas must do much leg-work. And
wheel-work too: a night car chase, a series of Vertigo-like trailings over
San Francisco's rollercoaster hills, and a one-man shuttle service between
the city and Stone's glass-and-stone mansion teetering above the Pacific
whitecaps.
Sadly, all this preludial stylishness gives way to hundred-horse-power
hokum. Just when director Paul 'Robocop' Verhoeven has begun to prove that
he can direct human beings - with fine use of focus-pulling to point up
staged-in-depth conversation scenes - screenwriter Eszterhas piles on Mr V's
shoulders one implausible plot twist after another.
This is one of those films in which complete strangers turn out to have been
at school together, or to have shared a common interest in ice picks, or to
have been patrolling the same corridor when bloke X, Y or Z gets a sharp
instrument through the jugular. Finally, the whole overwrought mess is
cleared up, but not so tidily that a final 'twist' does not leave open the
possibility of a lucrative sequel.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9443</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAFYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Getting customers
taped - Philips has discovered at last the value of promotion, and is
belatedly looking for ways to win over the consumer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Next month, an eye-catching dome big enough to house 80 people will go on
the road in the UK, visiting shopping centres.
The dome is a promotional gimmick from Philips, not best known for its
clever marketing techniques. The 'Entechdome' as it is called, will carry
demonstration booths for products which the Dutch group hopes will become
hits in the consumer electronics market.
Philips is demonstrating a new-found eagerness to reach out to consumers.
After years at the mercy of its Japanese competitors, it has discovered that
good marketing can make a difference. It reckons that the travelling
demonstration booth - a technique borrowed from Japan - is a better way to
publicise its products than conventional advertising.
The change in attitude is reflected in 'Operation Centurion', which Jan
Timmer, Philips' president, says will 'call entrenched views and habits into
question' and shake the company out of its traditional complacency.
When the programme was introduced a year ago, Philips was in dire need of a
shake-up. Not only was it making heavy losses, it had become a symbol of
what was wrong with much of European industry - it had superior technology
but could not bring it successfully to the market.
Its experience with video cassette recorders is a case in point. Philips was
the first company to make VCRs commercially available. Yet its own machine,
called V2000, which it confidently brought to the market as technically
better than competing products, was a flop because of a shortage of
pre-recorded tapes in the V2000 format.
Meanwhile, the VHS format, which was widely judged to be technically
inferior, was skilfully marketed by the Japanese, and has become the de
facto industry standard.
Philips had a similar experience with Laservision, its laser disc player
which failed to win over consumers largely as a result of a distribution
fiasco and marketing failure. Philips did not bother to ensure that the
discs were sold with the players and, more often than not, salesmen could
not even tell consumers where to buy them.
While its Japanese competitors were busy brushing up their publicity acts,
selling products which were largely based on foreign technology, Philips
appeared to be sleeping unbothered in Eindhoven, the small Dutch town where
it is based.
But the group believes it has finally learnt its lesson. 'We've been through
all the problems now,' says a spokesman.
As a result, the group's philosophy has changed substantially, it says. No
longer expecting products to sell on superior technology alone, it is paying
more attention to consumer needs and preferences, industry trends and
product design.
It has set up a number of task forces charged with keeping up to date on
trends in different markets and developing a greater awareness of customers'
demands. Earlier this year it hosted a Customer Day when Timmer addressed
100,000 Philips employees throughout the world on the subject of customer
responsiveness.
The company's new approach, it says, is illustrated by its approach to the
digital compact cassette.
The cassette tapes, which will be available in September, were developed
after extensive market research showed a need for a product to replace
conventional audio tapes, which have seen sales fall in the past few years.
'You're actually starting from a marketing need rather than take a
technology and try to find a market for it,' says a spokesman.
Philips is also working to improve its corporate image and product design -
two areas which, it now accepts, have an impact on competitiveness.
Where it had - by its own admission  - been old-fashioned in product design,
it is now trying to revamp its image with products that are aesthetically
satisfying as well as of high technical quality.
Its new range of sophisticated audio and video products, called the Philips
Collection, have a simple and elegant look. Consumers' perception of
Philips' products will inevitably influence their view of Philips as a
corporation. But Philips has no illusions about the challenge it faces in
trying to revamp its image as a safe, if dull, company.
The company is looking on enviously at the clever marketing of Sony, which
is aiming electronic products at children with the catch-phrase 'My First
Sony'. Those children who receive their 'First Sony' will grow up with a
feeling of fondness for the Japanese manufacturer's products which they are
likely to retain as adults.
Philips hopes the purchase of Whittle, a US company which produces
educational software, will help it in a similar way by introducing
schoolchildren to Philips' products at an early stage.
Many observers believe the steps it is now taking to shake up the group have
been long overdue. Some still have their doubts as to whether the changes
have come in time for the group to regain competitiveness in an increasingly
difficult environment.
Many of the changes have been accepted practice at Japanese electronics
manufacturers for years. The success of those companies has been founded not
only on the quality of their products, but on skilful marketing.
If Japanese manufacturers are to be taken as a benchmark, Philips still has
a lot of catching up to do.
</TEXT>
