<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Warhol silkscreen sold for Dollars 2m: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SILKSCREEN creation by Andy Warhol depicting 210 Coca-Cola bottles massed
in seven lines sold for Dollars 2m (Pounds 1.17m) at Christie's in New York
on Tuesday night. The buyer was Thomas Ammann, a Zurich dealer.
The price was below Christie's optimistic estimate of up to Dollars 2.8m but
the fact that the work sold for such a comparatively high sum will reassure
the contemporary art market, which has suffered a two-year decline.
The sale of 68 lots totalled Dollars 11.26m and was 18 per cent unsold.
Christie's had turned away works it considered unsaleable and had insisted
on low reserves on lots it did accept. That ensured that the great majority
sold, often close to their low estimate.
The painting 'Untitled' by Cy Twombly went for Dollars 660,000, also below
estimate, but 'The Ocean' by Hans Hofmann was at the top of its forecast,
making Dollars 550,000.
Christie's also offered 25 works from the vast collection amassed by the
late Frederik Roos. All but one sold and new auction records were set for
two of the UK's leading contemporary sculptors, Tony Cragg and Barry
Flanagan.
Cragg's 'Three Cast Bottles', executed in 1988 and consisting of three vast
bronze canisters, sold for Dollars 99,000. Flanagan's 'Acrobats', showing
one of his famous hares balancing another, one of an edition of five, made
Dollars 93,500 slightly below the Dollars 100,000-Dollars 150,000 estimate.
</TEXT>
