<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Engineers urge better technology teaching
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EIGHT-POINT plan to promote technology teaching in schools was put
forward yesterday by the Engineering Council, Andrew Adonis writes.
The plan calls for a practical technology curriculum, based on the design
and manufacture of products and systems. It was written by Professor Alan
Smithers and Dr Pamela Robinson of Manchester University's education
department.
They say technology is poorly taught in schools in spite of its inclusion as
a core subject in the national curriculum. It is mainly concerned with
generalised problem solving without specific knowledge or practical
application.
Technology in the National Curriculum. Engineering Council, 10 Maltravers
Street, London WC2R 3ER. Free.
</TEXT>
