<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Smithfield site row resolved in court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE High Court yesterday resolved a centuries-old dispute between the Crown
and the Corporation of London concerning the Smithfield meat market in
favour of the corporation.
Mr Justice Hoffmann decided that the corporation owned a plot of land
between St Bartholomew's Hospital and the meat market in the north of the
City of London, the ownership of which has been contested for at least 350
years.
The dispute came to a head with an idea to move the meat market and
redevelop the Smithfield site. Moving the outdated market has been supported
by many tenants, concerned about the rising costs of remaining in the City,
and by alternative sites, such as New Covent Garden, the fruit and vegetable
market in Battersea.
Nevertheless the Corporation of London is determined to keep the meat market
in the City and it recently approved a Pounds 50m refurbishment programme to
comply with EC hygiene regulations.
The land was given to the City under a charter granted by Henry VI in 1444.
The High Court yesterday rejected the Crown's argument that it had retained
the ownership of the site under the 1638 charter.
The judge said that his reading of the charter was that it had given
Smithfield to the City, although for the limited use of holding markets and
fairs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
