<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Sharp drop in company failures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of companies passing into receivership and administration last
month dropped to the lowest level since December 1990, indicating possible
economic recovery, figures from accountancy firm Touche Ross showed
yesterday.
There were 389 receivership and administration appointments, according to
statistics derived from the London and Edinburgh Gazettes, compared with 527
in March and 441 in April last year.
Mr Christopher Morris, national director of corporate special services at
Touche Ross, said the decline was 'indicative' of support from banks towards
companies to which they have loaned money.
'This shows grounds for very cautious optimism,' he said. 'But one swallow
doesn't make a summer. We can be much clearer about a trend when we see the
May and June figures.'
The proportion of appointments for last month fell in London and the
south-east - further evidence that the effects of the recession, which
affected the region particularly badly, may be receding.
There were 30 per cent fewer appointments in the service sector than last
year, while there were sharp increases among wholesaling and distribution,
hotel and catering, and retail.
Mr Morris cautioned that business failures normally peak 18 months after the
bottom of a recession, partly because companies are unable to borrow money
as they expand. He said banks also sometimes called in receivers when they
saw the prospect of recovering the value of assets in companies to which
they had made loans.
However, his recent discussions with banks had disclosed that a decreasing
number of companies were in their 'intensive care' departments on the brink
of insolvency.
National Westminster was the bank that most commonly called in receivers and
administrators, with 97 appointments, followed by Barclays, Lloyds and
Midland. Bank of Scotland and the Royal Bank of Scotland also saw an
increase in appointments, which Touche Ross said reflected the increase in
failures in Scotland and the north.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand was awarded the largest number of appointments.
</TEXT>
