<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / World standard training targets to be promoted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is for the first time actively to support the promotion of
world-class targets for training.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary, in a letter to the chairmen
of the 82 Training and Enterprise Councils, said one of her main goals was
to raise awareness of national education and training targets.
The targets were initially set by the government but were abandoned by her
predecessor, Mr Michael Howard, who subsequently supported their voluntary
resurrection by the Confederation of British Industry. Mr Howard never said
they were one of his priorities.
Tecs will be responsible at local level for working towards the ambitious
targets, which include 80 per cent of young people reaching National
Vocational Qualifications (NVQs) at level two by 1996.
At present, 40 per cent achieve that level.
Resources will be provided at national level to promote the targets through
the National Training Task Force, a group of senior business leaders.
Mrs Shephard, in her letter to the 82 Tecs, outlined six goals that she
wanted to achieve in the Tec area. She will discuss them today when she
meets G10, the group of 10 chairmen of Tecs that represents the common
concerns of the movement to government.
G10 will present its own agenda for change at the meeting. Tecs are
concerned about various issues, including cuts in training budgets this year
which they claim may affect the quality of training.
Mrs Shephard will find it as difficult as her predecessor to fight for more
funds from the Treasury but Tecs believe she may take a more active approach
to promoting them.
Mrs Shepard's goals are: raising awareness of and securing commitments to
targets and securing their delivery; boosting the performance of Investors
in People; promotion of Tecs, defence of their budgets and clarification of
their relationship with government; and taking forward work on women's
issues.
</TEXT>
