<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Stores' view of married women 'outdated'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MARRIED WOMEN are finding themselves in a 'ghetto of part-time work' because
of managers' outdated assumptions about attitudes to jobs, according to
research by Lancaster University into employment in the retail sector.
While married women were thought to be reliable, loyal and flexible, it was
also assumed they would take time off because of their children and give
their husbands' careers precedence, the report found.
The majority of the supermarket employees studied were part-timers, and most
of those were married women.
Stores surveyed were Asda, J. Sainsbury, Marks and Spencer, Littlewoods and
EH Booth branches in the Lancaster area.
Employment Patterns in Contemporary Retailing. Roger Penn and Betty Wirth.
Department of Sociology, Lancaster University, LA1 4YL. Pounds 50.
</TEXT>
