<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Hammersmith in court over interest rate swaps
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHEMICAL Bank went to the High Court in London yesterday to claim Pounds
2.94m from the London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham in an action arising
from the interest rate swaps debacle.
The action is one of six lead cases selected from the multiplicity of
litigation between banks and local authorities that followed the House of
Lords ruling in January last year that all swaps deals were invalid because
they had been outside councils' legal powers.
The ruling left 80 banks facing losses of about Pounds 560m on swap
transactions with 130 councils. Their only recourse was to try to recover
about a quarter of their losses by suing councils for funds they earned by
writing swap contracts.
The lead cases were selected because they covered most of the points of law
arising from the Lords' ruling. The intention was that they would enable the
court to give guidance for the remaining cases and reduce litigation.
That intention was frustrated when four of the lead cases were settled out
of court.
The opening of Chemical Bank's claim was delayed for an hour by last-minute
discussions at the door of the court yesterday. Although they did not bear
immediate fruit, negotiations are continuing and it seems unlikely that the
case will run its estimated six weeks before terms are agreed.
Mr Richard Southwell QC, for Chemical Bank, told Mr Justice Hirst that the
bank, which had made two swaps contracts with Hammersmith in March 1988, had
assumed that local authorities entering into such transactions were hedging
their interest rate risks as end users.
It had been a considerable surprise to the bank to learn during the
litigation that led to the Lords' ruling that in its contracts with
Chemical, Hammersmith had been trading for profit in the swaps market and
acting as an intermediary between the bank and two rate-capped London
councils, Haringey and Camden.
If Chemical had known the true position, it would not have entered into the
contracts. Its policy in relation to swaps had been not to deal with
rate-capped councils.
Hammersmith now contended that intermediation could be justified as
amounting to the management of interest risks on its debts.
The council's defence was that Chemical had voluntarily assumed the risk
that the deals might prove to be beyond Hammersmith's powers and its
payments to the council had therefore been voluntary and irrecoverable.
Mr Southwell said it was a somewhat remarkable proposition that a bank would
voluntarily hand over large sums on such a basis.
He said Hammersmith had been party to 592 swaps deals involving a notional
Pounds 6bn. The potential loss to its ratepayers - had the Lords not ruled
such transactions void - would have been Pounds 194.2m.
The fact that Hammersmith had been saved from making good that loss could be
taken into account when considering whether it was reasonable for it to make
restitution to Chemical Bank, Mr Southwell said.
The hearing continues today.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
