<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Early independence urged for central banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL central banks of the European Community should be made
independent as soon as possible after the planned start in January 1994 of
stage two of European economic and monetary union, Mr Erik Hoffmeyer, the
Danish central bank governor, said yesterday.
Mr Hoffmeyer, who also chairs the committee of EC central bank governors,
said central bank independence would improve the co-ordination of EC
monetary policy, which is an important part of moves towards Emu.
He was giving the 11th annual Mais lecture at the City University Business
School in London. Mr Hoffmeyer was careful not to mention any EC central
bank by name. However, his remarks are likely to renew controversy about the
status of the Bank of England.
The Bank has made no secret about wanting more independence. The Treasury
acknowledges that the Bank will have to be independent if Britain moves with
other EC member states to full monetary union in the third and final stage
of Emu but the government has rejected earlier independence for the Bank
because monetary policy will remain a national responsibility and it says
that should be accountable to parliament.
Mr Hoffmeyer also criticised the Emu provisions of the Maastricht treaty for
being 'weaker than appropriate'.
He noted that monetary policy would be concentrated in the European System
of Central Banks once full Emu had been established, while governments would
very largely retain responsibility for fiscal policy.
As a result, a close relationship between the future European central
banking system and 12 national decision-making units in fields other than
monetary policy would be difficult.
Although Mr Hoffmeyer said the proposed Emu blueprint 'is definitely a
workable proposition', he expressed concern about how it would operate.
Lines of liaison would have to be created between the future EC monetary
authority and national economic policy-making units. Such lines would be
weaker than existing links at the national level.
'This implies that the system will be more vulnerable,' he warned. 'There
will be a higher risk that tensions will create dissatisfaction at the
national level.'
</TEXT>
