FT  07 MAY 92 / Ford moves 300 R&amp;D jobs to Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD's restructuring of its European research and development operations
will consolidate them at its sites at Dunton, Essex, and Merkenich, near
Cologne in Germany.
As part of the restructuring, announced earlier this week, about 300 jobs
are to be transferred from the UK to Germany and 20-30 jobs will be moved
from Germany to the UK. Ford's Aveley engineering site, about 10 miles from
Dunton, will close. Ford said there would be no compulsory redundancies.
In the UK, Ford plans to move by the end of 1994 1,200 engineering staff
from satellite operations at Aveley, Basildon and Dagenham in Essex to the
main R&amp;D site at Dunton, where the total workforce will be increased to
nearly 4,000.
In Germany, about 1,300 staff are to be relocated to Merkenich from other
sites in Cologne. That will bring the total at the site to about 3,300,
including the 300 jobs transferred from the UK.
The engineering reorganisation follows a far-reaching review by Ford of its
European automotive operations, which had a net loss last year (including
Jaguar) of Dollars 1.079bn (Pounds 605m) from a net profit of Dollars 145m
in 1990.
Mr John Oldfield, Ford of Europe vice-president for product programmes,
vehicle and design, said the company was seeking to bring together design
engineers and production engineers at one site so that 'we can achieve
better communication and teamwork and thereby generate significant quality
and efficiency gains'.
Ford says it has to spend 10 per cent to 15 per cent more than rival
carmakers in Europe to have its R&amp;D operations split between the UK and
Germany.
However, it emphasised its continuing commitment to research and development
in the UK yesterday.
The company said it had invested heavily at Dunton, where the site
facilities had a total capital value of about Pounds 500m. It was planning
capital investment totalling Pounds 40m at Dunton this year, having spent an
average of Pounds 20m a year there since 1985.
Research and development expenditure at Dunton totalled Pounds 236m last
year. Further jobs would be created at Dunton over the next three years.
</TEXT>
