FT  07 MAY 92 / The Queen's Speech: No-win situation for Labour seats -
Boundary changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE GOVERNMENT has angered Labour MPs
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
and risked possible protests from its own supporters - by accelerating a
review of parliamentary constituencies which would help the Conservative
party at the next general election.
The work of Boundary Commissions is seldom without controversy. Before the
1983 election, Mr Michael Foot, then Labour leader, tried to use the courts
to prevent the last review's implementation.
After the 1955 general election, when acrimoniously debated changes
undoubtably helped the Tories to increase their majority from 17 to 60,
there was a consensus that the period between reviews should be extended.
The four Boundary Commissions (for England, Wales, Scotland and Northern
Ireland) were to report every 10 to 15 years, rather than every three to
seven years.
Now Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, is risking charges of
'gerrymandering' by planning to reduce the period between reviews to eight
to 12 years. More immediately, the Boundary Commissions' work, begun in
1991, will be speeded up. A statutory deadline of the end of 1994 will allow
conclusions to be reached in 'good time' for the next election, the Home
Office said.
The work could probably be approved by parliament well before May 15 1997 -
the latest date for the next general election. The consensus at Westminster
is that the reviews will help the Tories to gain up to 20 seats.
The 1983 review, which formed the basis for last month's general election,
was drawn up on the 1976 electoral register. There have since been
substantial movements of population out of inner cities - traditionally
Labour's strongest areas. Mr John Major's constituency of Huntingdon, for
instance, has an electorate of 92,913 while Birmingham Sparkbrook, held by
Mr Roy Hattersley, Labour deputy leader, has only 51,677.
But experience suggests that that will not stop complaints from Tory MPs who
will lose out - such as in Chelsea which has an electorate of 42,371 - and
even name changes could lead to local complaints.
</TEXT>
