FT  07 MAY 92 / The Queen's Speech: Lottery angers pools workers - National
Lottery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
USDAW, the union representing workers in the pools industry, voted
unanimously yesterday to campaign against the introduction of a national
lottery, warning that it could cost thousands of jobs.
The long-awaited announcement of plans for a UK lottery was first made in
March by the then home secretary, Mr Kenneth Baker, after a determined
campaign by lobby groups and a number of prominent MPs and public figures.
The new Department of National Heritage, under Mr David Mellor, is charged
with setting up the lottery, with proceeds going to sport, arts, heritage,
charities and a new Millennium Fund to celebrate the year 2000. It is
estimated that the lottery could raise up to Pounds 1bn a year.
An independent board will be responsible for distribution of the proceeds,
with day-to-day management undertaken by the private sector under contract.
Mr Garfield Davies, Usdaw's general secretary, warned that the lottery could
have a serious impact on the pools industry. 'If the pools companies lose
business then our members lose their jobs,' he told the union's annual
conference in Blackpool. Delegates unanimously backed a motion to campaign
against the lottery and to call for support from the TUC and the Labour
party to block the bill.
The pools industry has an annual turnover of Pounds 700m and employs nearly
7,000 people, mainly in Liverpool, with some in Glasgow and Cardiff. It also
provides part-time employment for around 70,000 collectors around the
country.
Mr Malcolm Hughes, managing director of Vernons pools in Liverpool, said he
was sceptical of the claim by lottery supporters that there was plenty of
room in the market for both pools and a lottery.
He said the argument that annual spending on gambling in the UK is
considerably lower than in other countries did not take account of the true
size and diversity of the British gambling market.
Littlewoods, the biggest pools promoter, said it had been invited to make a
joint submission about the lottery with Vernons and Zetters pools to the
government by the beginning of June.
A spokesman said he did not rule out the possibility that the pools industry
might bid to run the lottery itself. 'We have raised billions of pounds over
many years and would certainly be the most qualified to run it,' he said.
Mr Denis Vaughan, the conductor, and head of the Lottery Promotion Company
which has been lobbying for a lottery for more than a year, said he was
delighted with the proposed format, but was anxious that the proceeds should
be used only for capital investment and endowments.
He dismissed the threat to the pools industry, saying that several thousand
jobs were already at risk from a possible move towards online computer
systems. He added that any job losses in that area would be more than offset
by the estimated 85,000 jobs that could be created through investment of
lottery proceeds.
</TEXT>
