<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / The Queen's Speech (Analysis): Generators hold key to size -
British Coal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRIVATISATION of British Coal was confirmed, although no timetable was
given. Civil servants said yesterday that the sale could take place by the
end of next year.
The announcement provoked fresh criticism from the Labour party and mining
communities, which believe that the controversial privatisation could lead
to the closure of more of British Coal's 49 remaining pits.
The government itself says that the size of the company will be determined
not by privatisation, but by the contracts agreeing how much coal British
Coal sells to the privatised electricity industry.
The Queen's Speech announcement will intensify pressure for these contracts
 -which represent the bulk of British Coal's revenue  - to be renegotiated
within the next few months. Existing contracts expire in March 1993.
But they are proving difficult to settle, because the two big electricity
generators, National Power and PowerGen, believe that British Coal's product
is too expensive.
The signs are that they are reluctant to buy more than 50m tonnes - possibly
falling to less over the life of the contract - compared with 65m in the old
contracts. But this would force British Coal to close more pits.
The electricity companies accept that the government will have to intervene
to forge a deal that is acceptable to all the parties concerned.
There are still many obstacles. The generators need to back their contracts
with sales to the regional electricity companies, which supply domestic
consumers. And the regional companies are waiting for the regulator to give
them a sign of the kind of deal he thinks would be fair on domestic
consumers. But the regulator said yesterday that the negotiations between
British Coal and the generators were a matter for them alone.
The government will have to resolve this issue before it can proceed with
the privatisation.
It can, however, proceed with legislation. The first stage, the Queen's
Speech indicated, would be a 'paving bill'. This bill, which is expected
shortly, will simply give British Coal powers to restructure itself in
preparation for the sale.
This will be followed, probably in the autumn, by the privatisation bill, or
Coal Bill, itself - clearing the way for the sale late in 1993.
A white paper, or policy document setting out the government's approach,
would precede the bill, said officials at the Department of Trade and
Industry, which is now responsible for energy.
So far, the government has given few clues about how the privatisation will
be structured, and ministers are still studying reports from N M Rothschild,
the merchant bank advising on the privatisation.
But a likely option is that the company will be split into two or more
parts, and sold to trade buyers.
One prospective buyer is the Union of Democratic Mineworkers (UDM), which,
with Lloyds Bank, is planning an employee-led buy-out of the company.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
