<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / The Queen's Speech: Realism steers PM's first agenda -
Reduced majority forces caution; Balance of controversial and populist
measures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Mr Neil Kinnock began the unfinished task of returning the Labour party
to the centre ground of British politics, somebody coined the phrase 'the
new realism'.
As Mr John Major set out yesterday the first legislative programme that he
can call his own, it was from the comfortable position of a leader who has
defied overwhelming odds to win a fourth term of office for the
Conservatives.
Yet as the prime minister's colleagues emerged from the pomp and ceremony of
the state opening of parliament, the most frequent comment was that his
programme's strength lay as much in its realism as its radicalism.
Mr Major has not abandoned reform in favour of consolidation - but he has
called a halt to the permanent revolution that proved the downfall of his
predecessor.
The programme for the next 18 months is radical in intent but realistic in
its ambitions. It is intended to reinforce his reputation for achieving
objectives by consensus rather than confrontation. It recognises that there
is a world outside Westminster, that legislation is not the sole instrument
of change.
That does not mean it will be free of controversy. The short bill due within
a few days to implement the treaties concluded at the Maastricht summit will
provoke great public soul-searching on the right of the Conservative party.
With his majority reduced to 21, Mr Major cannot afford more than a handful
of rebels.
Mr Major's promise to make the London government more responsive to
Scotland's aspirations may do little to cap the rising tide of support north
of the border for a new constitutional settlement.
Legislation to privatise British Coal and parts of British Rail may not be
free from political risk. The first will force a belated acknowledgement
from the government that many more pits will be forced to close. The second
will throw up more hidden horrors - and demands for public money - than
ministers are ready to accept.
The education bill planned for the autumn - designed to accelerate rapidly a
move towards grant-maintained status for most of the nation's schools - will
oblige the government to decide who or what will replace local authorities
in making strategic decisions about educational provision. Some parents will
welcome the return of selective education. Many more will not.
Mr Major has been careful to balance the difficult with the more instantly
populist. The National Lotteries Bill and legislation establishing the urban
regeneration agency and extending further rights  - including rents into
mortgages - to council tenants promise some good headlines.
Even without its present debilitating troubles over the party leadership,
Labour would find it hard to stir public anger against the bill promising a
further erosion of the power of trade unions.
The pace will be more sedate. Ministers are desperately anxious to counter
the impression that parliament could be twiddling its thumbs for much of the
18 months. They admit, though, that the programme has been designed to mesh
with the proposed reform of MPs' working hours and with the political
reality of a reduced majority.
The prime minister's public avowal yesterday of the existence of the Secret
Intelligence Service was designed to signal another break with the past by
promising a more open, relaxed, style of government. But there was a more
substantial shift.
Much of the legislation has been framed around Mr Major's belief in
individual choice, ownership and responsibility, but a single sentence
emphasises the core of his own prospectus. The government, it says, will
'give priority to improving public services through the Citizen's Charter
which will be at the centre of decision-making'.
Translated, that means that the welfare state is to be preserved but its
monolithic structure dismantled in favour of a more diverse pattern of
locally managed services.
Mr Major's ambition is to create a new consensus on the management of the
public sector to outflank Labour in the 1990s, in much the same way as his
party's approach to the economy left the Opposition stranded during the
1980s.
It may prove a powerful brand of realism.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
