<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Environment protection pledge from top banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COMMERCIAL banks in 23 countries, with combined assets of Dollars 1,500bn
(Pounds 847bn), made a formal commitment at the United Nations yesterday to
pursue common principles of environmental protection in all their
operations, writes Michael Littlejohns, UN Correspondent, in New York.
An official of National Westminster Bank of the UK, an initiator of this
first such collective effort by the industry, told a press conference that
environmental risk was now a vital element in credit risk.
The group of 31 signatories did not include any US or Japanese banks. But Dr
Mostafa Tolba, head of the UN environment programme, said Citibank had
expressed an interest.
The signatories included Germany's Commerzbank, Deutsche Bank and Dresdner
Bank; Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corp; Credit Suisse and Swiss Bank Corp;
Westpac of Australia, Royal Bank of Canada, and Royal Bank of Scotland.
Among the principles to which they have committed themselves is to ensure
'the best practices in environmental management, including energy
efficiency, recycling and waste minimisation.'
In a report published today the UN environment programme says that
ecological destruction has accelerated over the last 20 years, David
Lascelles reports from London.
Malnutrition has increased, the gap between rich and poor has widened and
children have become the worst victims of environmental mismanagement.
The report predicts that the world's population, currently 5.4bn, will rise
by a further 1bn by the end of the decade.
</TEXT>
