<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Brazil may request loan tranche delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER and CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRAZIL is likely to ask the International Monetary Fund to delay the second
tranche of a Dollars 2.1bn (Pounds 1.18bn) loan agreed earlier this year
because it has failed to meet some targets agreed with the Fund.
Mr Marcilio Marques Moreira, the economy minister, does not want to ask for
a waiver fearing this will reflect badly on Brazil, which has never
previously come anywhere near completing an IMF programme, according to an
Economy Ministry official.
Instead, Mr Moreira has apparently suggested to Mr Michel Camdessus,
managing director of the IMF, that the Dollars 250m payment due in May be
delayed to August, when a six-month review of the programme is due.
A collapse of the IMF standby programme would jeopardise the government's
economic reform plan and severely set back Brazil's negotiations with
creditor banks over a reduction in its foreign debt burden.
Mr Pedro Parente, planning secretary, said yesterday the economic programme
was going well. 'We have met the majority of targets but some have been
missed by a small margin.'
The problem lies on the fiscal side. As a result of falling tax revenues,
Brazil's economic team has been unable to bring the operating deficit under
control.
An operating deficit means government revenues have fallen short of
expenditures, including interest payments on its debt. Tax receipts fell by
14 per cent in real terms between January and March.
Under the terms of the accord signed in January, Brazil must produce a
primary surplus - which does not factor in interest payments  - of 3 per
cent of GDP by the end of this year.
'We already have a primary surplus but it's just not enough,' Mr Parente
said.
The economic team hopes that by delaying the second drawdown to August it
will gain time for an increase in tax revenues as a result of tax reforms
coming into effect this month.
The news is likely to increase instability in the Brazilian financial
markets. The central bank started intervening again in the gold and parallel
(black) dollar markets yesterday after a six-month absence.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
