<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / White House reviews domestic policy in wake of riots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bush administration is working on a new domestic policy programme to
deal with problems exposed by last week's violence in Los Angeles and to
counter criticism of its lack of ideas or action.
President George Bush, who left for Los Angeles last night for a two-day
visit to tour the riot-torn areas of the city and discuss reconstruction
measures with local officials and community leaders, said he wanted new
ideas, not a continuation of existing welfare programmes that have not
worked.
'It is far more important to give people a piece of the action than it is to
have the federal government simply dump largesse on them,' he said.
The Republican administration has been put on the defensive by criticism of
its neglect of urban problems during 11 years in the White House.
Party strategists had been hoping the violence in Los Angeles would rebound
to their advantage by heightening concerns over law and order, a traditional
Republican strength.
But the haste with which the administration has struggled to define a new
urban policy agenda reflects a worry that voters might blame the incumbent
president for failing to tackle the underlying social problems.
The debate over how best to respond to the Los Angeles riots has now erupted
into a partisan argument over the social safety net programmes of the 1960s
and 1970s.
Mr Bush's Democratic opponents had at first reacted cautiously to the riots,
fearful of the dangers of appearing to politicise the issue. Goaded by the
White House's attack on President Lyndon Johnson's 'Great Society'
programmes as the cause of today's urban problems, however, the Democrats
have punched back.
'When domestic problems become too visible to ignore, all this
administration does is look for somebody else to blame. First it was Jimmy
Carter, today it's Lyndon John-son. Who is next? Grover Cleveland, maybe?'
sneered Congressman David Bonior, Democratic whip in the House of
Representatives.
Mr Bush said yesterday that he did not want to 'play the blame game,' but
went on to reaffirm his criticism of Great Society programmes.
The administration has, however, shifted its position to emphasise that it
has increased spending on many of these programmes, such as Medicaid and
food stamps. 'Every single agency of the federal government is spending more
today than it was in 1980 and spending more than it was in 1988,' said Mr
Jack Kemp, secretary of housing and urban development.
Mr Kemp has long been the principal, and sometimes only, advocate within the
Bush cabinet of a more active domestic policy agenda, based on the
'empowerment' of poor people by helping them accumulate capital to buy homes
and start businesses.
His ideas are now likely to receive more enthusiastic support from the White
House as it seeks to play up Mr Bush's response to domestic problems.
The programmes have their critics, but the more devastating charge against
the president is that he is once again following a pattern he has perfected
in his three years in office: create a paper trail by proposing legislation,
do nothing to push for its enactment, then blame the Democratic- controlled
Congress for not passing it.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9501</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAECFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Task force looks to the private sector: How restoration
plans for Los Angeles offer a national model
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REBUILD Los Angeles, the task force created by Mayor Tom Bradley to take
charge of efforts to restore the riot-ravaged sections of the city, has set
its sights on creating a model for urban renewal throughout the US.
To be headed by Mr Peter Ueberroth, whose ties to Los Angeles stem from his
role as chairman of the 1984 Olympics organising committee, the task force
aims to revitalise the economically depressed parts of the city that
suffered most of last week's destruction.
Private-sector investment will be the key focus of the group. State and
local government funding is limited. California is already facing a Dollars
9bn (Pounds 5bn) budget deficit that can only be worsened by the problems in
Los Angeles, while the city is in the red to the tune of more than Dollars
800m.
'We will be out soliciting and wrenching out commitments from the private
sector,' says Mr Barry Sanders, a prominent international business lawyer
and counsel to the 'extra-governmental' non-profit group and a member of
Rebuild LA.
The task force will seek support from a wide range of businesses with
established ties to Los Angeles, including foreign as well as US companies.
'We intend to reach out to the people who have investments in this
community, or who ought to have, and that will include the British and the
Japanese,' says Mr Sanders.
'There are Japanese car plants in southern California, for example. We want
those companies to consider locating their next plant in Los Angeles. We
will try to get tax breaks and low-interest loans for large and small
businesses. We want them to go into this with a profit motive but at the
same time train and employ people from this community.'
But that will take time. 'By next week there are going to be people asking
'why hasn't this group done anything yet',' Mr Sanders predicts.
Therefore, the initial thrust of the task force will be to have a visible
impact on the hardest hit areas; to move ahead with demolition and clean up.
Already there are tentative plans involving a landscaping industry group
that has offered to plant grass and trees and install irrigation on
demolition sites. Although such parks might be only temporary, at least they
would improve the outlook of burnt-out neighbourhoods and, as Mr Sanders
puts it, 'show that something is being done'.
Longer-term efforts to attract investment to the area may prove difficult.
'The riots have dealt a serious blow to Los Angeles' image,' says Mr Jack
Kyser, chief economist at the Los Angeles Economic Development Corporation.
'Foreign investors are hesitant. They are reconsidering the risks' in light
of last week's events. Even US companies may 'sit back and assess whether
they want to pump money into an area already besieged by problems of riots
and earthquakes,' Mr Kyser adds.
The more immediate problem may be to stem the outflow of businesses leaving
the area, Mr Kyser suggests. In the past 18 months California lost half a
million jobs, according to a report issued last month by the Council on
California Competitiveness, chaired by Mr Ueberroth.
Others are more optimistic. 'Los Angeles is still a huge market that will
continue to attract investment,' argues Ms Mary Tuten, president of the Los
Angeles World Trade Centre.
'Some businesses will leave, but some will view this as a tremendous new
opportunity,' she predicts. 'In the long term you will see major
reconstruction.'
History would suggest otherwise. The Watts district of Los Angeles, the site
of race riots in the 1960s, has never recovered despite reconstruction
programmes.
'But they were driven by government spending and it did not work for
business reasons. This is going to be different, this community is going to
rebuild itself,' Ms Tuten maintains.
Rebuild LA, however, has also yet to win the trust of key segments of the
community. Black leaders, in particular, have voiced concerns that the task
force may not provide opportunities for their people.
'Whatever we do, it must be done with the full involvement of all segments
of the community,' Mr Sanders responds. 'This cannot be a bunch of downtown
businessmen imposing their ideas on the community,' he stresses.
People from all segments of the community will be invited to join the
governing board of the task force. 'They have been at sword point with one
another, but this is a chance for them to start over, to work together, if
anything good is to come out of all of this.'
Raising hopes are the commitments of Bank of America and smaller local banks
to offer preferential loan terms to people affected by the riot.
And other offers are 'flooding in' to Rebuild LA, says Mr Sanders. 'We have
to capture this rush of enthusiasm and hope.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
