   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AN ACCORD is due to be signed next week to repatriate tens of thousands of
Vietnamese boat people from Hong Kong, the UK Foreign Office said last
night, PA reports.
'We are on the verge of signing an agreement to return to Vietnam all
Vietnamese who arrived in Hong Kong before October 29, 1991, who, after
careful screening, are judged not to be refugees,' an FO spokesman said. The
accord covers over 20,432 people, and the operation could take three years.
An agreement already exists between Britain, Vietnam and Hong Kong for
repatriation of boat people - not deemed political refugees - who have
arrived since October 29.
The Hong Kong government yesterday disclosed that its budget surplus for
last year was HKDollars 6bn (Pounds 437m) higher than its provisional
figure, revealed in March, writes Simon Davies in Hong Kong.
This brings the budget surplus for 1991-1992 to over Dollars HK20bn.
Financial secretary Hamish MacLeod's statement on the windfall surplus was
accompanied by a concession on his budget: property rates would not rise
half a point to 6 per cent, as announced in the budget speech. The revenue
fall was 'roughly equivalent' to the windfall surplus.
