<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Riots force Lebanese premier to quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LARA MARLOWE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIRUT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR OMAR Karami, Lebanon's prime minister, and his 30-member cabinet resigned
yesterday after anti-government riots spread throughout the country.
The departure of the pro-Syrian premier after two days' civil unrest may
diminish Syria's influence in Lebanon and presage a more independent line
for his successor. It is the first time a Lebanese government has been
toppled by civil unrest since the country's civil war began in 1975.
Thousands of rioters took to the streets of Beirut and other Lebanese cities
early yesterday, brandishing sticks, shovels and pistols. Main roads were
blocked by heaps of blazing tyres. They smashed windows of government
offices, banks and shops and set up barricades of burning tyres. Two
teenagers were wounded when looters broke into Beirut's Arab Bank.
Rioting broke out on Tuesday after radio reports that the Lebanese pound had
collapsed to about LPounds 2,000 to the US dollar on the black market. But
violence subsided after Mr Karami's resignation was announced. 'I have
resigned to save the country,' the 57-year-old lawyer said after meeting
President Elias Hrawi.
The unrest has been sparked by Lebanon's economic crisis. For the first
time, Lebanese of all faiths, trade unionists, industrialists, bankers and
business people united in denunciation of the government and support for a
four-day general strike aimed at ending its mandate. The country's main
trade union is scheduled to reassess the strike today.
Because the Karami half-Christian, half-Moslem cabinet was installed under
Syrian supervision in December 1990, Lebanese rejection of the government
constitutes a growing resentment of Syria's hold over the country. The
Treaty of Brotherhood, Co-operation and Co-ordination signed with Syria last
May required Lebanon to link its economic, foreign and security policies
with those of Damascus, which keeps 40,000 troops in Lebanon.
The Syrian presence made the disarming of Lebanese militias possible, but in
recent months the Syrian embrace has choked public confidence and potential
foreign investors. Lebanese leaders have made no important decisions without
travelling to Damascus for 'consultations'. Mr Karami had sought Syrian
approval in a trip to the Syrian capital on Tuesday before he resigned.
Mr Karami, a Sunni Moslem, feuded openly with President Hrawi, a Maronite
Catholic. When Mr Hrawi pleaded with Syrian officials for permission to
replace Mr Karami in March, the Syrians refused, saying the Karami
government would have to oversee parliamentary elections soon.
A new cabinet is unlikely to be announced immediately. Officials in Beirut
suggested the decision may take a few days. Most popular candidates to
replace Mr Karami are Dr Selim El Hoss, the former prime minister, and Mr
Rafiq Hariri, the Lebanese-born Saudi millionaire.
Mr Hariri, a friend of the Saudi royal family, would appear well placed to
obtain Saudi economic aid for Lebanon. Both men have in recent days met
Syrian leaders in Damascus. Both are believed to have demanded greater
independence from Syria as a condition for becoming premier.
Syria's strategy regarding the crisis in Lebanon remains unclear. Many
rioters in southern Lebanon and Beirut were members of the Syrian-backed
Amal militia, and Syrian troops made no attempt to intervene during the
disturbances. Damascus could seek to impose an even closer ally as prime
minister, perhaps Gen Sami Khatib, interior minister, who was among those
who resigned yesterday.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9504</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAD9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Thais urge general to resign as prime minister
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER UNGPHAKORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 80,000 Thais surrounded parliament last night demanding that the
general who engineered a coup last year resign from his new position of
prime minister, police said.
As room for compromise between Gen Suchinda and his critics appeared to
dwindle, a group of academics appealed to the king to defuse the crisis by
dissolving parliament and calling another general election.
The Thai monarch would have the power to do that although he normally keeps
strictly above politics. Some observers say his intervention might be the
only way to break the deadlock.
Maj-Gen Chamlong Srimuang, former Bangkok governor and leader of one of the
opposition parties, continued the hunger strike he began on Monday. His
threat to die if Gen Suchinda does not resign has brought a number of
normally passive supporters out on to the street in front of parliament
where he is encamped, communicating only in writing.
He has predicted he will last only seven days, adding urgency to the crisis
which has caused panic on the stock market, whose share price index shed
43.36 points yesterday to close at 717.62. So far, the protests have been
peaceful, but observers fear there is a real danger of unrest if Gen
Suchinda remains prime minister, as is his constitutional right, and Maj-Gen
Chamlong dies.
Maj-Gen Chamlong, whose party took 32 of the 35 seats in Bangkok in the
March 22 general election, has gained popularity as a modest-living
politician. For either to back down would mean a serious loss of face and
reputation.
Opposition MPs boycotted the start of yesterday's debate when the prime
minister presented his first policy statement to parliament.
After that, they launched a barrage of criticism, questioning his ability to
fulfil promises to maintain democratic government. They accused him of
destroying democracy by engineering last year's coup d'etat and putting
himself and his military friends in key positions.
Members of the five-party coalition defended their constitutional right to
pick an outsider to be prime minister. Opposition MPs also addressed the
rally outside parliament where the more emotive speeches concentrated on Gen
Suchinda's earlier promise not to accept the premiership after this year's
election.
One MP said the planned 12-hour debate on the policy statement would be a
waste of time because Gen Suchinda's word was 'worthless'.
MPs, who were expecting to continue until midnight, were caught by surprise
when Gen Suchinda left parliament shortly before 6pm and the debate ended
abruptly without any explanation.
Some opposition MPs said the prime minister feared for his safety because of
the large numbers outside parliament.
The debate is scheduled to to continue today.
