FT  07 MAY 92 / Minimum bank guarantees proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALL depositors in EC banks should have a minimum Ecu15,000 (Pounds 10,500)
of their deposits guaranteed, the European Commission proposed yesterday.
The EC executive began work on the draft directive before the failure of the
Bank of Commerce and Credit International (BCCI) last year, but accelerated
its initiative after the scandal surrounding the bank's collapse.
The Commission suggests that bank customers should obtain their deposit
guarantee reimbursement within three months, in contrast to the much longer
period that many depositors with the Luxembourg-incorporated BCCI had to
wait. Responsibility for deposit insurance would switch from the host to the
home country of a bank. Mr Pierre Jaans, head of the Luxembourg Monetary
Institute, said this would not pose a problem for the duchy. Very few
Luxembourg-based banks, with the notable exception of BCCI, had branches
abroad.
Commission officials hope that EC governments will reach basic agreement on
the guarantee scheme under the UK presidency of the EC later this year. The
plan would require Greece and Portugal to institute deposit guarrantees for
the first time.
</TEXT>
