<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Bold action to transform Russia's 'wooden' rouble
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DIPLOMATS and businessmen in Moscow laugh about it. Russian enterprises are
worried by it. The Russian people are bewildered. But the government is
deadly serious about it.
The announcement on Tuesday that the Russian government would make the
rouble internally convertible this summer was a bold political statement
following the west's decision to provide a Dollars 6bn (Pounds 3.3bn)
stabilisation fund for the project.
Politically, it served notice to the battered Russian people that the
government would deliver its promise to transform the much-maligned 'wooden'
rouble into a real currency. It told the world Moscow was on track with its
bold plans to integrate Russia into the world economy. It warned the other
republics that they would have to play by tough budgetary, financial and
credit policy rules dictated by Moscow in order to continue using the
rouble.
The plan involves floating the rouble rate from July 1 and then defending it
up to 7.5 per cent either side of the fixed rate from August 1. Russian
officials admitted yesterday that many of the details had yet to be decided.
But the general idea, as explained Mr Andrei Vavilov, the first deputy
finance minister, is that if central bank intervention to defend the rouble
becomes excessive, the government responds by either raising interest rates
(to encourage people to convert dollars into roubles to earn interest) or by
devaluing.
Foreign diplomats and businessmen doubt whether the rate of Rbs80 a dollar
at which the goverment hoped to start defending the rouble was realistic
given the enormous demand for hard currency in Russia. But Mr Alexander
Potemkin, head of the Russian central bank's international department,
suggested that the rate might be as strong as Rbs50-Rbs60 with the moves
towards convertibility. He pointed to three factors: if exporters were
encouraged to sell hard currency earnings at a free market rate there would
be more supply than at present. Secondly, if the government's macro-economic
reforms stayed on track, the state-owned enterprises would have to become
more efficient. Thirdly, he said, the exchange rate would continue to
benefit from a physical shortage of roubles in the economy - yesterday the
rouble strengthened to Rbs128 per dollar from Rbs143.6 last week.
The reform will seek to create a single exchange rate, abolishing all other
rates such as the punitive 'commercial' rate at which exporters are obliged
to sell 40 per cent of their earnings to the state. This means doing away
with favourable exchange rates for certain types of state-owned enterprises
to purchase vital imports such as spare parts.
Competition from imports is unlikely, since imports would probably remain
too expensive for most Russian consumers for some time. But for foreign
companies contracting to sell goods to solvent buyers in Russia, the system
would be little changed. The Russian buyer converts roubles into currency
and sends it to the seller's bank account.
Another argument in favour of proceeding with convertibility is to encourage
badly-needed foreign investment - investors will be less afraid of making
mountains of roubles they cannot spend or convert to hard currency.
It remains to be seen if the supply of currency can be vastly increased.
Estimated annual export earnings are Dollars 25-Dollars 30bn, but only 2 per
cent of that is sold voluntarily by enterprises to the state, with many
avoiding the 40 per cent tax by keeping earnings in foreign bank accounts.
The government plans to open exchange points around the country to encourage
the ordinary citizen to part with dollars. It is unlikely that this will
attract currency in itself. But what may have more of a role will be a
proposed clampdown on the use of the dollar to buy and sell goods within
Russia - if it can be enforced.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
