<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Major cuts at secrecy by naming MI6 chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday foreshadowed a significant shift towards more open
government with a pledge to provide a legal framework for Britain's Secret
Intelligence Service.
His public acknowledgement of the existence of the SIS, the first by any
prime minister since the forerunner of the country's spy establishment was
set up in 1909, came as he presented his legislative programme in the
Queen's Speech.
The programme includes bills to pave the way for the privatisation of
British Coal and parts of British Rail, as well as to implement the
Maastricht treaties on European union. A finance bill, due within the next
10 days, will reintroduce those measures in Mr Norman Lamont's Budget which
were dropped because of the general election.
Speaking in the House of Commons, Mr Major said one of his most immediate
aims was 'to sweep away some of the cobwebs of secrecy which needlessly veil
too much of government business'.
He confirmed that among the first steps would be publication of the details
of the cabinet committees which make most important government decisions and
of the guidance issued to ministers on their personal financial interests.
Mr William Waldegrave, chancellor of the duchy of Lancaster, had been asked
to review other areas where 'excessive secrecy' might be removed.
The prime minister then told MPs that it was time to acknowledge officially
the existence of the SIS, commonly known as MI6. It was responsible for
foreign intelligence designed to support the government's foreign, defence,
security and economic policies.
He confirmed that the service works directly to the foreign secretary and
the prime minister, and that its current chief is Sir Colin McColl. Sir
Colin is listed in reference books as a senior official at the Foreign
Office.
MI5, the domestic counterpart of the SIS, was given a legal basis in 1989.
This year, Mr Major broke with tradition by making public the appointment of
Mrs Stella Rimmington as its director. Between them the two services have a
budget of Pounds 185m for the current financial year.
Mr Major insisted that the government would continue to refuse to comment on
the activities of the two services because of the risk that would bring to
their effectiveness and staff.
Senior Whitehall officials said this meant that the legislation to place the
SIS on a statutory basis was unlikely to subject it to direct scrutiny by
MPs. Instead the legislation is expected to be modelled on that introduced
for MI5, which provided for limited rights of redress by the public.
Mr Major's first legislative programme as an elected prime minister included
a range of bills designed to enhance individual choice and ownership, and to
improve the responsiveness to public sector services.
Among the most significant measures in a parliamentary session which will
last until the autumn of 1993 are bills to push ahead with the government's
education reforms, to tighten the law on asylum and to set up an urban
regeneration agency.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9518</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / OFT blow for Lloyds' plan to buy Midland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFICE of Fair Trading plans to recommend that the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission examine Lloyds Bank's proposal to buy Midland.
It does not, however, believe the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation
bid for Midland raises competition issues worthy of extended investigation.
The disclosure of the OFT's view by a senior government official will come
as a blow to Lloyds. It has been hoping that both its plan and Hongkong
Bank's bid would be examined by the MMC. Lloyds has said it would only
convert its takeover plan into a fully fledged bid if the MMC looked at the
takeover approaches of both banks.
The official stressed that the OFT had not made a final decision. By the end
of the week it should have submissions from all three banks on the
competitive issues raised by the takeover proposals. It will review these
documents next week and make a recommendation to Mr Michael Heseltine, trade
and industry secretary.
However, OFT officials have had meetings with executives of all three banks
and they have already assessed the effect on banking markets of both
takeover proposals. The OFT believes that the Lloyds' approach may have a
detrimental effect on competition in small business loans.
The OFT decision on Lloyds and Hongkong Bank will be the last one taken by
the director-general, Sir Gordon Borrie, who retires in June. Mr Heseltine
has not instructed Sir Gordon to review the takeover by any other criteria
than those he has been using for the past eight years which give the highest
priority to competitive issues.
In the Hongkong Bank case, the OFT believes it will not have the leading
role in making a recommendation on whether there is a threat to competition.
It has been told by DG4, the European Community's competition authority,
that jurisdiction over the Hongkong Bank takeover offer is likely to rest
with DG4. A decision is expected in the coming week.
The government official said the question of which body has jurisdiction on
the competition question may be less important than Lloyds believes. If the
OFT were to have jurisdiction, the official said, it would not recommend
that the Hongkong Bank bid was scrutinised by the MMC.
Mr Heseltine does not have to follow the recommendation of the OFT. But in
the past 16 years, Mr Heseltine's predecessors have done the opposite of
what the OFT has recommended on only 14 occasions. On just two occasions
have they ordered an MMC inquiry when the OFT recommended against one.
Mr Heseltine could ask the MMC to investigate whether a Hongkong Bank
takeover of Midland would be against the public interest for reasons other
than competitive ones. But this would not be easy for him.
If the EC decides it has jurisdiction on the competitive aspect of the
Hongkong Bank bid, Mr Heseltine could ask for a separate UK review of
whether the takeover was a threat to Midland's depositors.
However, he would have difficulty making such a request, because the Bank of
England has already said it does not believe Hongkong Bank's bid would put
Midland's depositors at risk.
Mr Heseltine could also argue, under Article 9, that the Hongkong Bank bid
raises general issues of national concern and should therefore be reviewed
in the UK. However, the European Commission has to date been reluctant to
comply with requests for national reviews of takeovers under Article 9.
Lloyds is putting pressure on Mr Heseltine not to deprive Midland
shareholders of its takeover proposal by making a reference.
However, the government official hinted this argument was unlikely to
influence the government. Lloyds' condition that the bid will only be made
if there is no MMC reference is self-imposed, he pointed out, and can
therefore be dropped.
</TEXT>
