<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / UK shares reach record high as hopes of recovery rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARE PRICES in London closed at record levels last night on the back of
optimism about recovery prospects and signs that sterling was holding on to
its recent gains.
The FT-SE 100 index of leading shares gained 36.5 at 2,698.7 as investors
took heart from Tuesday's half-point cut in interest rates to 10 per cent.
The reduction in borrowing costs is expected to lead to a gradual uplift in
the retail and housing markets - developments seen as helping a sustained
revival from the recession that started around mid-1990.
Sterling was unchanged in London against a stronger D-Mark, closing at
DM2.925. That underlined the perception of many investors that, in spite of
the cut in UK rates, sterling is unlikely to encounter serious strain within
the European exchange rate mechanism over the next few weeks. The currency
was close to its London levels in late New York trading.
The possibility, viewed as remote by many economists, that the Bundesbank
council might decide to increase German rates at its regular meeting today
led to some switching of funds into the D-Mark. This caused the dollar to
drop 1 pfennig to DM1.6305 in London. It closed at DM1.6287 in New York.
But the buying pressure buoying the D-Mark was not enough to disturb
sterling's position within 3 pfennigs of its DM2.95 central ERM rate.
Against the dollar, the pound gained more than 1 cent in London to Dollars
1.7945. It closed at Dollars 1.7975 in New York.
The rise in share prices pushed the FT-SE index above its last closing high
of 2,683.7, reached eight months ago. The rise contrasted to Tuesday's tepid
stock market reaction to the UK's first base rate cut since September.
Mr Richard Jeffrey, head of economics research at stockbroker Charterhouse
Tilney, said investors had needed time to tell whether the rate cut would
damage sterling. 'If you are confident an upturn is really going to happen,
the stock market looks 10 per cent undervalued.'
Lex, Page 24
London stocks, Page 44
