<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (15): The nuts and bolts - Engineering
is still the motor of the economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
    By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY PEOPLE still tend to think of Switzerland as a country of solid banks,
delightful tourist retreats and quaint watchmakers.
In fact, the country's outsize engineering industry is the motor of the
Swiss economy. With 3,000 companies and a labour force of 370,000, it dwarfs
the banking sector, and its exports of SFr39.3bn last year were worth six
times those of the watchmakers.
By the late 1980s, the Swiss engineering industry had become so large that
it was having difficulty keeping up with its customers' demands. In
particular, it was suffering from skilled labour shortages, and chafing at
Switzerland's tough restrictions on immigrant workers.
In the past year, however, the industry's concerns have changed dramatically
as, like its counterparts elsewhere in the world, it has been hit by the
downturn in capital spending in many of its important markets.
While Asea Brown Boveri (ABB), by far the biggest group in the sector,
managed to eke out a 2 per cent improvement in pre-tax profits last year,
few others did as well.
Von Roll, the steel and machinery group, and Rieter, the textile machinery
group, slumped into loss, while others, such as Sulzer Brothers, the pumps
and textile machinery group, George Fischer, the machine tool builder, and
Schindler, the lifts and rolling stock maker, reported sharp declines in
their profits.
At the annual press conference in February of the Swiss Association of
Machinery Manufacturers (VSM), concern about labour and skill shortages gave
way to shock at the soaring jobless rate. By the end of 1991, the number of
full-time unemployed in the sector had nearly tripled to 5,700 compared to
the end of 1990, and short-time working, which was virtually non-existent in
the late 1980s, was affecting 21,000.
Hardly a week goes by without announcements of closures and redundancies.
Perhaps the most significant last month was the closure by Sulzer Brothers
of its large-piece grey iron foundry at Oberwinterthur. This was the last
remaining large-scale iron foundry in the country, and even though its
demise will eliminate only 520 jobs, it was a chilling indicator of how
tough things have become in some industry sectors.
Sulzer pointed out that the foundry's main clients were the machine tool and
textile machinery industries and their combined orders tumbled from 10.7m
tonnes in 1989 to only 5.3m tonnes last year.
Surprisingly, output and order statistics do not yet fully reflect the agony
that is being felt in many engineering sectors. Last year, new orders of 200
leading companies surveyed by the VSM were down only 1.4 per cent and their
combined sales advanced a healthy 11.3 per cent to SFr26.1bn. Total industry
exports were up 0.3 per cent.
However, other figures are more revealing. The combined backlog of 260
companies in a VSM study dropped from 6.1 months in the fourth quarter of
1990 to 5.3 months in the fourth quarter of last year, the lowest level in
10 years. Capacity utilisation also fell from a record 91.5 per cent in 1990
to a seven-year low of 85 per cent last year.
The hardest hit was textile machinery, which is the second largest sector in
the industry after machine tools. Textile machine sales were down nearly 18
per cent, as clothing and home furnishings makers turned cautious.
The machine tool industry's sales tumbled 11 per cent to SFr3.6bn, hurt by
the virtual drying up of eastern European markets. Sales of electrical and
precision equipment eased 2 per cent, but electronic industries' revenues
were up, thanks in part to major modernisation programmes of the Swiss
telecoms establishment.
As for the outlook, there is little optimism for the near term. Mr Martin
Erb, executive director of the VSM, noted in February that the slight upturn
in orders in the fourth quarter of last year was due to a single large order
received by ABB to build a power station in Indonesia.
In the first quarter of this year, exports were up a surprisingly healthy 7
per cent by value, but VSM officials cautioned against reading this as an
indication that there will be much improvement in the year as a whole.
For one thing, the export figure is flattered by the sharp decline in the
value of the Swiss franc in the past year. For another, the important
machine tool sector is still sagging, with exports down 21 per cent.
Another negative factor is that domestic demand is likely to be softer this
year than last because of budget constraints at all levels of government.
'It is still difficult to tell if we will even achieve the same level of
sales this year as last year,' a VSM official says gloomily.
This sharp change in the industry's health has heightened its anxiety about
Switzerland's position in Europe and the world. Nearly two-thirds of all its
exports go to EC countries and over 70 per cent go to the 18 west European
countries.
The VSM has long officially supported the idea of Switzerland joining the
European Community and major international organisations, and this year
added its formal endorsement for the proposal to join the European Economic
Area.
Mr Erb said that the engineering industry, with its record exports to the
EC, 'provided further proof of the absolute necessity of free access to the
largest internal market in the world'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9524</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (14): Wine goes upmarket - The
country's last cottage industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE mid-1980s Swiss winemakers awoke from a slumber worthy of Rip van
Winkle to find the world utterly changed. Shifting consumer tastes and a
domestic wine glut are forcing the country's last remaining cottage industry
to become more efficient, professional and outward-looking.
As a consequence, thousands of small vineyard owners are expected to bow out
over the next few years.
Traditionally, Switzerland has produced eminently quaffable but unremarkable
wines with little staying power. About 60 per cent of its production, 140m
litres last year, is white wine, mostly from the Chasselas grape. The
dominant red grapes are Pinot Noir, Gamay and Merlot.
Cushioned by high government subsidies and tight restrictions on competing
imports, especially for white wine, Swiss growers had little need to worry
about quality in what was essentially a captive market. For white wine,
domestic production meets nine-tenths of consumption, against about
one-third for red wine. Winemakers had little interest in exporting abroad
and no incentive to do so.
Things changed abruptly 10 years ago when a string of bumper harvests from
1982 created Switzerland's very own wine lake, one big Valais winery went to
the wall, and the federal government was forced to implement a costly
surplus disposal programme.
In 1986, the mountain canton of Valais, Switzerland's main wine-producing
area, became the first to impose stringent measures to rein back production
and boost wine quality by restricting the quantity of grapes left to grow on
the vines. Switzerland's first 'Appellation d'Origine Controlee' (AOC), wine
conforming to strict quality standards, was introduced in 1987, also in the
Valais.
The Swiss parliament is currently discussing a draft federal decree that
will restrain production and improve wine quality nationwide. At the
beginning of this year the government scrapped import quotas for bulk
deliveries of red wine, and it plans further liberalisation of wine imports
in the light of the international trade talks under way in Geneva. Earlier
government proposals to regulate wine production were thrown out by voters
two years ago on the grounds that they did not go far enough to eliminate
barriers to imports.
The draft decree also classifies wines into three quality groups (with
'appellation d'origine', 'indication de provenance' and 'vins ordinaires').
This, too, is a big break with the past. In the Valais, for instance, most
small growers sold their grapes to big wine distributors to be bottled
simply under the generic names of Fendant (Chasselas), Johannisberg
(Sylvaner) or Dole (Pinot Noir and Gamay).
The effects on the structure of the Swiss wine industry will be
far-reaching. Mr Francois Cordonnier, president of the Valais Federation of
wine growers, thinks the number of vineyard keepers in the canton could
shrink from 22,000 to just 4,000 over the next decade. One in five working
adults has a vineyard, often no bigger than a tennis court, and 90 per cent
of holdings are worked part-time.
Equally revolutionary, the Swiss are turning their minds to markets abroad,
and not just for offloading the odd surplus. Switzerland now exports under
2m bottles of wine a year, a tiny 1 per cent of production which the
Association of Swiss Wine Exporters in Lausanne would like to see boosted to
5 or even 10 per cent in the longer term.
The problem with exporting more, as Swiss growers concede, is that
Switzerland has few distinctive wines, and even fewer distinguished ones, to
entice sophisticated overseas palates. Yet with production costs in
Switzerland two to four times those elsewhere in Europe, Swiss winemakers
have little choice but to follow their compatriots in watchmaking, machine
tools and other export industries in moving resolutely upmarket.
The industry is split on how best to do this. Some growers in
French-speaking Switzerland, which produces 80 per cent of the country's
wine, propose abandoning the ubiquitous Chasselas grape in favour of more
reliable varieties such as Chardonnay or Sauvignon Blanc. Others say the
Chasselas gives Swiss wine its distinctiveness and advocate research to
improve the grape's wine-making qualities.
Mr Christophe Von Ritter, secretary-general of the wine exporters'
association, thinks prospects are good for wines made from some of
Switzerland's unique indigenous grape varieties, which could sell not only
on quality but also on curiosity value. But, despite the association's best
endeavours, exporting is likely to remain a marginal pastime for growers
while subsidies and protection continue to provide easier rewards in the
domestic market.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9525</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (13): The prospect of a Swatch car -
After the rescue of the watchmaking industry, there are more ambitious plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ON APRIL 1, the French language daily, Le Nouveau Quotidien, published an
interview with Mr Nicolas Hayek, boss of SMH, the watchmaking company best
known for the Swatch plastic watch. Referring to the current political row
over the Swiss government's intended purchase of 34 US fighter planes, Mr
Hayek said Switzerland should develop its own aeroplanes. Aircraft design
needed rethinking to produce a high-performance, low cost, environmentally
friendly machine.
Of course, the 'Swatch fighter' was a spoof. But Mr Hayek's real-life
project to build a Swatch car has met much the same kind of amused
disbelief. In proving the scoffers wrong, he hopes to demonstrate a personal
conviction that Europe, even high-cost Switzerland, need not surrender its
manufacturing base to the Far East.
This conviction underpinned Mr Hayek's rescue plan for the Swiss watchmaking
industry in the early 1980s when it was in danger of obliteration by
Japanese competition.
An engineering consultant who had already built up a successful business,
Hayek Engineering, Mr Hayek was brought in by the banks to guide the
troubled merger of SSIH and Asuag, the two biggest watchmakers, to form SMH
(Societe Suisse de Microelectronique et d'Horlogerie) in 1984.
Rejecting the conventional wisdom that Switzerland should retreat to the
luxury end of the watch market, he argued that a thriving industry needed
the mass market to provide the impulsion for cost control, technological
development and marketing. The Swatch, which first appeared in 1982, was to
spearhead recapture of this market from the Japanese.
Greeted sceptically at the time, the Swatch has become a classic success
story. Last month, the 100 millionth Swatch came off the production line -
making it the biggest selling watch in history. Early Swatches are
collectors' items, fetching thousands of dollars at auction and contemporary
Swatch variants like the chronograph are the object of a flourishing black
market trade.
Stylish, constantly changing designs, a careful distribution policy and
clever marketing have kept the Swatch boom going. But at its heart rests the
original Swatch innovation - a big cut in the number of watch parts and a
way of assembling them in one operation, allowing fully automated production
for the first time. Today, the basic Swatch still sells for its original
price of SFr50.
Sales of Swatches, which are all produced in Switzerland, topped 17m in
1991. SMH plans output of 25-30m this year, doubling to 50m within five
years, including variants such as the Pop Swatch, chronograph and the Scuba
diving watch. A Swatch automatic, with a self-winding mechanism, will be
launched later in 1992.
Swatch accounts for something over half SMH's finished watch output of 30m
last year and about a quarter of its SFr2.37bn sales. But production and
marketing skills honed on the Swatch have helped to revitalise SMH's
higher-priced watch brands, such as Omega, Longines, Rado and Tissot.
SMH is now a world leader in luxury watches, which are estimated to
contribute over half its profits, though analysts think it may be losing
money in the highly competitive medium-priced market.
The company has also pursued an ambitious strategy of vertical integration,
manufacturing its own components including state-of-the-art microchips and
batteries. These, and some 50m watch movements produced by SMH last year,
are sold for assembly by other manufacturers in Switzerland and elsewhere.
Within a decade, SMH has become the world's most profitable watch company,
according to James Capel, the London stockbrokers, and sales by value are
poised to overtake Seiko of Japan within five years. Profits have risen
steadily, jumping by a third last year to SFr252m, and in 1992 the company
is expected to have cash in hand after repayment of debt.
Taking watches and movements together, SMH accounts for some three-quarters
of total Swiss production (about 13 per cent of the world total) and about a
third of Swiss sales. The rest is accounted for by mainly top-of-the-range
watchmakers such as Rolex and Patek Philippe, whose dominance in the luxury
market gives Switzerland over half the total world watch sales by value.
Mr Hayek, who with a group of investors, bought out the banks' controlling
shareholding in 1985, says SMH is and will remain primarily a watch company.
But he believes other, more dynamic markets are ripe for the Swatch formula
of technological innovation combined with skilful design at a competitive
price, that can capitalise on the company's experience with micro-electronic
and micro-mechanical devices. About 5 per cent of SMH's sales are currently
outside the watch sector, mostly accounted for by the Swatch twinphone (a
dual handset model) in the US and Europe.
However, initial problems with telephone type approval, marketing and
distribution have now persuaded SMH to opt for tie-ups with established
telecommunications companies. Mr Hayek plans to announce in June a deal with
a major telecommunications manufacturer to produce the twinphone and the
cordless, cellular and fax telephones SMH already has on the stocks. SMH
hopes to produce 1m twinphones this year - assembled in south-east Asia -
and in March launched the Swatchpager, a paging watch, in the US in
partnership with BellSouth.
More ambitiously still, SMH and Volkswagen, the German car maker, last year
set up a joint venture to develop, manufacture and distribute the
Swatchmobile, an ecological car intended to exploit the huge potential
market for non-polluting vehicles, especially in the US. The rewards could
be enormous for a car with the right price-performance combination, which
has so far eluded the big car makers.
A Swatchmobile prototype is already under test, and the two companies are
hoping to start production in 1994 for launch in 1995. The details are a
closely guarded secret but the car will have an electric or hybrid
petrol-electric motor and, Mr Hayek claims, the performance and safety
features of a normal petrol-driven model.
Though the project seems fanciful, SMH is not taking too big a risk. VW is
thought likely to put up most of the funds needed for the manufacturing
operation, with SMH taking a royalty fee on sales and perhaps an equity
stake. The companies, which are sharing development costs of around Dollars
20m, are planning production of 100,000 cars a year if the launch goes well.
Analysts concede that Mr Hayek's track record makes it difficult to dismiss
the idea out of hand. 'If VW and SMH can bring a car to market that is
cheap, clean, handy and comfortable, it could be a nice surprise,' says Mr
Roland Leutenegger of Bank Julius Baer in Zurich.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9526</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (12): A radical package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTOR-FRIENDLY is the great buzz-word among Swiss quoted companies these
days.
They are all rushing to publish more - and more revealing  - information
about their activities and trying to make their shares more attractive to
investors, including foreigners.
In part, they are doing this to get their share prices up, so they can raise
capital on better terms. But for the biggest companies, such as Nestle and
Roche, the hard fact is that the Swiss capital market can no longer meet
their needs, so they have no choice but to appeal to foreign investors.
If there were an award for the Swiss company that has done the most in the
shortest time to become investor-friendly, it would undoubtedly go to Holvis
Holzstoff, formerly Holzstoff, a long-established, medium-sized group
(SFr823m consolidated sales last year).
Holvis has transformed itself in the past two years from a boring pulp and
paper maker to a world leading producer of the non-woven polymer-based
material for disposable nappies and dozens of other trendy products.
Even the group's name is new, created to help it shed its identification
with paper, which accounted for only 14.5 per cent of sales last year.
Holvis used to be one of the most secretive Swiss companies. 'It was very
conservative; there was almost no information,' Mr Rudolf Wenger, finance
director, says. And when it finally decided last year to change its spots,
it got off to a very bad start.
Like many others before it, Holvis proposed eliminating restrictions on
foreigners owning its registered shares but installing in its place a
general restriction on anyone registering more than a 2 per cent stake. The
idea was to prevent someone from secretly accumulating a bid stake, a move
which is still possible in Switzerland because there is, in effect, no
takeover code.
To their surprise, Holzstoff directors ran into a barrage of criticism from
Swiss institutional investors. 'The culture around us had changed,' says Mr
Pedro Reiser, chief executive, ruefully.
So the directors went back to the drawing board, and emerged in early March
this year with the most radical package of proposals yet advanced by a Swiss
quoted company.
The proposals, which were to be approved at yesterday's annual general
meeting, included the consolidation of capital into a single class of
registered shares with no restriction on ownership, by numbers or
nationality.
In addition, the shares would be split 10 for one to make their price more
accessible to small shareholders.
In terms of disclosure, the group has also led the way, being one of the
first Swiss companies to publish a breakdown of its profits last year by
division. And the directors promise that this year's financial statements
will be published in accordance with international accounting standards
(IAS).
Mr Reiser says that one of the group's objectives in liberalising was to
improve the rating on its shares so that it could raise capital more cheaply
in the future. It spent Dollars 175m in 1990 buying the non-woven assets of
the US paper group, James River, and might need to return to the capital
markets in the future. Since the announcement of the capital restructuring
in early March, the group's bearer shares have risen from SFr5,040 to
SFr5,600.
Mr Wenger adds: 'Management has started to understand that shareholders are
an important part of a company's life. In Switzerland, that has been
neglected.'
However, the group has taken a risk by going all the way, because it is now
vulnerable to a surprise hostile takeover bid. Several other Swiss
companies, including Nestle and Sulzer, intend to liberalise their capital
structures this year. But they have decided to maintain a limit on the
proportion of share capital that any individual may register until a proper
takeover code is in place in Switzerland.
Mr Reiser acknowledges the problem, but he says the rise in the market
valuation of the group's shares since the announcement should drive away the
opportunistic bidder.
'Even if we maintained restrictions, we could not stop a determined
strategic bidder. We could only delay him,' he says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9527</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (10): The mobilisation of a diehard
patriot - Profile: Christoph Blocher
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TO SOME, he is a right-wing eccentric, to others he is the conscience of the
nation, the quintessential Swiss patriot.
Christoph Blocher is a colonel in the Swiss army, a member of the federal
parliament for the conservative People's Party and executive chairman of a
successful speciality chemical company.
He also led the forces that six years ago successfully opposed the proposal
that Switzerland join the United Nations. And now he is in the forefront of
efforts to block the federal government's plans to take the country into the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the European Community.
If he were British, he would undoubtedly be a diehard Thatcherite. He
distrusts bureaucrats and believes passionately that less is better when it
comes to governments.
He is also suspicious of corporate bureaucrats, and prefers to pay out big
dividends to Ems-Chemie shareholders rather than use the company's strong
cash flow for risky diversification projects or acquisitions.
Next week, the Swiss are to vote in a referendum on joining the IMF and
early next year they will have to decide whether or not to ratify the
so-called European Economic Area (EEA) treaty, which would bring the six
countries of the European Free Trade Area (Efta) closer to joining the EC.
Mr Blocher is already mobilised for these campaigns, with beguiling negative
arguments at the ready.
On the IMF and World Bank, as on the UN, he h a s no particular complaints,
but he thinks Switzerland is better off as a non-member. He insists that the
country is not isolationist; it pays to support many of these organisations'
projects and agencies, but it also reserves the right not to participate if
it thinks a particular project is ill-conceived.
'If we were a member, we would have only one vote. We are a little country,
so no one would listen to us. So it is better for us to be on the outside
and decide on a case-by-case basis. I think also that our views are sought
more than they would be if we were members.'
Mr Blocher also resents the enthusiasm of what he calls 'official Bern' for
joining these organisations. 'They say we must participate, that we must be
in solidarity with other countries, but they really just want to be in the
club so they can tell us, the people, that the club has decided something
and there is nothing we can do about it. They like power, but Swiss
democracy is against power.'
His complaints against the EC are more numerous. Indeed, Mr Blocher opposes
the EEA because he believes it is designed as a halfway house towards full
EC membership. 'The government's policy is that the EEA is a first step
towards EC membership. You cannot find many people in Switzerland who are
for the EEA and against the EC. If anyone says he likes the EEA but not the
EC, he is saying it for tactical reasons.'
The basic problem with the EC, he says, is that it is an 'intellectual
construction'. Viewing it with Swiss eyes, it appears very centralised,
undemocratic and unfederal. 'We have a lot of difficulty finding out what
officials in Bern are doing with our money. Brussels would be much worse.'
He says the whole idea of a united Europe is fundamentally flawed. Europe is
composed of several states with substantial differences in history, culture,
language and economic and political systems. Several attempts have been made
to unify it, but all have failed, and the EC will fail too. 'I am sure that
it cannot function.'
The current tensions between Germany and other countries in the European
Monetary System (EMS) illustrate the difficulties. 'It is not that Germany
has made a mistake or France or Britain; the mistake is having one system.'
Mr Blocher thinks it is better to have competition between governments to
prevent any one of them from getting too powerful or arrogant.
He acknowledges that if it turns out that Switzerland is the only western
European country to refuse to join the EC, Brussels might get tough. 'But
they need Switzerland, too. This is not a new problem for us, and we have
been in much more dangerous positions in the past than we are today.
'The EC wants to export. We are their largest single market after the US and
they sell more to us than we sell to them.'
Mr Blocher is not distressed either by the prospect of 'missing the train'
by not joining the EC at the same time as the other Efta countries. 'Nobody
can see what Europe will be like in 10 or 20 years. Perhaps it will be more
decentralised, and then we could apply, if we wanted to. In a situation like
this, it is better for a little country to wait and watch.
'This is not an egotistical stance. We want to be friendly with everyone,
politically and economically open, but always maintaining our sovereignty.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
