<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (11): A neutral force - Is the army
that absurd?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE NEVER knows whether to treat the subject of the Swiss army with humour
or respect.
The idea of a small, resolutely neutral, land-locked country of 6.8m people
having a huge citizen army constantly at the ready to repel any invader and
enough nuclear shelters to house every citizen somehow seems absurd.
Yet historically, Swiss military achievements, up to and including the
second world war, speak eloquently for the competence and courage of the
country's armed forces and for the durability of the country's neutrality
and democratic institutions.
And the Swiss militia system, under which every able-bodied male is
constantly on call and has to train for a few weeks every year, has long
been admired for its contribution to the country's social fabric as well as
to its military effectiveness. The system has even been copied, notably by
Israel.
And yet, and yet. The cold war is over and the prospect of nuclear
conflagration on the European continent seems to have disappeared.
Even before the fall of the Berlin wall, Switzerland's military stance had
been questioned. After all, the military was still working under a security
doctrine published in 1966. Did the country still need a 600,000-strong
army? Did every strategic bridge and tunnel in the country still have to
have vast quantities of high explosives strapped to it?
Some even doubted that the country needed an army at all. In 1989, a
referendum on the subject revealed that a startling 35.6 per cent minority
favoured scrapping it.
Perhaps that galvanised the federal government into action. In the spring of
1989, Bern launched a full-scale re-evaluation of the country's future
military requirements, called Army 95.
The result will be implemented towards the middle of the decade.
The plan retains the principle of armed neutrality for Switzerland, claiming
that an army contributes to the credibility of a country. It also accepts
that Switzerland should continue to rely on an army composed almost entirely
of part-timers.
But it acknowledges that the potential missions of the military concerns
about maintaining order at home in the event of natural catastrophes or
shock waves from conflicts or disasters in neighbouring countries.
'The line between simple violence and warlike actions is a very moving one,
notably when the development of a situation has not been understood quickly
and responded to energetically,' the draft says.
As a result, Switzerland needs a smaller, more flexible army. Troop numbers
could fall by a third to 400,000 and the class system, dividing soldiers
among elite, support and stormtroop cadres, should be eliminated.
Time given over to military service could be substantially shortened. Now
the minimum service consists of a 17-week basic training course at age 20
plus a further 12 sessions totalling 212 days taken up to the age of 50.
Under Army 95, it would be reduced to an initial 15 weeks and only 10
additional sessions of 19 days, taken every two years up to the age of 42.
There has been little public reaction to the Army 95 proposals, which would
suggest that most Swiss are comfortable with them. Many men in their 40s are
pleased because they are at points in their careers where the time given
over to the military can be a real loss.
Similarly, young people now envisage the possibility of doing some kind of
civil service instead of joining the army. Up to now, this has been
forbidden, but a referendum on a proposal to introduce it is being held next
week.
In March, a consultation process on creating a battalion of 600 armed 'blue
helmet' forces to help in United Nations peacekeeping operations has also
yielded positive results. Up to now, the country has supplied only unarmed
'blue beret' peacekeepers, but the political parties are agreed that the
country must do more in the future.
All this is not to say there has been no controversy on the military front.
The country was gripped last month by a surge in opposition to the
government's plan to invest Dollars 2.3bn in 34 McDonnell Douglas F-18
fighter aircraft to replace ageing Mirages.
The plan was approved by one of the two parliamentary chambers in March and
now requires only approval from the other in June to be put into effect.
The pacifist Group for an Army Free Switzerland has launched a petition that
would cancel the project, and hopes to raise the 100,000 required signatures
before the June vote.
The drive just might succeed. Many Swiss who are not pacifist still do not
understand the need for a sophisticated fighter aircraft to face the kind of
adversaries posited in Army 95.
Another issue is the future of Swiss neutrality. In March, a group of
experts submitted a report to the government, saying that the country's
tradition of neutrality did not prevent it from joining the European
Community or participating in UN mandated economic sanctions. EC entry would
not conflict with Swiss neutrality as long as the EC did not have security
and defence policy structures fixed by treaty.
If the EC subsequently set up a military alliance, the Swiss might have to
reassess their policy of neutrality but, 'even as a member of the EC,
Switzerland could stand aside during conflicts between other states,
maintain a credible and autonomous national defence and carry out its
traditional humanitarian and mediating roles'.
The foreign ministry is now assessing the report and may recommend policy
changes to the cabinet.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
