<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (8): Struggle to stay at the top - The
problems of Swissair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SWISSAIR may be a widely admired airline, but as a shareholder-owned company
based in a small country, it has a struggle on its hands to keep pace with
the giant groups taking shape in its industry.
Last year, in common with most international airlines, the group suffered
from a substantial slump in traffic. Total passengers carried were down 8.2
per cent to 7.9m and cargo volume eased 3.3 per cent to 271,000 tonnes.
However, thanks to cost-cutting and more than normal aircraft sales, the
group was able to show a substantial gain in net profit from SFr48m in 1990
to SFr83m last year. Still, as Mr Armin Baltensweiler, the retiring chairman
said, this was 'not a brilliant result by any means', with return on equity
a dismal 3 per cent.
On the other hand, the group has a relatively strong financial position for
an airline, with debts of SFr5.3bn supported by SFr2.8bn of shareholders'
equity, and its fleet of 60 aircraft has an average age of only six years.
Swissair's major problem is that it has a small national customer base. This
makes it hard for it to muster enough passengers to fill the non-stop
flights that customers demand these days.
New medium capacity aircraft with long-haul capability, such as the
McDonnell Douglas MD-11, have helped the group remain competitive, but its
main strategy for dealing with this problem has been to form pacts with
other airlines.
Late in 1989, it formed one with Delta Airlines of the US and Singapore
Airlines for long-haul routes. In May 1990, it formed another with Austrian
Airlines and Scandinavian Airlines, called the European Quality Alliance.
The idea was that the airlines would share facilities and route management
and exchange strategic share- holdings, but they have found that working
together is easier in good times than in a recession.
'Alliances are not enforceable,' Mr Paul Muller, a Swissair director, says
wryly. 'And when things are bad, a company's first thoughts are for its own
problems.'
There were, for example, plans for SAS and Swissair to combine forces on
aircraft purchases, but they have been scuttled because of SAS's financial
problems. Similarly, the depressed state of the shares of both companies has
delayed a planned share swap.
Swissair's role as the distribution and collection point for Delta in Europe
was undermined when Delta acquired Pan American's European routes.
However, that does not mean the alliances have failed. Mr Muller claims the
co-ordination of Swissair and SAS schedules has contributed to a big
increase in Swissair's business from Scandinavia to and from Africa. SAS,
Swissair and Austrian Airlines have set up a jointly operated station in
Vilnius, thus saving costs.
Also, Swissair has won a contract to service Delta's 21 Airbuses, 'our most
important maintenance contract in 10 years,' Mr Muller says.
Swissair's other big headache is a political one. The airline is terrified
about being left out in the cold when EC-wide air transport policies are
made.
'If Switzerland remains isol- ated from the rest of Europe, our ability to
compete will be further handicapped,' Mr Otto Loepfe, the airline's
president, said last month. 'Swiss integration in Europe is a matter of
survival,' he added.
Most other Swiss companies have already insulated themselves against the
possibility that Switzerland will not join the EC by setting up subsidiaries
and factories within EC countries. However, Swissair cannot do this, because
EC transport policy requires that EC airlines be owned and controlled by EC
nationals.
The country will hold a referendum later this year on the plan to build new
tunnels through the Alps. This is a vital element of the Alpine transit
treaty negotiated last year with Brussels. Also in the treaty is a provision
for bilateral air transport negotiations.
Swissair desperately hopes the treaty will be approved by the Swiss people.
'We are telling all our employees to be sure to vote and to get their
families to vote too,' Mr Muller says. 'It is not a matter of politics; it
is a matter of jobs.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
