<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (5): A tale of triumphs and disasters
 -Banks have scored bigger profits and record loan provisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SWISS banking industry has lived through a bewildering combination of
triumphs and disasters in the past year.
Many banks scored handsome increases in profits. The big three universal
banks all recorded new records on the bottom line and showed that in spite
of the unpopularity of the notion of global banking these days they could
made significant progress in international markets.
Yet most banks had to make record provisions for bad loans, some in
connection with the embarrassingly well publicised collapses of companies
controlled by Mr Werner Rey and the late Robert Maxwell.
The Swiss banking community was also embarrassed by the spectacle of the
forced closure of a sizeable regional bank, Spar und Leihkasse Thun, last
October, something no-one ever expected to see in Switzerland.
And early this year, the removal by Moody's of its triple A rating from the
long-term debt of Credit Suisse, and its threat to do the same to Swiss Bank
Corporation (SBC) caused further discomfort.
Moody's cited the increased risk to banks caused by the liberalisation of
Swiss banking and security markets in the past two years, but the
indications are that over the period both the big universal banks and the
top private banks have strengthened their positions in securities dealing
and fund management.
Probably the most important of these developments is the growing success of
the big three banks in world markets. Union Bank of Switzerland (UBS), the
largest, and Credit Suisse have had considerable troubles in the past with
their foreign subsidiaries and SBC was slow in establishing an international
strategy.
But in the past year, aided by their strong balance sheets and no doubt also
by the retreat of troubled Japanese and US banks from the key international
markets, the big three have found profitable pickings in international
lending, foreign exchange dealings and fund management.
Credit Suisse said 30 per cent of its net income came from foreign
operations, but Bank Julius Baer, in a recent study, argues that the figure
would be more like 66 per cent if income from the group's Luxembourg-based
mutual funds, which are managed from Zurich, were included. UBS said the
foreign contribution to its earnings last year tripled to 25 per cent.
SBC said that its association with the derivative specialists, the O'Conner
Partnerships in Chicago, in which it invested about SFr90m a little over a
year ago, yielded net income of SFr107m last year, but overall foreign
earnings were depressed by large provisions on bad debts.
In spite of the Thun failure, the country's regional banks also did well.
The Union of Swiss Regional Banks (VSRB) said its 173 members increased
their combined net profits by 12 per cent to SFr264m and enlarged their
balance sheets by 5.1 per cent to SFr86.1bn. However, even their combined
profits are tiny in comparison with UBS's SFr1.2bn last year, indicating the
need for further consolidation.
Mr Robert Studer, chief executive of UBS, startled a Zurich audience in
March by predicting that 100 of the country's banks could disappear in the
next 10 years.
That seems a large number for a small country, but it makes more sense when
you consider that Switzerland's total bank count is still a whopping 630.
Indeed, some might think Mr Studer's proposed reduction too modest.
Leaders of the country's financial services industry have known for a long
time that rationalisation was inevitable, and that the need for action had
intensified since various cartel-like conventions, providing protection for
various types of banks, were abolished.
But they preferred not to think about it much until the failure of Spar und
Leihkasse Thun shocked them into action.
It was the first time in memory that the Federal Banking Commission had
closed a well-known bank without warning, and the sight of queues of
depositors outside the bank's doors was not one anyone had ever expected in
Switzerland.
In the wake of the closure, the various bank associations in February agreed
to set up a two-layer safety net designed to prevent any more forced
closures.
First, the VSRB, which represents many of the smaller local banks that are
in the greatest difficulties, has formed an examining board to discover
problem cases and try to solve them. Union officials say that about a dozen
of their 185 member banks are now being examined.
Ideally, another bank will be found to take on the problem bank or its
assets. If a problem bank refuses to co-operate, the Federal Banking
Commission will apply pressure. If no bank is willing to take over the
troubled bank, a working group within the Swiss Bankers Association will
move in to make sure that, whatever happens, creditors are protected.
Meanwhile, rationalisation is also the order of the day among big banks. In
his March speech, Mr Studer also shocked his audience by suggesting that one
of the big three might decide to give up retail banking in the foreseeable
future because profits were so thin in this area.
Analysts immediately pointed the finger at Credit Suisse, the third largest
of the big three, and a relatively recent player in the retail area.
However, Credit Suisse officials denied that they had any intention of
abandoning its retail network.
Nevertheless, all three big banks are now looking carefully at their retail
businesses for ways to raise revenues and trim costs. Thus, UBS announced in
January that it would concentrate certain specialised services in a limited
number of branches rather than have every branch offer every service. Credit
Suisse said it had already made considerable progress on this front.
Mr Franz Galliker, chairman of Swiss Bank Corporation, said last month that
SBC too was thinking of 'streamlining' its branch network. In March, SBC
announced that it was restructuring Banca della Svizzera Italiana, in which
it acquired a majority stake last year, to become part of a private banking
group, leaving it with retail activities only in its canton Ticino base.
The big three banks have also participated in the trend among leading Swiss
companies to greater transparency and investor friendliness in recent
months. They have much stronger equity bases than most of their leading
international competitors, but their return on equity, ranging from 7 per
cent to 10 per cent, still leaves considerable room for improvement.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
