<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (9): Trying to carve out a niche -
Profile: Volksbank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW PEOPLE outside Switzerland had heard of Swiss Volksbank until it emerged
as a lender of Dollars 35m to a private company controlled by the late
Robert Maxwell.
The loan attracted wide attention abroad because it was made only after Mr
Ian Maxwell and Mr Kevin Maxwell had pledged Berlitz shares owned by Maxwell
Communication Corporation (MCC) to Volksbank. The brothers had previously
agreed to sell the shares to a Japanese company.
The loan also raised eyebrows because few people in Switzerland would have
expected this rather sleepy and parochial bank to be involved with the likes
of Maxwell.
Although Volksbank is Switzerland's fourth largest commercial bank, it is a
distant fourth behind the third largest, Credit Suisse, and does not have a
particularly distinguished performance record.
While Credit Suisse had total assets of SFr155.6bn at the end of last year,
Volksbank had only SFr46.5bn. And Volksbank's after-tax return on equity was
only 3.1 per cent, compared with 9.9 per cent at Credit Suisse.
The bank has been trying to improve its performance, and the Maxwell
misadventure is a curious footnote in the story.
Volksbank has long looked a rather awkward player on the Swiss banking
stage. Though it is in a different league from the big three Swiss
commercial banks, it is more than just a building society.
It is a full service bank with 191 branches and agencies throughout
Switzerland and a strong presence in both retail and corporate lending.
The fact that Volksbank does not fit neatly into a clear category has given
rise to speculation that it might be taken over. But none of the big three
banks - and they are the most likely potential bidders  - is much interested
in expanding its already large presence in the Swiss market.
Volksbank's leaders recognised a few years ago that their main customers -
Switzerland's army of small and medium-sized businesses  - were expanding
abroad. 'We did not want to lose them because we could not serve them any
more,' says Mr Rudolf Bosshard, the bank's director responsible for
international development.
They knew that they could not match the big three in the world's leading
financial mar- kets. But they thought they could build a sufficient inter-
national presence to preserve their client base at home.
The obvious first step was to set up offices in the key financial centres
that could provide customers with export finance, foreign exchange, capital
markets and portfolio management services on competitive terms.
A London branch was opened in 1985, and offices in New York, Tokyo and Sing-
apore followed in 1989. Early this year, Volksbank purch- ased a 20 per cent
stake in Banque Odier Bungener Cour- voisier in Paris rather than try to
build up from scratch there.
Ironically, it was through the application of this strategy that the bank
came into con- tact with Robert Maxwell. In 1987, one of its Swiss
industrial customers won a contract to supply machinery to a Maxwell company
and Volksbank's London branch provided a guarantee of delivery.
The contact was maintained. Volksbank lead-managed a bond issue for MCC a
few months later and participated in a syndicated loan for it. However, it
then decided to back away a bit. 'We realised Maxwell was too big for us,'
Mr Bosshard says.
Even so, the bank still has some Maxwell business on its books, and last
year made provisions for a Dollars 73m loan to MCC. No provision was made
for the Dollars 35m loan to the private Maxwell company because it was
covered by the Berlitz shares, which the bank has since claimed.
The second stage of Volksbank's international strategy began to take shape
last year. Under its expansion programme, it has concluded co-operation
agreements with banks in Bavaria, Baden-Wurttemberg and France. Now, says Mr
Bosshard, it is looking for a partner or acquisition in northern Italy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9532</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (7): Cloud over the cartels - Trade
policy faces an overhaul
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PARTICIPATION in the European Economic Area (EEA) and eventual EC membership
will give a substantial boost to the Swiss economy, but some sectors will
suffer painful adjustments. Economists agree that the impetus to growth will
come not so much from higher exports to more open European markets, but from
greater efficiency due to stiffer competition in domestic markets.
Though Switzerland's heavily protected agricultural sector is not directly
affected by the EEA, it too is being forced to contemplate radical change in
the light of the current round of global trade talks now nearing a close
under the auspices of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) in
Geneva.
A Gatt report on Switzerland's trade policy last autumn pointed out that,
while Swiss per capita incomes were more than 25 per cent above those in the
US and Canada in 1989, they lagged in terms of purchasing power. Swiss food
prices are well above EC levels, with consumers bearing 80 per cent of the
SFr7bn annual cost of farm support through guaranteed prices, tariffs and
border restrictions.
In industry too, while external trade policies are a model of liberal
economic principles, a network of formal and informal cartels between
domestic producers and traders keeps prices high and stringent regulations
tend to restrict competition from new entrants. As a result, Swiss consumers
pay over 40 per cent more for goods and services than their EC counterparts,
according to the Swiss Bank Corporation.
Unusually in Europe, Swiss law permits cartels, providing only for
investigation of abuses. No-one knows for sure how many cartels there are,
but one estimate puts the number at 900, many of which involve price-fixing.
Some, as in brewing, have crumbled under competitive pressures and others,
like the banking conventions, have been dismantled at government insistence.
But the bulk have been untouched for many years.
EEA membership will entail adoption of EC competition law which forbids
cartels and curtails monopolies. The SBC study published last month
estimated that the EEA could boost Switzerland's economic growth rate by 0.5
percentage points a year, a gain of 4-6 per cent by the end of the decade.
The Basle-based Economic Research Institute (BAK) thinks the benefits would
be even greater, with the Swiss economy growing by 2.3 per cent a year
within the EEA to the year 2000 and only 1.1 per cent a year outside it.
SBC's economists identified two vulnerable sectors: the construction
industry, due to an opening of public procurement - especially at cantonal
level - to foreign bidding; and medium-sized companies geared primarily to
the domestic market, notably in commerce, the food and drink industry and
services. Main beneficiaries would be pharmaceuticals, insurance companies
and multinationals including the banks.
Switzerland's successful export industries have undergone major structural
adjustments over the past decade or so, shifting further to
capital-intensive, high value-added products and services to economise on
scarce and expensive skilled labour and land. Most already have a solid base
in the EC. The Community accounts for nearly half Switzerland's foreign
assets of SFr85bn, half the near-1m overseas employees of Swiss companies,
and two-thirds of Switzerland's foreign trade.
Useful but unspectacular gains will come from harmonisation of standards and
common regulations throughout the 19-nation EEA, as well as freer movement
of labour and an end to the Lex Friedrich which restricts land sales to
foreigners. Industry will also welcome the assurance of future harmonisation
of technical and environmental standards, which could otherwise pose trade
barriers.
Swiss farmers view the future with much more apprehension. They have turned
out in their thousands to demonstrate in the capital, Bern, and in Geneva
against Gatt proposals that would oblige Switzerland to scrap its import
quota system on agricultural products in favour of tariffs, and reduce
domestic subsidies for agriculture by some 20 per cent by 1999. These
proposals, and future EC membership, could slash farm incomes by as much as
half, according to farmers' groups.
The government has said that the Gatt plan is not acceptable. But it has
admitted that Switzerland's 'war economy' farm policy based on ensuring food
self-sufficiency and maximising farmholdings is no longer tenable.
The effect has been to generate chronic surpluses and encourage heavy use of
chemical fertilisers and pesticides, while failing to protect farmers'
incomes or stop the exodus from the land.
The federal council is now proposing a shift from price supports to direct
income payments which would be largely independent of production. These
would be permitted under the Gatt plan. The intention is to target payments
at services provided in the public interest, such as food security and care
of the countryside, while ensuring that prices better reflect market
conditions and come down further towards EC levels. This is bound to produce
some restructuring and consolidation of Switzerland's 90,000 farms, 40 per
cent of them part-time.
While international pressures will lead to greater economic competitiveness,
many of the economic and political constraints that handicap efficiency will
require independent action by the Swiss government. The federal council has
said that it plans to reduce the extent of regulation (for instance, it
recently denoun- ced the International Labour Organisation convention
banning night work for women in industry). But it is not obvious how it can
reform the legal and political system that enables citizens to delay
inordinately investment projects and other economic initiatives, while
maintaining desired high environmental and health and safety standards.
Mr Jean-Pascal Delamuraz, the economy minister, gave a telling example of
Swiss dilatoriness to the upper house of parliament a couple of months ago.
'One Sunday, the Swiss people said yes to Rail 2000 (a programme to
modernise and expand the rail network). The following Monday, the French
government said yes to the construction of the Atlantic TGV. Result: we have
constructed a few metres of Rail 2000 and Adolf Ogi (the transport minister)
is fighting 80 appeals per kilometre. Meanwhile, the TGV is running at 514
kilometres an hour from end to end.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9533</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (4): Worrying outflow of funds - Moves
to stem the decline of a financial centre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF INTEGRATION with Europe is the biggest concern of the Swiss these days,
the second biggest may well be the future of their country as an
international financial centre.
Hardly a week goes by without someone worrying about or proposing measures
to secure the future of what is known in all the official Swiss languages as
Finanzplatz Schweiz.
The name itself reveals part of the problem. One does not discuss the future
of Finanzplatz Zurich or Finanzplatz Basel, or even La Place Financiere de
Geneve. The country's financial industry is typically Swiss; it is
decentralised inconveniently among three centres (not to mention Lugano) and
to propose any large-scale concentration is out of the question.
Although precise statistics are hard to come by, there is no doubt that
Switzerland has declined as a financial centre in the past decade.
The country's big corporations have gone global for their banking and
capital market needs, and the big Swiss banks have followed them. This year,
some even held their financial results press conferences in London rather
than Switzerland. While the Japanese provided a blizzard of equity-linked
Swiss franc bond issues in the late 1980s, these have petered out as Tokyo's
stock market has plunged.
Many of the 42 Japanese banks and brokerage houses in Switzerland have been
shedding staff in recent months, and observers expect more than a few to
close their doors within the next year or so.
Meanwhile, the heart of the equity market has decamped to more liquid
London, where prices for most leading Swiss shares are now set. Mr Robert
Studer, president of Union Bank of Switzerland, says that about 15 per cent
of dealing in the top 18 Swiss blue chips now takes place in London.
Dealers point out that the figure would be larger but for the reluctance of
the big banks - which dominate equity trading  - overtly to irritate the
Swiss authorities by executing more deals in London.
Ironically, Zurich is about to open a new spacious stock exchange building,
planned more than a decade ago in anticipation of expansion that has gone
elsewhere.
Zurich's foreign exchange market is also fading, as trading is increasingly
concentrated in three big global centres: London, Tokyo and New York. And
the big three banks have tended to build up their trendy derivatives
businesses outside Switzerland as well.
The only sector in which the Swiss financial centre appears to be holding
its own is in asset management, mainly in connection with private banking.
According to Mr Jean Pierre Cuoni, president of Coutts &amp; Co in Zurich,
Switzerland still attracts about half of the world's cross-border private
banking business - worth perhaps Dollars 1,500bn.
The country also has outsize institutional pools of money because of its
large insurance companies and legislation requiring every Swiss company to
have a pension fund for its employees.
Indeed, private banking is an area where even foreign banks, including
Coutts, think they have a future in Switzerland.
If that roughly is the state of play, perhaps the first question to ask is
whether it is the result of a shift away of financial activity, especially
to London, or whether things can be done to improve or restore some lost or
weakened elements of Finanzplatz Schweiz.
The consensus appears to be that some of the outflow, notably of mutual
funds to Luxembourg, could have been stopped if the Swiss government had
been more sensitive to the negative impact of some of its regulations and
taxes in this area.
Similarly, if the country's stock exchanges had combined forces sooner, they
might have created a sufficiently liquid market in Switzerland so that
London would not have snapped up so much of the dealing business. Even
today, there are still three stock exchanges in Switzerland.
However, in a book* published this week, Mr Hans-Dieter Vontobel, president
of Bank J. Vontobel, a leading Zurich private bank, suggests that the
departure of much financial activity from the country was inevitable because
of the 'opening up and vitalising process of the foreign financial centres'.
Mr Vontobel also blames the four big banks for being too willing to let the
Swiss financial centre decay. He points out that the four opened only 10
branches in Switzerland in the 1980s, while they created nearly 150 offices
abroad.
In any event, he thinks there is not much point chasing after lost business.
Instead, it would be better to concentrate on taking steps to help preserve
the competitiveness of the Swiss asset management sector.
His main argument is that competition should be allowed free rein. He claims
that despite the elimination of various conventions in the banking sector in
the past two years, there is still too much concentration and oligopolistic
practice and the Swiss generally are too afraid of competition.
But Mr Vontobel says there is not much point in waiting for the government
to take action as the process is too slow. The international competitiveness
of Swiss asset management has to be ach- ieved by the firms themselves,
notably through productivity gains. He suspects that 20 per cent of the
115,000 jobs in the Swiss financial industry could be lost in the next five
to 10 years, even if the government moved quickly to improve the regulatory
environment.
The next reform milestone comes in the autumn when a referendum will be held
to approve a government proposal to reduce substantially the 0.3 per cent
stamp duty that has been blamed for much of the weakening of the Swiss
financial centre.
Although the reform is endorsed by virtually all political parties,
financial circles fear that it will be rejected by the people. Many Swiss
see no reason why the big banks should receive a gift at a time when they
are boasting about record profits.
The irony is that more and more of the banks' profits are coming from
abroad.
*Wettbewerb als Chance (Competition as Opportunity), by Hans-Dieter Vontobel
and Lukas Morscher, Verlag Neue Zurcher Zeitung, Zurich.
</TEXT>
