<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Switzerland (1): Gear after neutral - The
government has firmly committed itself to joining the European Community.
Line is overdrawn But doubts remain about whether the inhabitants of neutral
Switzerland will want to follow this lead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TIME for decisions has at last arrived. Over the next year, the Swiss
will be called upon, after years of debate and soul-searching, to take a
number of decisions that will set the framework for their relations with the
rest of Europe and the rest of the world for the foreseeable future.
At stake is whether the country will continue to pursue its detached stance,
maintaining strict neutrality and avoiding foreign alignments. Or will it
adopt a more conventional role for a small, landlocked, resource-poor
country of 6.8m people, and join formally with its neighbours in building
the European Community of the future?
Opinion polls have consistently indicated that the Swiss are sharply divided
on these questions, worried, on the one hand, that if they remain detached,
their highly developed industrial base will suffer and their much-envied
standard of living will decline.
These worries are understandably acute at a time when the Swiss economy is
having difficulty pulling out of a year-long recession, when inflation is
uncharacteristically high and the country's role as a financial haven seems
to be disappearing.
But the Swiss are strongly attached to their decentralised style of
self-government and they fear that their interests would be not be
well-protected in an organisation such as the European Commission. They
dread a further rush of immigrants and foreign property buyers if the
country has to accept the EC principle of freedom of movement of people.
It would be wrong to overdramatise the distance between the two options on
offer. Even if it decides to maintain its autonomy, Switzerland would not be
isolated or aloof from the problems of its continent or the world. It
already participates as a non-member in the activities of most international
organisations; it has an increasingly liberal and open economy and it shares
the burdens of refugees that strain most western European countries these
days. More than 16 per cent of Swiss residents are non-Swiss.
Conversely, if the Swiss decide to move towards joining the European
Community, they will still be able to maintain - at least at the local level
 -their unique and cherished political structures.
The decision-making process on these issues begins as early as next week
when the Swiss will vote in a plebiscite on whether their country should at
last join the International Monetary Fund and World Bank.
This will be the first test of Swiss sentiment towards international
organisations since a majority rejected a proposal in 1986 to join the
United Nations. In the meantime, Switzerland startled many observers by
joining in the UN-led coalition to roll back Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
A few weeks ago, it joined the sanctions against Libya over airline
terrorism.
In the autumn, the people will vote in another plebiscite on a mammoth
project to drill two new rail tunnels through the Alps. This project, called
NEAT, is the Swiss government's contribution to trying to solve the
inflammatory dispute that pits Austria and Switzerland against the EC over
the use of Swiss roads by EC lorries moving between Italy and Germany.
The EC and the Alpine countries reached a comprehensive agreement on the
problem late last year, subject to ratification by the Swiss and Austrians.
The importance of the agreement for EC-Swiss relations is great enough in
itself, but other factors make it even more important.
For one thing, it includes an air traffic agreement, which is vital to the
survival of Swissair, the Swiss national airline, especially if Switzerland
later decides not to join the EC.
The treaty is also part of the transport element in the agreement between
the six European Free Trade Area (Efta) countries, including Switzerland,
and the EC that was initialled last month to create what is called the
European Economic Area (EEA).
So if the NEAT proposal is rejected by Swiss voters, Switzerland will have
reneged on its commitments under the EEA treaty.
The final referendum of interest is on the EEA itself. This was originally
going to be held in December, but because parts of the agreement had to be
rewritten early this year to overcome the objections of the European Court
of Justice, completion was delayed and so the referendum must be postponed
until May 1993.
The vote on the EEA has taken on increased importance since the federal
cabinet's declaration last autumn that it considers the EEA nothing more
than a first step towards full EC membership. Thus, the ground has been cut
from under those Swiss who like the idea of the EEA - essentially a free
trade area - but do not like the EC, at least in its present form.
Since the cabinet's declaration, some political and business leaders have
argued that the country should put in its application to join the EC
immediately rather than wait for the EEA referendum result. They say that
speed is of the essence if the country is to sit around the table with the
likes of Sweden, Austria, Norway and Finland rather than having to apply in
a few years' time with Czechoslovakia, Turkey and Hungary.
In particular, the Swiss would like to be involved in the resolution of how
neutral countries' interests will be protected in the EC. This will be
sorted out in the negotiations with Austria, Sweden and Finland, so if
Switzerland is not present, it will have to accept the same terms when and
if it applies at a later point.
There is also a tactical point. Some argue that if a majority of the Swiss
vote against joining the EEA in next May's referendum, it would be awkward
for the government to turn around and apply immediately for EC membership.
Thus, these people say, it would be smarter to put the application in now.
Then, if the EEA referendum was lost, the government could just move on to
the EC negotiations.
Even though the federal government and most top business leaders are
recommending that the people endorse all the above steps towards integration
with the European Community and the world, it is far from certain that they
will do so.
The Swiss tend to be very practical voters and, according to one Zurich
banker, they will probably vote against joining the Bretton Woods
institutions simply because they do not see what they will get out of them.
Attitudes toward Europe are more complex and varied. In general, the Swiss
do not like what they see as the concentration of more and more jurisdiction
at the EC centre in Brussels. One is frequently told that if the EC were
developing along the more decentralised lines that the British government
has proposed, then the Swiss might be more enthusiastic.
In the business community, the thousands of small wholesalers, retailers and
contractors - not to mention farmers - who still benefit from protection
from foreign competition obviously fear the potential arrival of the EC
anti-cartel office and the Common Agricultural Policy.
For totally different reasons, many of the country's large industrialists
and bankers no longer seem terribly worried about the outcome, which means
that they may feel free to vote with their hearts rather than their heads.
This is because, at their level, life has already become very European and
international. Switzerland exports 36 per cent of its output and imports an
almost identical proportion of its consumption, with the great majority of
its trade in both directions being with other European countries. Leading
Swiss banks and industrial companies have large and successful operating
bases abroad, and many leading EC companies, notably car makers, have
substantial sales in Switzerland.
More important, whatever unfair advantages they once enjoyed as a result of
being based in Switzerland are rapidly being swept away.
Perhaps the most significant of these advantages was the relatively closed
Swiss capital market, which is now in serious decline. (Ironically, Swiss
voters are expected to veto in yet another referendum later this year a
government plan to help the capital markets by cutting an irritating stamp
duty on securities transactions.)
This decline has forced big companies to make their shares more accessible
and attractive to foreigners and to become more transparent in their
reporting so that they can attract foreign capital. In the past few months,
several companies have split their shares and removed restrictions on
foreign ownership.
They are still feeling their way in the new, more liberal environment and
there have been no hostile foreign takeovers of Swiss companies so far.
Friendly sell-outs are starting to occur though. In January, German
interests took control of the big Movenpick restaurants and hotels group and
an Italian company took a strategic stake in the machinery group, Saurer.
But one lesson that already seems to be emerging is that business will go
on, whether or not companies are controlled by Swiss owners. It will also go
on whether or not Switzerland joins the EC.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page I
</PAGE>
