<DOCNO>FT922-9537</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Pension Fund Investment (16): Investors urged to
behave like owners - Corporate governance is taking hold in the
consciousness of UK pension funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER YEARS of determined passivity, UK pension funds are finally waking up
to their own power. With over Pounds 250bn in assets, they provide the
largest single source of working capital for British industry.
Thus, it should come as no surprise that pension funds are finally coming
around to the view that they should act like owners, rather than simply
passive investors.
The issue of corporate governance - the way companies are governed by their
directors - has slowly taken hold in the consciousness of UK pension funds
in a way unimaginable just a few years ago. Shareholders are beginning to
demand that managements tell them more about how their companies are run,
and seeking the right to do something about inefficient, profligate or
arrogant managers.
In the US, where the corporate governance movement has been in full swing
for years, pension fund activism has been assisted by the US Labour
Department, which in 1988 determined that voting rights are an asset of
pension fund trusts which must be exercised on behalf of members.
Meanwhile, in Britain, the National Association of Pension Funds last year
highlighted the passivity of its members, when it conducted a survey showing
that fewer than 20 per cent of them regularly exercised their proxy rights.
Mr Clive Gilchrist, deputy chairman of the NAPF and chairman of BesTrustees,
a company which acts as an independent trustee on pension boards, has
repeatedly urged members to use their voting rights. A survey conducted in
1990 showed that some 23 per cent of NAPF members did not even know whose
responsibility it was to make voting decisions. 'By 1991, the numbers were
only very slightly better,' he said.
To encourage members to vote, the NAPF has just established a proxy voting
service. In its initial stages, it will track all the companies in the FT-SE
100 index, preparing reports on matters to be voted at each annual general
meeting. The reports make no effort to advise pension funds on how to vote;
they simply inform readers whether or not the matter in hand is consider
contentious. It will also inform readers whether they are being asked to
approve a development which does not conform with NAPF guidelines on best
practice on corporate governance.
Mr Angus Matheson, chairman of the NAPF's investment committee, acknowledges
that the group has not been deluged with demands for the new service, but
says that, at Pounds 2,000 per participant, response has been better than
expected. Currently, about six large institutions have signed up. 'So many
of then haven't even given the matter of voting any thought,' said Mr
Matheson.
The debate about corporate governance has been spurred on by the recession
of the past three years, which has exposed many managerial weaknesses
covered up by the go-go years of the late 1980s. Shareholders began asking
hard questions only when managements proved themselves unable to cope with
the downturn in business.
The NAPF, among other shareholder groups, has been busy developing codes of
practice intended to promote shareholder influence and make companies more
responsive to the interests of their owners. As a member of the
Institutional Shareholders Committee, it has participated in the drafting of
codes outlining the rights and responsibilities both of directors and of
shareholders.
Also, the NAPF has held discussions with the Accounting Standards Board, to
urge new rules which would require companies to disclose more about their
operations in their annual accounts.
Meanwhile, the legitimacy of demands for better corporate governance is
likely to get a boost from a report to be issued at the end of this month by
the so-called Cadbury Committee. The Committee on the Financial Aspects of
Corporate Governance, chaired by Sir Adrian Cadbury, is expected to
recommend a wide range of measures, aimed at improving the quality of
information offered to shareholders and improving board accountability.
For hawks on the corporate governance issue, the report is likely to be
disappointing, because it will have no enforcement mechanism other than a
new rule from the London Stock Exchange requiring companies to disclose the
extent to which they comply with its recommendations.
But the report will underline the growing seriousness of investors in seeing
to it that boards are held accountable for their own performance.
But if those codes are to be any more than self-righteous posturing,
shareholders will have to use their muscle in the form of votes to put their
recommendations to the test.
Mr Matheson notes that, for those pension funds that use external managers,
the sheer mechanics of voting mitigate against it. 'For a large external
manager with several hundred clients, there's quite a lot of paper to be
signed,' he said.
A manager unable to contact pension fund trustees may have to forgo a vote
on their behalf. Also, many pension fund trustees may feel they are not well
informed enough about each company's affairs to use their votes wisely.
Thus, such decisions are better left to professional money managers who are
paid fees for their judgments.
Mr Matheson said that the NAPF's effort to encourage members to vote has
been helped by the Institutional Fund Managers Association, a trade group,
which urges the adoption of a standard management agreement authorising the
manager to make voting decisions on the pension fund's behalf.
Ann Simpson, co-director of the Pensions Investment Research Council, which
largely advises local authority pension funds, notes that, when fund
managers need to seek trustees' permission to vote, the typical 21-day
notice period offered by most companies is inadequate.
The PIRC has for some time been running a proxy voting service similar to
that newly established by the NAPF. However, the PIRC's bulletins include a
discussion of matters not on the agenda - such as companies' refusal to
offer their executive directors for periodic renomination - and suggests
that shareholders raise the issue with managements.
Meanwhile, Mr John Wilcox, chairman of Georgeson, a US-based investor
relations consultancy, argues that UK laws actually offer far more freedom
to domestic institutions to influence managments than is offered to their US
counterparts. US securities laws, for instance, prevent institutions from
discussing joint courses of action without filing certain documents with the
Securities and Exchange Commission. 'The barriers to the exercise of power
are much lower here in the UK,' he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9538</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFADBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Pension Fund Investment (17): Morale lift for
boutiques - A move towards specialist managers in the UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINE MOIR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOMETHING ODD seems to be going on among trustees when it comes to selecting
pension fund investment managers. Are they, or are they not, abandoning the
traditional UK preference for balanced managers in favour of US-style
specialists? The latest evidence appears to point both ways at once.
Until the late 1980s, British pension schemes not managed internally were
nearly always entrusted to investment houses with a very broad brief - to
invest at their discretion across the spectrum of equities, bonds and cash.
Only property investment, always regarded as something of a law unto itself,
was usually conducted by a specialist manager.
This style of management, which produces a balanced portfolio, is in marked
contrast to the US, where trustees themselves set a specific strategy for
the fund and then hire numbers of specialist managers to carry out different
aspects of the strategy. Only funds too small to warrant splitting up into
separate tranches are generally managed by a broad-spectrum 'balanced'
manager.
By 1990 the UK picture had begun to change sufficiently for the National
Association of Pension Funds' committee of inquiry into investment
performance measurement to take note. In his report, the committee chairman,
Maurice Stonefrost, commented on the 'move towards some specialisation of
managers' briefs (and therefore greater trustee involvement in detailed
asset allocation decisions).'
Mr Stonefrost attributed this in part to the increasing availability of more
detailed disaggregated information on managers' performance in the 'sub sets
of balanced fund portfolios' - for example, in their international
investment portfolios.
He also believed that it reflected regulatory change. The Financial Services
Act, for instance, requires trustees explicitly to define objectives as part
of their contract with managers, because the ultimate responsibility for a
fund's investment risk profile, and therefore broad asset allocation, lies
with the trustees.
That same year, a survey by Phillips &amp; Drew Fund Managers (PDFM) of large
pension schemes, produced some electric figures in support of this view.
Although only 14 per cent used specialist UK equity managers and 20 per cent
used international equity specialists, more than 10 per cent said they were
actively considering such a move.
The enthusiasm with which trustees appeared to be embracing specialists was
a great morale booster for small or new niche managers, who could not hope
to compete across the board with large 'balanced' houses.
One such niche (though hardly small) boutique is Lombard Odier Investment
Management, the London-based fixed income and continental equities
investment arm of the Geneva bank. Paul Abberley, LO's head of fixed income,
explained:
'We are seeing a trend towards funds splitting into a balanced core and
specialist satellites as and when they review the structure of their
operations. There is no reliable data yet, but the shift is quite strong
whenever trustees undertake their reviews.'
Even the established houses are prepared to concede that they may soon face
competition from specialists. However, Chris Cheetham, director of
investment strategy at the Prudential, warned that Mr Stonefrost may have
overstated the change.
'We are seeing the growth of specialisation,' said Mr Cheetham, 'but it
won't reach US proportions.' Today his caution seems more than justified. A
second survey carried out by PDFM in 1991 showed little growth in the
numbers of specialists actually hired. But, more important, the number of
trustees actively considering their use had dropped sharply to under 4 per
cent.
And the initial figures from the 1992 survey, which will be published in the
summer, are nearly identical to last year's. If PDFM's figures are reliable,
'the move from balanced to specialist, which most commentators expected to
accelerate, appears to have come to a very sharp stop.'
PDFM can throw little light on the turnround, although they speculate that
there may be three factors at work:
1, The difficulty of controlling asset allocation within a specialist
structure;
2, The difficulty of coping with innovation in a rigid specialist structure
(except by adding more and more specialists); and
3, Lack of evidence of any improvement in performance.
If trustees have abandoned their shift to specialists on the basis of poor
performance over just two years, this will disappoint Mr Stonefrost's
committee, which strongly advised that performance should be measured
against a background of no less than five years.
But it may be that PDFM's surveying equipment is not sensitive enough for
what is going on. Lombard Odier, for example, has noticed a shift from
balanced to regional bond and equity portfolios as updated computer
facilities have introduced trustees to tactical asset allocation techniques.
This in turn, they say, has meant that trustees who used to 'employ more
than one balanced manager, now farm out the asset allocation decision to
these professionals who in turn appoint a growing number of specialists'.
Thus, in one sense, the trustees can still claim to be running balanced
funds while simultaneously promoting the growth of specialists.
PDFM's antennae have been able to pick up another curious fact: a clear
tendency for larger schemes to go the specialist route, sometimes by
appointing an internal specialist. It is possible that the internalising
process may have taken the place of overt external specialisation to the
point where the slow growth of external specialists does not tell the true
story.
If that is so, it suggests that trustees want to have their cake and eat it,
carrying out specialist techniques under a balanced label.
</TEXT>
