<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAC8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Pension Fund Investment (12): Holidays reduce the
flow of new money - Charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GIVEN THE current level of fierce competition in the fund management
industry, pension funds ought to be in a better position than ever to get
the service they want at attractive prices.
Competition for pension fund management mandates has been heightened by,
among other things, the recent surge of non-UK houses into the market. Major
US firms, offering their expertise in index-matching and 'active
quantitative' approaches to investment, have aggressively sought to mark out
their stake in the pensions market.
But also, competition has been heightened by a shrinking pie. The past three
years' recession has caused so many companies to seek 'contributions
holidays' from their pension funds that, in fact, pension funds under
management in 1991 actually experienced a net outflow of roughly Pounds
2.5bn, according to figures compiled by Caps, the pension fund performance
measurement service.
Only 30 per cent of funds surveyed by Caps in 1991 had any new money to
invest over the year. Since fund managers' fees are expressed as a
percentage of funds under management, the shrinkage in pension pools hits
them in the pocket.
Mr Rob Collinge, director of compensation and benefits at SmithKline
Beecham, said he had recently renegotiated management contracts with a
number of his outside fund managers which, to his surprise, had resulted in
lower charges for some. 'I was surprised at how successful we were,' he
said, explaining that several of the managers involved had strong
performance records and no shortage of clients.
The problem with competition, he said, was that those fund managers with
mediocre performance records were the ones most willing to cut fees. 'But
for us, a few basis points of improved performance can far outweigh the
advantages of slightly lower fees,' he added.
The shrinkage has caused a pinch for investment managers who have now had to
work harder to secure mandates away from their competitors. However, it has
also provided the incentive for managers to find ways to cull fees from
clients in ways which are not immediately obvious. Indeed, at least one US
bank was said to have been offering its index-matching fund management
services for no fee at all - provided the clients used the bank's global
custody service.
The use of hidden - or so-called 'dirty' charges  - is an issue that has
troubled pension fund trustees for a long time. But in recent years,
publicity surrounding charges and the ensuing calls for regulators to do
something about them has made trustees look even harder at them. Indeed, the
National Association of Pension Funds has formed a committee on fee
transparency, to examine dirty charges and make recommendations to members
about how to deal with them.
Pure charges on pension fund pools range from 0.2 to 0.5 per cent for
balanced pools, depending on the size of funds under management. However,
segregated pools or specialist and overseas accounts incur transaction
charges of up to 1 per cent and additional charges above that, depending on
circumstances.
By international standards, particularly those of the US, UK pension fund
management charges come cheap. In the US, fees can easily average 1.5 to 2
per cent, partly reflecting the wider use of specialist and boutique-type
fund managers.
But it is the hidden charges that are the bone of contention in the UK. The
most significant of these are 'soft commissions' - the provision of services
in kind to fund managers who transact a pre-agreed level of
commission-generating business through a broker.
Last month, the Securities and Investments Board, after vacillating for
months over the matter, declined to outlaw soft commissions, on the grounds
that fund managers can use them legitimately to obtain services which
ultimately enhance returns to clients. However, it has required fund
managers who accept soft commissions to begin disclosing the extent of these
to clients. Among services typically received by fund managers in exchange
for soft commissions are research, data retrieval systems and software
packages.
Because all commissions costs are deducted from the clients' total funds
under management, effectively, it is one way of shifting overheads to
clients from fund managers.
Mr Nick Fitzpatrick, partner at pensions consultants and actuaries Bacon and
Woodrow, said that there was no good reason for pension fund managers to pay
soft commissions. 'Commissions are a voluntary cost, because many fund
managers are able to negotiate transactions with no commission whatsoever,'
he said. 'The only reason I can see for paying soft commission is to hide
the charges from the customer.'
In the US, where disclosure rules have been in place for some time, pension
funds are increasingly demanding that soft commission payments be rebated to
them by the managers which accept them.
Also, fund managers are able to add on dirty charges by placing client funds
in internal unit trusts, which carry charges of 0.5 to 0.75 per cent. While
these are typically used for overseas assets, managers are often inclined to
place clients with pools below Pounds 10m in domestic unit trusts as well.
Mr Fitzpatrick says that he urges clients to seek 'clean' charging
structures wherever possible. While these rarely mean lower costs for
pension funds, they do clarify exactly what the service costs. In a clean
structure, a client may not be charged for anything but the service fee.
Mr Collinge said that almost all his fund management agreements were now
'clean'. 'Its a cost control mechanism - we know what we are paying,' he
said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
