<DOCNO>FT922-9543</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAC6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Pension Fund Investment (13): New code agreed -
Performance measurement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PENSION FUND performance measurement has moved into a new era this year,
with the publication of a code which has the backing of many pension
industry interests. But, ironically, the whole idea of league tables and
performance comparisons could be undermined by a slowly emerging trend
towards individual fund benchmarks.
Performance measurement is now a highly developed service, which has become
concentrated into two main specialist operations. One is the World Markets
company, which started as a soft commissions venture of a stockbroking firm
but is now owned by Bankers Trust, the US commercial banking group. The
other is Combined Actuarial Performance Services (Caps) which, as its name
suggests, is the result of merging the separate measurement service of
various actuarial firms such as R Watson, Bacon &amp; Woodrow, Mercer Fraser and
Noble Lowndes.
WM is the market leader in terms of the size of funds measured. Last year
its WM All Funds Universe consisted of over 2,000 UK pension fund portfolios
worth Pounds 241bn, said to represent about three-quarters of the industry.
Caps measured rather more portfolios, at 2,760, but a rather smaller
aggregate of Pounds 156bn.
While Caps has a slightly smaller - although clearly overlapping - coverage,
in some respects its funds are more typical of the industry. The WM results
tend to be affected by the performance of a few huge funds which may have
rather different characteristics, such as a significantly higher investment
in property. The WM Universe had an 8 per cent property content in its
aggregated portfolio last year, against only 2 per cent for Caps.
However, the performance of property can be separated out. Moreover, WM now
also divides its funds into the WM Very Large Funds Universe, worth over
Pounds 1bn each, and the WM Average Funds Universe.
A dismal property market meant that the giant funds did worse than average
in 1991. The WM Very Large Funds earned an average rate of return of 16.2
per cent (income plus capital growth) compared with 17.8 per cent for the WM
Average Funds.
Meanwhile, the Caps median fund earned 18.3 per cent including property, and
18.6 per cent excluding it.
Despite an element of harmonisation within the past year or two, the WM and
Caps services retain slight technical differences. WM tends to talk about
averages, and Caps about medians, for instance. But these are of little
consequence, and there will be no repetition of the minor embarrassment two
years ago, when the rate of return on the FT-Actuaries All-Share Index for
was measured as 36.1 per cent by WM and 35.5 per cent by Caps. The
discrepancy related to the timing of dividend receipts. For 1991, however,
both services measure the All-Share return as 20.7 per cent.
Possibly the methodology still needs to be refined in specialist areas such
as index-tracking funds. Last year, for instance, the presence of a
significant element of recently-privatised stocks within the All-Share
tended to flatter the index funds, because they held these shares in
partly-paid form, and outperformed because prices rose. However, such
details may be a matter for interpretation rather than changes in technique.
At any rate, a code of practice for both methodology and the presentation of
historical performance records has now been agreed. The code was developed
because of complaints that performance measurement figures have been misused
by fund managers, particularly when soliciting for new business.
There has been a tendency to choose funds selectively for inclusion in the
records, and to pick particular periods, indices or measurers. Fund managers
have developed a kind of Orwellian tendency to rewrite history, notably by
dropping poorly-performing funds from their records, on various pretexts.
Accordingly, a National Association of Pension Funds inquiry in 1990
recommended the establishment of a voluntary code; and the simple outline of
the code has now been published by a working party, which included the
representatives of various industry bodies.
A further working group has been set up to monitor compliance with the code,
and consider how it might be further developed in the future.
Already many investment management houses have
begun issuing figures which they certify to be in accordance with the code.
This means, inter alia, that the standard performance presentation should
cover five calendar years, should include all discretionary balanced funds
under management, and must state the name of the measurer.
At the very least, the industry is therefore now developing a standard
format for performance data. But there remain some grey areas, particularly
in the selection of funds and the definition of 'discretion' as applied to
management mandates.
From next year, however, the performance league tables which have been
appearing in various journals and consulting actuaries' circulars will have
a little more credibility, although gaps may remain. The biggest pension
fund manager, Mercury Asset Management, has refused to publish any aggregate
figures, probably because it fears that clients underperforming the
published house median would complain.
Moreover, the whole idea of developing comparable performance statistics may
be torpedoed by a trend towards the setting of individual performance
benchmarks by pension funds. In time, the idea of discretionary balanced
management may fade away.
Already, WM has divided its Universe into two. In future, the measurers may
need to set up a series of specialist universes (global equities, say, and
international bonds, or UK index trackers). Beyond that, increasing numbers
of funds may give their managers individual briefs in terms of investment
risk and return in relation to specific scheme liabilities.
It could be that the industry league table could will begin to lose its
relevance almost as soon as it has emerged into statistical daylight.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
