<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAC5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Pension Fund Investment (9): Opportunities for
overseas players - Japan's rapidly ageing population will oblige funds to
place greater emphasis on performance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PENSION FUND management in Japan, traditionally the exclusive territory of
Japanese life assurers and trust banks, is changing as the emphasis in fund
management appointments shifts towards performance.
The shift in attitudes is expected to provide opportunities for foreign
companies, which have been unhappy with the limitations due to appointments
ruled by the complex and cosy corporate networks.
The recent appointment of Invesco MIM Asset Management, the Japanese arm of
the UK asset management group, by Nagasakiya, a leading retail company, to
manage a portion of its pension funds, came as a surprise to the industry.
Foreign managers have only managed to win appointments from quasi-government
organisations, and Nagasakiya became the first single private Japanese
company to appoint a foreign-based fund manager. Nagasakiya indicated that
it was dissatisfied with the returns of investments by trust banks, and
allotted Y1bn of its Y23.7bn (Dollars 178m) pension fund to Invesco MIM.
Foreign fund managers and more aggressive Japanese managers believe that the
rapid ageing of the country's population will force company funds and the
Japanese government to put more emphasis on performance. Other leading
Japanese companies have also started to indicate interest in allowing
foreign companies, which have more expertise in fund management.
For those companies wishing to diversify their investments internationally,
foreign fund asset managers are attractive, because foreign asset management
companies are permitted to invest up to 70 per cent of assets overseas,
compared with 50 per cent for domestic asset managers.
The weakness of the Tokyo stock market has made Japanese companies wary of
the deployment of funds. The uncertainty over Japanese share prices has made
overseas investments all the more attractive.
Last year, Japan's 1,400 pension fund schemes had Y38,500bn in assets. This
figure is expected to hit Y161,000bn by the year 2000. Public pension funds
and mutual aid programmes boasted another Y127,000bn.
Foreign companies also hope that the government's own concern about the
financial burden of expected demographic changes in Japan will stimulate
further reforms of pension fund management. About 11 per cent of Japanese
are now aged 65 or over, but the ratio is expected to jump to 16 per cent by
2000.
Given such figures, the momentum for pension management reform is mounting.
Asset management firms were allowed limited access to pension fund
management in 1990. Investment advisers were permitted to manage only new
pension contributions in portfolios with a minimum value of Y1bn and up to
one third of total assets.
The finance ministry responded to US pressure last year by allowing foreign
affiliated asset managers to handle pension funds with as little as Y500m in
assets and to hold up to 70 per cent in foreign investments.
SG Warburg, Jardine Fleming and Fidelity were appointed to handle a fraction
of the Pension Fund Association's own account, and part of the
schoolteachers' fund was handed over to Jardine Fleming and Merrill Lynch.
Foreign trust banks, which have been in the pension fund management business
since 1985, now manage Y59bn, of which Y29bn is handled by Bankers Trust.
Mr Noboru Terada, of the Pension Fund Association, says there is a change in
attitude among Japanese companies towards appointing foreign managers.
However, he points out that companies are still worried about the commitment
the fund management company has made to Japan and the efficiency of
administration and reporting procedures.
Mr Haruaki Deguchi, at Nippon Life, Japan's largest life assurer, says that
pension fund management will shift to be more 'western style' in the future.
'Japan's pension fund system is relatively new compared with that of Europe
and the US. As the pension liabilities of companies start growing, managers
will become more severe about investment returns,' he adds.
Corporate pensions have usually been allotted to trust banks in the same
keiretsu (corporate group), or to life assurers which in return would be
buyers of the company's equity in times of fund raising. Until recently,
trust banks held 65 per cent of the market, while life assurers held 35 per
cent. Winning an appointment would be virtually impossible for a
fund-managing company without such links.
This arrangement has started to become a burden for the life insurers. The
slump in share prices and low dividend payments has made long-term
shareholdings unattractive investments. Mr Deguchi says that if companies
start to base fund management relationships on performance, the nature of
the funds will become more unstable. Selling life assurance policies,
roughly 80 per cent of the total funds in the life assurance industry, will
be the main focus of business, rather than pension fund management.
However, changes in Japan do not happen overnight. Objective performance
analysis of the industry has yet to be established, and performance data is
not available to western consulting firms in Tokyo, including Intersec
Research and Frank Russell.
Once the growth in pension liabilities starts to affect a company's profits,
the improvement of return on assets will become a more pressing matter for
the companies. To wait for this to happen may require patience, because it
could be at least another five to 10 years.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
