<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Pension Fund Investment (10): Protectionism and
suspicion of equities - A genuinely open market for pensions in Europe is
still some way off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CURTAIN on a single European market formally goes up in less than eight
months' time. But so far as pension funds and their managers are concerned,
the long anticipated drama will take rather longer to unfold.
It is not just that the draft EC directive on pension fund freedoms - likely
to be adopted by member states later this year - will not be implemented in
many national legal systems until the mid-1990s. The challenge of securing a
genuinely open market for pensions will only be achieved when cultural
barriers, local protectionism, and continental suspicion of equities as a
suitable investment medium are finally overcome.
Major UK groups, such as Morgan Grenfell Investment Management (part of
Deutsche Bank), Warburg Asset Management and the merchant bank Robert
Fleming, are all chipping away. It seems, however, that some of the UK
investment management industry's earlier expectations of picking up mainland
European business were overdone.
'The European marketing chaps are the ones with the big expense accounts and
glamour lifestyles,' observes an employee in one leading fund management
business, a touch irreverently. 'The amount of money which they have brought
in is pitiful compared with what we can pick up in the UK.'
Signs that the French government, for one, may introduce tax-efficient
money-purchase schemes to take pressure off the state - notwithstanding
recent opposition from unions and others - is one good reason not to lose
heart over Europe. Others are the EC pension fund directive, and pressure
which continues to be exerted on Brussels by multinational companies seeking
a more efficient way of organising their employees' pension arrangements.
Ironically, last October's draft EC pensions directive omitted the freedom
which the likes of IBM would most dearly appreciate, namely cross-border
membership of funds. The Commission insists that it has not abandoned this
principle for the longer term, but acknowledges that the inherent tax
complications could hold up progress on the other morestraightforward
issues.
These are the freedom for pension funds to choose an investment manager
anywhere in the Community, and the removal of national restrictions on where
and how funds should invest their money. Neither of these will fundamentally
alter the UK market per se, but they are highly relevant in countries such
as Belgium and Portugal.
One question constantly raised by the approaching single market and the
reduced currency risk of the exchange rate mechanism is whether the EC
should be seen by pension funds as a single area for investment purposes. At
the end of last year, however, the split of UK to continental European
investments was roughly 6:1, suggesting that old preconceptions die hard.
One measure of the appropriate split, for instance, might be individual
stock market capitalisations, which showed the UK as 42 per cent of total
European stock markets at the end of December 1991. It is not as though
historic performance justifies UK pension funds' bias in favour of their
domestic territory.
Another consideration is whether multinational employers will ultimately
want to take advantage of the possibilities for consolidating the pension
fund assets of their various European subsidiaries. IBM and Digital
Equipment Corporation are among those looking at the options, but Ford Motor
company is among those adopting a more cautious approach. The companies
which are pursuing consolidation plans clearly think that they will be in a
strong position to negotiate a competitive fee structure and reap the
advantages of economies of scale.
Within the EC, there are signs that some pension funds are beginning to look
beyond traditional boundaries for new opportunities - the Dollars 90bn Dutch
civil servants pension fund ABP being one cited by the leading consulting
group Watsons. Wells Fargo Nikko was a beneficiary to the tune of a Dollars
600m account, but generally the sums involved tend to be much smaller as
companies put their toes in the water. Many managers admit that their
continental fees are smaller, not least because of competing local banks'
ability to take advantage of dealing spreads.
The Netherlands is the one market which is recognisable from an Anglo-Saxon
point of view. As Mr Patrick Gifford, a director of Fleming Investment
Management, puts it: 'Everyone in Holland has a funded pension, and the
country is open to non-resident managers.'
At this stage, though, it looks as though Europe's big banks and insurers
are fiercely protecting their patches from the incoming hordes. Another
problem is that the cult of the equity is only slowly catching on, while the
saga of employees dependent for their pensions on companies controlled by
the late Robert Maxwell has hardly advanced the cause. Some have not been
slow to point out that the German system of accounting for pensions on a
company's balance sheet has its advantages after all.
Reaching clients, meanwhile, is not easy, given that the UK's consultant-led
marketing structure is not familiar in continental Europe. Firms such as
Watson and Wyatt have blazed a trail, but they are not retained by companies
in the same way as in the US and the UK.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9546</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFAC3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Pension Fund Investment (7): UK funds hesitate to
leap in the dark - The progress of quantitative management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON'S QUANT scene is hotting up. A number of new quantitative managers,
such as Pareto Partners, Quorum and Barr Rosenberg European Management, have
opened up, joining the slightly longer-established operators like PanAgora
and GMO Woolley. Many of these have American connections.
Domestic leaders include clearing bank subsidiaries like County NatWest
Investment Management and Barclays de Zoete Wedd Investment Management.
These dominate the basic quant product area of index funds. And there are
clear ambitions on the part of several houses to move into higher value
added sectors, involving active, rather than passive, management, for which
much higher fees can be charged. But British pension funds appear to be
rather cautious.
Quant managers seek to exploit electronic technology and statistical
analysis to achieve enhanced investment performance.
Index management is still in a growth phase. Its characteristic is that it
involves large economies of scale so that, untypically of investment
management in general, indexation has become concentrated amongst a few
large players.
The UK market leader is BZWIM, which has been putting on new business at the
rate of Pounds 1bn or more annually for the past few years. It now runs
almost Pounds 10bn in indexed portfolios tracking various equity and bond
indices.
It is estimated that about 15 per cent of the assets of UK pension funds are
now indexed, formally or informally. There is still some way to go to reach
the US indexed proportion of more like 25 per cent; the US penetration has
changed little for five years, suggesting that it represents something of a
natural ceiling, which may also eventually apply in the UK.
Indexation is a cheap, low-risk option for pension fund trustees
disappointed by traditional active managers. This is no strategy for
trustees aiming to top the performance league tables, but it has obvious
appeal for those fed up with featuring in the fourth quartile.
For more ambitious clients, however, the quants have plenty of
second-generation products. Some of these are bottom-up stockpicking
systems, which aim to add several percentage points a year to investment
performance without adding risk. There has also been a lot of emphasis
recently on top-down models to control tactical asset allocation -
basically, bond-equity switching  - and handle currency exposures for global
portfolios.
County NatWest has found UK pension fund clients for its Value-Based
Investment Service, an asset allocation system. But generally its more
advanced and weirdly-named products, like Dynamic Currency Hedging and
Ratcheted Multi-Bond Option (call it Rambo for short), are only selling in
Japan and the US.
Japanese houses have become quite keen on quant. Nikko's London asset
management arm, for instance, has this year launched a so-called Return
Reversal Fund, aimed at exploiting stock rotation effects in the Tokyo
market. But it has not been fortunate with its timing.
Several of the US-owned houses in London are basically selling global
products back into America. Pareto, which has only been running for about a
year, but is backed by Mellon Bank, has already won over Dollars 2bn of
currency overlay business, mainly from US pension funds.
Mr Ronald Liesching, a director of Pareto, suggests that many US
institutions may already have becoming disillusioned with 'black box'
stockpicking products, some of which have had enough time to go wrong for
American clients. 'Those approaches which have been devised to fit history
are shortly doomed to join it,' he says.
In the UK, he adds, quant is only making very slow progress. In fact, there
are signs that continental European clients are more receptive, being ready
to make the quantum leap from low-performing life assurance contracts or
Swiss bank fiduciary accounts to state-of-the-art high technology investment
products. In contrast, British pension funds have generally received
excellent returns from traditional balanced managers in the 1980s, and have
little reason to take a leap in the dark.
Barr Rosenberg is nevertheless trying to sell to UK as well as continental
funds, seeking to exploit the poor relative performance achieved by British
managers in US and Japanese equities.
Ms Jennie Paterson, the firm's marketing director in London, tends to play
down the technological wizardry. She describes Barr Rosenberg's method as
'using an expert computer system to duplicate the thought processes of the
typical investment manager'. British pension funds have been 'very receptive
to the idea' but have yet to sign up.
Certainly, active quant has had an uncertain reception in the UK. There was
the example of Lazard Investors, which imported an American value-based
system in the late 1980s just when growth stocks were beginning to take off
and value stocks wilted. Lazard dumped the system at the end of 1990 in
favour of a traditional style, with which apparently it has enjoyed
considerable success.
Nevertheless, some active quant products have begun to achieve a
breakthrough. Hill Samuel Investment Management, for instance, a few weeks
ago picked up a Pounds 50m account from the Cable and Wireless pension fund.
It will run the UK equity portfolio, using its established quant product
called Active Value Management.
HSIM has now built up a five-year record for AVM, outperforming the
All-Share Index return by some 4 per cent a year on average, albeit with
some significant short-term fluctuations. AVM portfolios now total Pounds
360m.
Mr Alan Greenhorn, HSIM's quant director, says: 'Many quantitative managers
are single-factor strategists. With AVM, we do not expect any one strategy
to be successful for ever.' Various tilts have been used in practice over
the five years, starting with high asset value, then moving to high overseas
earners, with a recent shift from high to medium market capitalisation.
This restless search for new values and insights could be said to be true of
quant management as a whole. And with computer brainpower and memory
capacity becoming ever cheaper, no traditional manager can afford to ignore
the trend.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
