<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Pension Fund Investment (3): Big players sink in
the pool
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of smaller pension schemes which cannot economically justify their
own segregated investment portfolios are clients of the life companies and
other investment houses which provide pooled investment products.
Top performer last year was Lloyds with a rate of return (given full
investment discretion) of over 20 per cent. But curiously the big contenders
in the field - Scottish Widows, Provident Mutual, Confederation Life and
Scottish Amicable - were well below average.
The Caps survey suggests that the median return was 17.4 per cent for 1991
(a little below the median of 18.3 per cent for segregated funds), while the
WF Corroon performance evaluation service reports an average of 16.2 per
cent.
On a long-term view, Confederation Life stays top of the 10-year rankings,
according to Caps, returning 18.4 per cent a year on average.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9553</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFACWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Survey of Pension Fund Investment (1): Consensus at risk -
Investment performance does not currently cause concern, though there are
warning signs in Japan. UK funds must decide how to respond to an increase
in gilt issues, and any stumble in the equity market might lead to a change
in strategy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGERS OF Britain's near-Pounds 300bn pension funds are still obsessed
with the consensus. The handful of top management companies which have
played the game of balanced discretionary management to perfection in the
past few years have wound up with an unprecedented proportion of the
available business. But is the game about to change?
The collapse in the Japanese stock market could be a warning sign. With the
typical fund holding 5 per cent of its assets in the Tokyo market at the end
of last year, the market's tumble has knocked more than a percentage point
off portfolios.
It is not a loss which in itself will greatly concern pension fund trustees.
They have other, bigger, worries on their minds: the implications of the
Maxwell scandal, for instance, which will soon lead to new pensions
legislation; and the growing pressure for pension funds to act as good
corporate citizens, exercising votes and behaving like responsible
proprietors.
Investment performance is not currently a source of concern. Most schemes
have healthy surpluses. The long run of years of strong equity market
performance during the 1980s was resumed last year after a hiccup in 1990.
Professional investors mostly remain highly optimistic: last month,
according to an opinion survey by Godwins, the pensions consultants, 84 per
cent of top fund managers thought that UK equities would be high in a year's
time.
At the end of 1991, the typical British pension fund, according to the Caps
measurement service, had 59 per cent of its assets in UK equities and
another 24 per cent in overseas equities. The 83 per cent commitment to
equities in aggregate is the highest ever in the UK, and is much greater
than for pension funds in other countries: the corresponding figure is some
48 per cent in the US and about 25 per cent (though rising) in the most
comparable European country with large and mature pension funds, the
Netherlands.
At the end of the 1970s, British pension funds were much more diversified
than they are now, with some 25 per cent of their assets in sterling bonds
(almost entirely UK government securities, or gilts) and a significant
direct investment in property, too. The main diversification now is that
overseas equities have replaced gilts, which in their fixed-interest form
account for only 3 per cent of the average fund today.
The justification for this strategic shift is that equities have given
splendid performance and are the natural form of investment for final
salary-linked pension schemes, which are the most common in Britain.
In price terms over the past five years, however, UK equities have performed
only in fits and starts. The average annual rate of return of 11.7 per cent
achieved in UK equities by pension funds has only just exceeded the gilt
return of 11.5 per cent. Overseas equities have lagged badly, returning only
4.4 per cent a year.
A few fund managers are starting to look again at the strategy, but there is
no inclination on their part to begin with a clean sheet. Most managers
regard the performance of the median fund as their benchmark, and indeed
this is often part of their contract with the trustees. A modest, but
increasing, number of schemes have undertaken asset-liability modelling
exercises and have established customised benchmarks. For most external
managers, however, to diverge very far from the consensus asset allocation
would constitute a severe business risk, more important in practice than the
investment risk being borne by the client.
Consider the view of Mr Hugh Jenkins, chief executive of Prudential
Portfolio Managers, with around Pounds 10bn of corporate pension fund assets
under his care. 'We are the people who challenge the consensus,' he claims.
But what he means is that the Pru, like other managers, will diverge only
slightly from the norm; the intention is to add a percentage point or two of
performance without greatly exposing the managers to the risk of serious
divergence from the median.
For example, the Pru recently had something of a bet on UK equities over the
election period, raising its exposure to 63-64 per cent instead of the
standard 59 per cent. This has paid off for the Pru, continuing its good run
which began last year. But it is far from being a radical formula.
One of the few mavericks who rejects the whole approach of trying to be
slightly ahead of everyone else year by year (or even quarter by quarter) is
Mr Bruce Campbell, an Australian who runs a global management boutique in
London called Pyrford International. Much of Pyrford's Pounds 800m-plus
under management comes from overseas, but it recently picked up a Pounds 40m
mandate from Fisons.
At present Pyrford's strategy for UK pension fund clients is to hold only 40
per cent in equities (about half in the UK), with 30 per cent each in bonds
and cash. It has nothing in either the Japanese or US stock markets. It was
the best performing manager of all in 1990, but was a long way down in the
bottom quartile last year, underperforming the Caps median by some 7 per
cent.
Is this a high-risk approach? 'No, it is the other managers' strategy that
carries extremely high risks,' Mr Campbell insists.
It is true, however, that conventional managers have been diversifying
modestly into international bonds, with the average exposure rising from
zero to 6 per cent over the past four years. International bond portfolios,
in fact, outperformed UK equity portfolios last year.
Specialist international bond managers, however, see little interest so far
from UK pension funds. Mr Paul Abberley, fixed income director at Lombard
Odier in London, hopes that opportunities will come for his company now that
the UK is firmly established in the low inflation EMS currency bloc. 'Fixed
income instruments may be more appropriate for UK pension funds than in the
past,' he argues. But he admits that there are few global bond briefs from
UK pension funds. 'It is slow progress at present.'
But UK funds inevitably face a decision about how to respond to the huge
prospective increase in gilt issues as the British government moves into the
forecast budget deficit - of Pounds 28bn this year. As in the 1970s, it
looks as though a substantial proportion of future issues will have to be
taken up by domestic pension funds. So far, though, life insurance companies
and foreign investors appear to be dominating the gilt-edged auctions.
The pension fund strategy consensus survives. So far equities, especially UK
equities, have done what has been required of them. The stock market revival
after the election on April 9 has put a spring back into the step of fund
managers.
But successive collapses on Wall Street and in Tokyo - and the fear that the
US market may again have departed seriously from fair value - must cast
doubt on the wisdom of the current extreme strategy. If the UK equity market
falters, the consensus may encounter a real challenge.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
