<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SERIES of large buying orders early in the session sent stock index
futures sharply forward and led the underlying cash market higher, writes
Joel Kibazo.
Early trading in the June contract on the FT-SE had pointed to a quiet
session as it retreated 9 points with dealers digesting the poor overnight
performance on Wall Street and the weakness in the gilts market on Tuesday.
However, a turnround was staged mid-morning as James Capel, along with
several leading US houses, went on a shopping spree. June moved ahead on the
orders, but it was a large early afternoon order from international futures
trader Cargill, said to have been acting for a US investment fund, that
triggered a further squeeze. A firm Wall Street only served to underline the
positive mood.
June closed at 2,737, up 35 from the previous session and around 24 points
above its estimated fair value premium to cash of about 18. Turnover reached
9,006 lots.
Volume in the traded options market reached 32,794 contracts, of which the
FT-SE 100 option accounted for 8,914 contracts. Amstrad was the busiest
stock option, trading 2,831 lots, with the June 30 calls the most traded
series.
