<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / World Stock Markets: New listing rules to put listing ship
on even keel - The efforts of private managers to give weight to the Jakarta
exchange
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
First impressions of the Jakarta stock exchange do not inspire confidence.
Surly lobby attendants sit on battered chairs, their feet planted on desks,
and a hand-written paper sign is taped to the wall outside the office of
Bursa Efek Jakarta (BEJ), the private managers who took over the running of
the exchange from the government last month.
BEJ's adjoining offices are a building site, indicating that some kind of
transformation is under way. Indeed, the aim of Mr Hasan Zein Mahmud, the
BEJ president, is to inject life and confidence back into the stock market.
Jakarta attracted the attention of international investors in 1990 when the
official index rose 70 per cent in the first three months to peak at 638.8.
It subsequently suffered a severe fall, as a series of accounting scandals
tarnished the market's image, and is now trading just below 290.
Mr Mahmud faces a big challenge in overhauling the stock exchange. The
biggest problem is the lack of liquidity. As one foreign broker comments:
'Try and buy a reasonable stake in some companies and you could double their
share price.'
Domestic investors, such as the state pension funds, have opted to place
money on deposit or invest in property rather than in shares. Deposit rates
have peaked at 20 per cent, pushed up by the government's tight monetary
policy imposed after bank credit grew by more than 50 per cent in 1990. The
central bank has recently eased controls on money supply, but there will be
some delay before commercial bank rates fall.
Lending rates of 26 per cent, coupled with an economic downturn in export
markets, have squeezed company profits and further depressed share values
and trading volume. The value of daily transactions last year averaged
Rp24.9bn (Dollars 12.4m). This increased to Rp29.6bn in January and Rp39.5bn
in February but fell back to Rp25.3bn in March.
BEJ has tightened the listing requirements in an effort to improve investor
confidence and liquidity. From June 18, the qualifications for a listing
are: an operating profit for two consecutive years; minimum assets of
Rp20bn; equity capital of at least Rp7.5bn and paid-up capital of more than
Rp2bn; at least 200 public shareholders; and a free-float of at least 1m
shares.
Companies may be struck off if: they record losses for three consecutive
years; their shares are not traded for more than six months; they cannot
produce scheduled financial reports; or accounting standards are not met.
Brokers had estimated that up to 40 companies of the 141 currently listed
were liable to be struck off. But last week BEJ said the new requirements
would only apply to companies entering the exchange. Brokers now expect
fewer than five companies, which have failed to produce annual reports, to
be delisted.
The tighter listing procedures have been welcomed by brokers, except for the
threat to remove loss-making companies. 'The temptation for loss-makers will
be to falsify accounts, a problem BEJ should be deterring,' explains a local
broker.
Mr Mahmud, however, says the main purpose is to provide an early warning
system to the investor. Furthermore, the removal of loss-making companies
will not be automatic but at BEJ's discretion.
Brokers complain that there are too many of them - 189 domestic brokerages
and 26 joint ventures - for the size of the stock market. Mr Mahmud reckons
75 to 100 firms would be sufficient, but denies that BEJ will limit numbers:
'I do not like the idea of directly intervening in the market.'
BEJ has a paid-up capital of Rp12.3bn, owned equally by 205 stockbroking
firms. The venture will be financed by a 0.1 per cent commission on every
share transaction, and an annual listing fee for listed companies of 0.1 per
cent of the face value of their shares.
Under new rules, local stockbroking firms must have a paid-up capital of
Rp500m, or Rp5bn if they want to act as underwriters. The requirement is
double for joint ventures, in which foreign companies can hold up to 85 per
cent.
BEJ also intends to streamline clearance and settlement, which currently
takes five days or more, but there are no immediate plans to computerise the
exchange.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
