<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: LME plans recycled aluminium
contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LONDON Metal Exchange is to launch a contract in secondary (recycled)
aluminium alloy in early October. The contract - the first totally new
product since the launch of the nickel contract in 1979 - has been the
subject of hot debate in both the industry and the exchange for nearly two
years.
During metals week last October some LME members put the chances of getting
the contract off the ground at only 50-50. But the odds shortened
considerably earlier this year when a special LME committee recommended its
introduction.
In a short statement yesterday the LME said trading in three month secondary
aluminium will begin on October 6, and trading in cash metal on January 4.
The exchange has not confirmed the grades of metal to be traded, but they
are likely to be the Japanese ADC12, the German DIN 226 and the US 380. The
contract is expected to be in US dollars, cover lots of 20 tonnes and be
traded 15 months forward.
Secondary aluminium was an obvious choice for the LME as it searches for
ways to expand its business. Secondary production is a large industry, with
output of about 4.5m tonnes a year, mainly of automotive grade alloy. The
motor industry uses more than 70 per cent of production.
The secondary industry has been growing at 5 per cent a year, compared with
only 1 per cent for the primary industry.
Mr Angus MacMillan, of Billiton-Enthoven Metals, said the contract would be
good for both the LME and the secondary aluminium market. 'It's another
example of how the LME has started to drag itself into the 20th century
since the tin crisis.' Mr Robin Bhar, consultant to Carr Kitcat &amp; Aitken,
also welcomed the contract. Hedging secondary metal against the primary
contract was difficult, he said. In theory the two should move in parallel,
but in practice they do not.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 34
</PAGE>
