<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Coffee and cocoa futures prices
slide to fresh lows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON ROBUSTA coffee and cocoa prices continued their declines to new lows
yesterday, while in New York the July arabica coffee contract had fallen
below 60 cents a lb by midday.
London's July robusta contract plunged nearly Dollars 40 a tonne to a
22-year low of Dollars 678 a tonne before recovering to Dollars 690, down
Dollars 26 on the day. July cocoa closed only Pounds 1 above a new 16 1/2
 year low of Pounds 574 a tonne.
Producers with abundant supplies of both coffee and cocoa have this year
been faced with the stark fact that consumers have high stocks, and see no
need to buy. 'Producers have to sell for what they can get,' said Mr
Lawrence Eagles, analyst with London futures broker GNI.
Stocks of coffee held in importing countries have now reached 90m bags (60
kg each) - probably twice the required level, according to Mr Peter Kettle,
analyst with ED &amp; F. Man, the London trade house.
Mr Eagles also pointed out that the markets had become increasingly
oligopolistic, with few trade houses and few consumers. He cited a recent
Unctad report pointing to 'a shrinking number of participants in many
commodity markets' with increasing power to influence prices through actions
such as holding stocks.
</TEXT>
