<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Spice trade put through the
mill - Problems posed by tighter food safety regulations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INTERNATIONAL spice trade is being ground down at present by a range of
non-tariff barriers imposed by some of the major importers. But producers
are hopeful that they will see a recovery in 1993.
Reports by the International Trade Centre of the United Nations Conference
on Trade and Development and the Commonwealth Secretariat, say that the
increase in the number and type of non-tariff barriers coincided with the
lowering of tariffs under several rounds of the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade negotiations and the introduction of special market access for
some of the least developed countries.
'The most important non-tariff measures imposed by developed countries
usually relate to health and phytosanitary (plant health) regulations,' says
a report from the International Trade Center that was presented to a meeting
in Jamaica of the International Spice Group, made up of producers and
consumers. 'The public concern in these countries about food safety has led
to stricter regulations on food items, including spices.' The report says
that in the US specifications on cleanliness established by the American
Spice Trade Association 'are considered the most stringent among developed
countries'.
The regulations, which differ from country to country 'are so diverse and
standards vary so much that spice exporters in developing countries
frequently experience great difficulty in obtaining up to date,
comprehensive information about them.'
Mr Hernal Hamilton, chairman of the International Spice Group, says that
some spice exporting countries have encountered problems because of the
cleanliness requirements, but many have overcome these by implementing more
rigid inspection systems.
The industry is also worried about the effects on the major markets of the
banning of fumigants, particularly by European consumers, and a reluctance
to accept irradiation to improve cleanliness and remove bacteria.
Successfully meeting the US demands for cleanliness is considered by the
industry to be crucial to hopes for expanded trade, as that country is the
world's largest market. In 1990, US imports, including spice herbs, mustard
and sesame seeds, amounted to 238,949 tonnes, valued at Dollars 355m.
Although the volume imported by the US in 1990 was 12,277 tonnes more than
in 1989, the value was Dollars 19m less.
The volume of spices traded internationally in 1990 reached 400,000 tonnes,
valued at USDollars 1.5bn, according to the International Spice Group. But
producers are unhappy that prices for key products are low, with pepper
fetching about Dollars 1,200 a tonne, a third less than six years ago.
'Sixty per cent of global imports are for the food industry, so any
projections for higher volumes and better prices must be based on the
performance of this industry,' says Mr Fazli Husain, a senior marketing
adviser on spices for of Unctad's International Trade Center.
Consequently, producers are laying great store by the performance of the
food processing industry in the industrialised countries, mainly the US and
Europe.
An improved market will ease the concerns of those producers who have
suffered from recent developments in Europe. Exporters have been affected by
the instability of imports into eastern Europe and the CIS, because of a
lack of foreign exchange to maintain imports.
This has been particularly painful to Jamaica, the leading producer of
pimento (allspice), with exports averaging of 2,500 tonnes a year,
accounting for 70 per cent of world output. The industry earns the island
about Dollars 7m a year.
The Jamaican industry suffered a setback with the loss of an important
market for pimento in what was the Soviet Union. 'The purchasers in what was
the USSR did not buy any pimento last year because of the political
upheaval, but we expect this to be a temporary problem,' says Mr Hamilton,
who is also managing director of the Jamaica Export Trading Company, which
markets the spice.
'They need the pimento for their fish processing industry and we expect this
industry to be in touch with us again soon. We have not lost that market and
I am optimistic that shipments will resume when the political situation
settles down.'
Hopes in the trade for significant increase in the consumption of spices in
non-traditional industries are unlikely to materialise, according to the
International Spice Group.
'The consumption of spices in the non-food sector, in pharmaceuticals and
perfumery, is not in general appreciable, and does not have any significant
effect on overall demand,' it says.
Despite this, consumers and producers are likely to take comfort from
indications that the size of the market could be increased significantly by
two developments that promise an expansion of the trade.
The creation of a single European market at the end of the year will bring
changes in import patterns and could lead to increased demand, the ISG says.
The second development expected to affect that trade is the Uruguay Round
discussions. These will be of benefit, says the International Trade Centre,
'provided the trade liberalisation objectives for tropical products. . . are
attained and maintained'.
In the background, however, lurks a threat from modern technology. The ISG
says that except for vanilla, spices have not so far been threatened by
synthetics and substitutes. It says substitutes for pepper have been
developed, but have not yet made an impression on the market.
'However, the availability of spices in forms other than the 100 per cent
natural spice needs to be monitored. In recent years, spices in other forms,
such as encapsulated spices and spice drops, are entering the market, which
could influence not only the usage pattern, but also affect the actual
amount of spices used, particularly in the industrial sector in the longer
term.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 34
</PAGE>
