<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ZINC prices fell at the London Metal Exchange yesterday, although the
tightening squeeze on supplies available for nearby delivery was reflected
in the further widening of the backwardation (cash premium over forward
metal). The cash price fell Dollars 8.50 to Dollars 1,379 a tonne, but with
the three months position slipping another Dollars 17.50 to Dollars 1,273 a
tonne the backwardation climbed to Dollars 106 a tonne. Traders said that,
while zinc chart indicators were bearish, nervousness about the technical
tightness might discourage fresh sales for the time being. ALUMINIUM staged
an early rise, which traders thought might be linked to May option
declarations, but quickly ran into resistance when the three months price
moved above Dollars 1,321 a tonne. By the close three months metal was
quoted at Dollars 1,317.50 a tonne, up Dollars 5 on the day, and the cash
position was up Dollars 5.50 at Dollars 1,291.50 a tonne. TIN prices also
rose in early trading. Gains were trimmed by profit-taking but three months
metal closed Dollars 37.50 up at Dollars 5,937.50 a tonne and traders said
the near-term target of Dollars 6,000 could reached soon.
Compiled from Reuters
