<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / International Capital Markets: Italy absent from
international market for last 14 months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR A country with a burgeoning public sector borrowing requirement, Italy
has been notable by its absence from the international bond market over the
past year.
The last Eurobond issue by the Republic of Italy was in February 1991, a
Ecu2.5bn 20-year issue lead managed by Paribas Capital Markets.
The deal marked the culmination of an increasingly ambitious borrowing
programme in the Euromarket, which saw Italy's international bond market
borrowings rise from Dollars 1bn - Dollars 2bn a year in the mid-1980s - to
Dollars 5.4bn in just the first two months of last year.
Italy's absence from the international market over the last 14 months is
partly due to a deterioration in it's public finances and credit quality.
Shortly after the Ecu issue last year, Moody's Investors Service, the US
credit rating agency, lowered Italy's top triple-A credit rating.
The deterioration of public sector finances continues to worry credit
analysts. Yesterday, Standard &amp; Poor's, which does not rate with the
co-operation of the authorities, said that the outlook for its AA+ rating of
Italy (the same level as Moody's) was now negative.
The rating agency said 'the continued delay in reducing large fiscal
imbalances and the lack of strong political leadership' meant that Italy's
credit quality was likely to diminish over time.
Analysts estimate that the 1992 deficit is now likely to top L170,000bn,
against a budgeted L128,000bn. Parliamentary elections last month failed to
produce a strong government. President Francesco Cossiga resigned two weeks
later, reducing the likelihood of strong measures to curb government
spending.
The decline of Italy's credit rating has made borrowing in the international
bond market less attractive.
Italy would certainly have to pay a premium over top-rated sovereign
borrowers in the international market. Syndicate officials said yesterday
that a 10-year Eurodollar deal should be priced to yield around 45 basis
points more than US Treasury paper, against a yield spread of perhaps 25
basis points for a borrower such as Austria.
Ironically, Italy's reluctance to tap the international bond market may be a
positive factor, according to the rating agencies. With only Dollars 22bn
foreign currency borrowings, Italy is not reliant on international
investors.
While foreign investors are nervous about the prospects for Italy, the
government has continued to raise funds successfully in the domestic bond
market. Last week, for example, the Italian Treasury successfully auctioned
L18,000bn of fixed and floating rate bonds.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 33
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9567</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEGBFACIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 92 / International Bonds: Enthusiastic response to Compagnie
Bancaire Dollars 400m issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR sector of the international bond market had its first sell-out
for some time yesterday when Compagnie Bancaire came to the international
bond market with its first big dollar issue. 'It was one of the deals of the
year so far,' said a rapturous banker, echoing the sentiment elsewhere.
'People are clamouring for more.'
The reason: the Dollars 400m issue, later raised to Dollars 500m due to
demand, was priced at a seemingly generous level, given the poor state of
the dollar swaps market.
The indicated spread over US Treasuries of the 10-year issue, to be priced
today, was 75-78 basis points, though the final pricing is expected to be at
a 75 basis points spread.
That was seen as a fair spread for the AA-rated borrower. However, were the
proceeds to be swapped into floating rate dollars at that level, the cost to
the borrower would be about 45-50 basis points over the London inter bank
offered rate (Libor) - some 20-25 basis points above the level at which Cie
Bancaire might normally expect to borrow, according to bankers close to the
deal.
The Cie Bancaire transaction, its first attempt to generate a following
among institutional investors in the international bond market, has been
planned for some weeks, perhaps helping to explain its pricing. In spite of
the deterioration of the swaps market, the borrower was keen to push ahead
with the deal, its main aim being to complete its first substantial
transaction successfully. It is not known if the proceeds were swapped,
though bankers close to the deal believed they had not been.
The generous spread against Libor was said in some quarters to have prompted
a degree of asset swapping - that is, banks taking fixed rate paper and
selling on floating rate paper to investors. The co-lead managers to the
deal are thought to have agreed not to engage in asset swapping, but other
banks involved commented that it was impossible to prevent the process if
the attractions were significant, as in this case.
JP Morgan, which led the Cie Bancaire deal, was also credited yesterday with
an Ecu150m issue for Johnson &amp; Johnson which was reported to have sold well.
The five-year issue, yielding 9 per cent, was almost guaranteed to find a
market among retail investors in Europe given the big-name, AAA-rated
borrower, other bankers said.
The yield was nine basis points above the level at which Credit Local's
five-year benchmark Ecu issue was re-opened yesterday by UBS Phillips &amp;
Drew, taking the total size of the issue to Ecu900m.
Meanwhile, the World Bank brought its first dollar floating rate issue
priced against Libor, with a Dollars 250m 10-year issue organised as a block
trade through Salomon.
Banco Comercial Portugues (BCP) has launched an Ecu140m convertible bond
issue, led by UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, Merrill Lynch International and Companhia
de Investimentos e Servicos Financeiros (CISF), the BCP group's investment
and financial services company. The bonds are convertible into BCP shares,
and offer 8.75 per cent interest and a conversion premium of 16 per cent
above BCP shares market price at issue date.
The issue is the first convertible issue launched on the international
market by a Portuguese financial institution. It forms part of a wider
programme aiming to raise Esc50bn (Dollars 357bn) on the international
markets and domestically to build up its international position and
shareholding base.
</TEXT>
